<FIRST>r a AM-ApolloExperiments     07-18 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apollo Experiments,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Experimental Instruments Left on Moon Are Still Working</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A laser reflection experiment that scientists
compared to using a rifle to hit a moving dime two miles away is the
only instrument on the moon from the Apollo program still working,
NASA officials said Tuesday.
   The device, called a laser ranging retro-reflector, is used
regularly to reflect laser beamss aimed at it from Earth, said
officials at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena.
   One was set in the lunar dust in the Sea of Tranquility 20 years
ago by astronauts Neil A. Armstrong and Edwin E. ``Buzz'' Aldrin
Jr., the National Aeronautics and Space Administration said.
   ``One of the reasons why it's still being used is because there's
no energy required on the moon for it to be used,'' said Jean
Dickey, supervisor of the Space Geodetic Science and Applications
Group at the laboratory.
   Similar reflectors were left elsewhere on the moon by Apollo 14
and Apollo 15, and by Lunakhod 2, an unmanned Soviet lander, and all
four still are used by three ground stations on Earth, Dickey said.
   ``It's the only experiment from the Apollo program that is still
working,'' she said.
   A solar-powered instrument package also was left on the moon to
transmit data back to Earth by Apollo 11, and each of the five
successful lunar landings placed nuclear-powered instrument stations
on the moon.
   But all were shut down during the mid-1970s, as budget cuts made
it impossible to continue processing data transmitted from the moon,
said Charles Redmond, a NASA spokesman in Washington.
   The laser ranging retro-reflector is the moving dime in
scientists' rifle-shooting analogy, and was designed to reflect
laser pulses fired from the McDonald Observatory in Fort Davis,
Texas. The idea was to measure the round-trip travel time of a pulse
of light from the Earth to the moon and back.
   The information can be used to calculate distances with
unprecedented accuracy, not only from the Earth to the moon, but
between particular observatories on Earth, Dickey said.
   ``When you think that we can measure the distance from the Earth
to the moon to within three centimeters, about an inch, it's really
pretty incredible,'' Dickey said.
   Among other things, experiments have shown that the moon is
gradually pulling away from the Earth, at about 1{ inches a year.
   Scientists using the lunar reflectors also have measured how the
Earth's continental plates are slowly drifting. They found that the
atmosphere, tides and Earth's core cause variations in the length of
a day, varying by about one-thousandth of a second over a year.
   ``There's been a tremendous growth in our accuracy,'' Dickey
said. Twenty years ago, ``the original ranges were with an accuracy
of meters.''
   Improvements in accuracy were made possible primarily by the
placement of additional reflectors on the moon, and of two
additional observatories, in Hawaii and France, Dickey said.
   The reflectors are too small to be seen from Earth, so even when
the laser is correctly aligned on Earth it is a challenge to
actually hit the lunar target, laboratory officials said.
   The amount of light reflected back to Earth is very small, Dickey
said, and usually is measured in photons, the fundamental unit of
light.
</TEXT>
