<FIRST>r e BC-Ballet     07-18 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ballet,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirov Dances `Bayadere' and `Potemkin'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kirov Ballet combined the beautiful ``La
Bayadere'' third act with a paean to its revolution, ``Battleship
Potemkin,'' at the Metropolitan Opera on Tuesday night.
   Altynai Asylmuratova, 28, the ballerina most admired during the
current Kirov Ballet engagement, danced the leading role opposite
Konstantin Zaklinsky, who is her husband, in ``La Bayadere.''
   There is a story to this Marius Petipa ballet, but seeing the
third act alone, one doesn't need to know it and dancers don't need
to act characters. The corps de ballet enters, one at a time, and
this corps de ballet is unsurpassed for timing and sweetness. Miss
Asylmuratova didn't surpass memories of Dame Margot Fonteyn dancing
the same thing, but she, too, made this section of ``La Bayadere''
magical.
   Three ballerinas, Irina Chistyakova, Yelena Pankova and Zhanna
Ayupova, who danced variations, all were wonderful.
   ``Battleship Potemkin'' was choreographed some four years ago by
the company's artistic director, Oleg Vinogradov, to a score
composed for it by Aleksandr Tchaikovsky. Americans would consider
``Potemkin'' a novelty but it's obvious from its hour-plus length
and many elaborate backdrops that it's intended to be more than
that. Americans probably also wouldn't want to see ``Potemkin'' more
than once. Some of it is decidedly odd.
   The choreographic technique is to use modern dance, not following
the rules of ballet but making the turns and steps extremely
balletic, especially for solos by Vladimir Bondarenko and Andrei
Garbuz as sailors. Ship's officers kick a sailor to death, then
another. Death (Gennadi Babanin) has a long, athletic duet with each.
   The ship's commander (Yuri Gumba) hops with both feet together
and has other steps which portray him as a childish madman. The Tzar
and Tzarina come on board, moving stiffly like puppets. She dances
as though imitating the can can. The choreography makes the
oppressors look silly but it isn't very interesting as dance.
   Finally the sailors band together, face officers with guns who
run away, kick the commander, toss their shirts in the air, cavort
with joy and run down an aisle.
   The artistic image to hold from this program is ``La Bayadere.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
