<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     07-18 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Batman' Sets Warner Bros. Record, `Lethal Weapon 2' Claims No. 1
Spot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Batman'' has passed such stellar hits as ``The
Exorcist,'' ``Gremlins'' and the original ``Superman'' to become the
highest-grossing film in Warner Bros. history.
   Although it finished second on the weekend box-office charts,
with receipts of $15.1 million, ``Batman'' has collected $167.6
million to date, and will almost certainly become this summer's
biggest hit, surpassing ``Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade.''
   Meanwhile, ``Lethal Weapon 2'' claimed the No. 1 spot for the
second consecutive week, leaving the new James Bond film ``Licence
to Kill'' reeling in its wake.
   ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' starring Mel Gibson and Danny Glover as Los
Angeles policemen out to smash a South African money laundering
scheme, grossed $17.2 million nationwide to lead all other titles,
according to figures released Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co.
   In third place over the weekend was the Disney comedy ``Honey, I
Shrunk the Kids,'' which continues to attract waves of moviegoers.
``Honey,'' starring Rick Moranis, sold $8.806 million worth of
tickets, topping the opening of ``Licence to Kill.''
   The latest Bond film, starring Timothy Dalton, debuted weakly,
grossing $8.775 million to finish in fourth place. The last Bond
film, ``The Living Daylights,'' netted more than $11 million in its
opening weekend in 1987.
   In fifth was Disney's re-release of the animated ``Peter Pan,''
with sales of $5.6 million. It was followed in sixth by Steven
Spielberg's ``Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade,'' with a gate of
$4.6 million.
   The comedy sequel ``Ghostbusters II,'' starring Bill Murray and
Dan Aykroyd, was seventh on proceeds of $4.33 million. In eighth was
Robin Williams in ``Dead Poets Society,'' which grossed $4.26
million.
   Rounding out the Top 10 were ``Weekend at Bernie's,'' with $3.7
million, place, and ``Do the Right Thing,'' with $3 million. The new
romantic comedy ``When Harry Met Sally...'' had a strong opening in
a limited release, selling $1.1 million worth of tickets in only 41
theaters.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' Warner Bros., $17.2 million, 1,830
screens, $9,392 per screen, $49.2 million, two weeks.
   2. ``Batman,'' Warner Bros., $15.1 million, 2,201 screens, $6,867
per screen, $167.6 million, four weeks.
   3. ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids,'' Disney, $8.806 million, 1,460
screens, $6,031 per screen, $74.8 million, four weeks.
   4. ``Licence to Kill,'' MGM-UA, $8.775 million, 1,575 screens,
$5,571 per screen, $8.775 million, one week.
   5. ``Peter Pan,'' Disney, $5.6 million, 1,475 screens, $3,805 per
screen, $5.6 million, one week.
   6. ``Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade,'' Paramount, $4.6
million, 1,717 screens, $2,687 per screen, $166 million, eight weeks.
   7. ``Ghostbusters II,'' Columbia, $4.33 million, 1,978 screens,
$2,192 per screen, $93.2 million, five weeks.
   8. ``Dead Poets Society,'' Disney, $4.26 million, 1,047 screens,
$4,068 per screen, $63.9 million, seven weeks.
   9. ``Weekend at Bernie's,'' 20th Century Fox, $3.7 million, 1,139
screens, $3,292 per screen, $12.9 million, two weeks.
   10. ``Do the Right Thing,'' Universal, $3 million, 498 screens,
$6,060 per screen, $13.4 million, three weeks.
</TEXT>
