<DOCNO> AP890718-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-OklahomaTaxes     07-18 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oklahoma Taxes,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Governor Proposes Eliminating Property Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Henry Bellmon unveiled a plan Monday to
do away with property taxes and substitute a system of income tax
surcharges and new levies on most goods and services.
   The governor said the plan, designed to increase financing for
public schools, could generate $245 million in new revenue beginning
in 1991, amounting to about 8 percent of the state budget.
   ``Teachers would get most of this new money,'' Bellmon said,
noting it could mean average raises of up to $6,000 per teacher.
   The Republican governor met privately with legislative leaders to
discuss the plan, which Bellmon said he wants the Legislature to
pass in a special session he has called to begin Aug. 14.
   Teachers' union officials praised the plan, but some legislators
expressed reservations about the possibility of passing the
``Funding Equity and Equal Educational Opportunity Act'' in the
special session.
   Bellmon said the plan addresses public school funding and teacher
pay, areas in which Oklahoma has lagged far behind the national
average.
   ``We believe that once the plan is understood, there will be
widespread support,'' Bellmon said. ``Once the plan is fully
implemented, Oklahoma will be among the leaders in educational
excellence.''
   The state ranks 48th nationally in teacher salaries, with an
average of approximately $$22,000 a year, according to the Oklahoma
Education Association.
   The tax program overhauls the method of financing schools and
county government by replacing the local property tax with a 15
percent income tax surcharge and a new 2 percent ``school tax'' on
goods and services.
   The 2 percent ``school tax'' would be levied on value received
from the sale or lease of finished goods and services. It would be
in addition to the current 4 percent state sales tax.
   Groceries, on which the sales tax is now levied, and prescription
drugs would be exempted. The sales tax exemption would be removed
from the value of professional services such as those provided by
doctors, dentists, attorneys, accountants, plumbers, barbers,
beauticians and mechanics.
   The income tax surcharge would be assessed as a percentage of
personal and corporate income taxes paid. That money would be used
to fund county government that now depends on property taxes.
   The plan abolishes property taxes on homes, farms and other
personal property. A property tax would remain for commercial
property valued at more than $100,000 and on utility company
property.
   Local property taxes now produce more than $800 million for
schools and county government.
   Bellmon said his proposal is designed to solve ``a whole series
of problems related to education.''
   Kyle Dahlem, president of the Oklahoma Education Association, was
smiling broadly after Bellmon unveiled the plan.
   ``I am optimistic,'' Ms. Dahlem said. ``I must be optimistic. We
cannot afford to go another year or two or three without a
long-range plan.''
   Some legislators expressed caution.
   ``It's quite the most comprehensive change I've been associated
with since I've been in the Legislature,'' said Democratic Sen. Bob
Cullison, president pro tempore of the Senate. ``Maybe this plan has
merit. I hope it does.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
