<FIRST>r a AM-LoiteringLaw     07-18 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Loitering Law,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Anti-Loitering Law Targeting Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Courtroom spectators cheered Monday as a
judge upheld an anti-loitering ordinance designed to rid streets of
drug dealers.
   The 4-month-old city ordinance was challenged by attorneys for
four men arrested under the law and by the southwest Michigan
chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union. They argued that the
law violated the constitutional right of freedom of association.
   District Judge Quinn Benson ruled the city had a ``compelling
interest to stem the flow of drugs'' which outweighed any potential
infringement on the right of people to associate with drug dealers.
   City Attorney Robert Cinabro and lawyers representing four
neighborhood groups argued that without the ordinance, the rights of
residents to lead peaceful, safe lives would be violated.
   ACLU attorney Robert Travis argued that if the ordinance was not
overturned, then it should be amended to allow the arrest only of a
person having intent to use or sell drugs.
   The ACLU said it had not decided whether to appeal Benson's
ruling.
   Under the law, those who knowingly loiter in places where drugs
are used or sold may be arrested.
   Benson's ruling was cheered by Mattie Jordan, executive director
of the Northside Association for Community Development. ``This is
going to clean our streets up,'' she said. ``At least the police are
left a tool to fight the war.''
   City police have made 33 arrests since May, said Capt. Scott
Dolfman of the department's Special Investigations Unit.
   ``We've allowed citizens of the area freedom of movement in their
neighborhoods again,'' Dolfman said.
   Although other cities around the country have similar laws, the
only similar ordinance in Michigan is in Detroit.
</TEXT>
