<DOCNO> AP890718-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-18 0887</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodity Credit Farm Investments Remain Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The taxpayer's investment in surplus farm
commodities continues to show a sharp decline from last year's
levels, largely as a result of drought-reduced crop production in
1988 and rising market prices.
   An Agriculture Department report released Monday showed the
Commodity Credit Corp. had $13.5 billion invested in price support
loans and actual inventories as of May 31. That included $9.1
billion in loans outstanding, and $4.4 billion in government-owned
commodities, said the report by Keith Bjerke, the CCC's executive
vice president.
   A year earlier, on May 31, 1988, the CCC had an investment of
$23.1 billion, including $14.3 billion in loans outstanding and $8.8
billion in inventories.
   The CCC finances various price support operations of the
department, including those for wheat, feed grains, rice, tobacco,
cotton, soybeans, dairy products, honey and sugar.
   In the case of the major grain crops, the 1988 drought reduced
production and pushed up prices. That reduced the need for price
support loans and forfeitures, which means the CCC takes over
ownership of crops when farmers opt not to repay the loans.
   When market prices are high enough, it's usual for farmers to pay
off the loans and use or sell as they choose.
   The farmer-owned grain reserve, which enables wheat and feed
grains to be stored and kept off the market under government loan
until prices rise enough to trigger their release, consisted of 287
million bushels of wheat valued at more than $1 billion as of May
31, the report said.
   Corn and other feed grains in the reserve totaled more than 1.03
billion bushels valued at $2.57 billion.
   The total value of commodities acquired by CCC in the first eight
months of the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1 was $1.72 billion,
the report said. In the same period of 1987-88, CCC acquired
products valued at $9.62 billion.
   Net losses to CCC totaled about $3.52 billion through May 31, the
report said, compared with a loss of more than $10 billion in the
same eight months of 1987-88. The decline was mainly due to the
smaller volume of grain moving into CCC inventories, and reduced
payments to farmers.
   Dairy inventories held by CCC also continued to edge down from
the high levels of a few years ago.
   As of May 31, for example, total holding were reported at 567.6
million pounds of products valued at $759.4 million, compared with
715.9 million pounds with a CCC investment of $820.1 million.
   Inventories of dried milk and cheese were down sharply, but the
butter stockpile was up from a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department scientists are working
on an edible, nearly invisible coating made from milk that could
extend the shelf life of fruit and vegetables.
   Attila E. Pavlath, a chemist with the department's Agricultural
Research Service, said tests are concentrating on a film based on
casein, a milk protein. A small amount of vitamin C is added to help
protect against browning.
   Pavlath, who works at the agency's research laboratory in Albany,
Calif., said in a report released here on Monday that small pieces
of sliced and peeled apple dipped in the coating stayed fresh for
several days. Unprotected pieces shriveled and turned brown within a
few hours.
   The scientists want to make the film thinner, a process that
might take two more years, Pavlath said.
   Films that ``the tongue cannot feel and the taste buds cannot
detect'' also could be made from protein in soybeans, corn and
wheat, the report said.
   ``Some people who like fresh produce don't necessarily want to
spend time in their kitchen washing, slicing, peeling, pitting and
paring,'' Pavlath said. ``It's part of the trend toward buying food
that is ready to use and easy to store.''
   A successful coating would allow more types of produce to be
pre-sliced and packaged. Such coatings may have other potential
uses, perhaps for keeping fillings in pizzas or preventing pies from
soaking the crust.
   Unlike waxes on cucumbers or other edible coatings such as the
``skin'' on sausages, new films could be modified to add flavors or
colors to standard fare, Pavlath said.
   One possibility, he said, would be fresh sliced pears protected
with a somewhat thicker protein coating flavored with red cherries.
   John M. Krochta, a former chemical engineer at the Albany
laboratory who is now at the University of California, Davis, said
an ideal edible coating should keep out microbes that promote
softening, browning, mold and other types of decay.
   The coating should also trap vital moisture in produce to keep it
fresh, yet enable it to ``breathe'' by taking in oxygen and giving
off carbon dioxide, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John A. Stevenson, the Ohio state executive
director of the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service,
has been named as the No. 2 official in the Agriculture Department
agency.
   Undersecretary Richard Crowder said that Stevenson ``brings with
him first-hand experience and knowledge of our complex farm
programs.'' The position of associate administrator, as it is known,
pays $71,800 a year.
   Stevenson, who lives in Circleville, has been Ohio state
executive director for four years. He has been farming since 1958
and has an 800-acre operation in partnership with his daughter in
Pickaway County.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
