<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryBills     07-18 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities are at their highest level in more than two weeks.
   The Treasury Department on Monday sold $6.6 billion in
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.87 percent, up
from 7.76 percent last week. Another $6.6 billion was sold in
six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.67 percent, up from
7.50 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 7.96
percent on July 3 and six-month bills averaged 7.78 percent on June
26.
   The discount rates understate the actual return to investors _
8.14 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9.801.10 and 8.09 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,612.20.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.85
percent last week, down from 7.97 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
