<FIRST>b w AM-HamblenExecution-SCOTUS     07-18 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamblen Execution-SCOTUS,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Blocks Florida Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court granted a stay of execution
early Tuesday for convicted killer James William Hamblen, hours
before he was scheduled to be executed in Florida's electric chair.
   The stay was granted to permit the justices to review an appeal
by Hamblen's lawyers, said Toni House, a spokeswoman for the high
court.
   Since the court is out of session and won't be back until
October, Hamblen's appeal cannot be heard until then, she noted.
   The stay of execution was granted without comment, she said.
   Hamblen had been scheduled to be executed at 7:01 a.m. EDT for
the April 24, 1984 robbery-murder of Laureen Jean Edwards, owner of
the Sensual Woman lingerie shop in Jacksonville.
   Hamblen, during his trial in 1984, fired his court-appointed
attorneys and pleaded guilty, agreeing he deserved the death
penalty. He also admitted killing his ex-girlfriend, Debbie Abbot in
Spring, Texas, earlier the same year.
