<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     07-18 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Fire On Student Demonstration, Eight Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers opened fire to break up
a small demonstration at the University of El Salvador, and eight
people were reported injured, including an American who broke his
leg while fleeing.
   Students said the soldiers fired to prevent the roughly 30
demonstrators from leaving the campus Monday night. But a military
officer said the troops were returning shots fired from inside the
school.
   No soldiers were reported hurt.
   The protest was called to demand that soldiers free Rene Cruz, an
economics student and leader of the General Association of
Salvadoran University Students. Students say soldiers arrested him
Sunday, but the army denied it.
   The military said in a statement on the demonstration that the
students committed ``acts of provocation against the troops that
guard and provide security to the University of El Salvador.''
   During the protest, police defused a car bomb 500 yards from the
1st Infantry Brigade headquarters, near the school, the statement
said. It did not say whether the military believed the protest and
the bomb were related.
   Several students, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
soldiers fired to keep the demonstrators from leaving the campus.
   But Col. Francisco Elena Fuentes, commander of the 1st Infantry
Brigade, said in a telephone interview that Soviet-made AK-47 rifles
were fired from inside the school and that firebombs were thrown.
   In television film of the disturbance, shots appeared to be
coming from one of the campus buildings.
   Ambulances were not allowed onto the campus until the shooting
stopped, two hours after the disturbance began, said a Red Cross
worker who requested anonymity. He said eight people were taken to
hospitals, including a man who identified himself as Robert Drennon,
33, of New York City.
   Drennon, who said he has been studying Spanish on a student
exchange program, told reporters: ``When I heard the shots I ran and
I broke my leg.''
   The Red Cross did not describe the injuries suffered by the other
seven protesters who were taken to the hospital.
   The rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, fighting for
nine years to overthrow the U.S.-backed government, said in a call
to a local radio station that its urban units were not involved in
the the university incident.
</TEXT>
