<HEAD>KAL Jury Picked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-member jury has been selected to decide a
suit which accuses Korean Air Lines of willful misconduct when one
of its passenger jets was shot down by Soviet planes in 1983,
killing all 269 people aboard.
   Families of 132 of the passengers killed when Flight 007 was
destroyed are suing KAL. They claim the plane's crew, due to a
navigational mistake deliberately left uncorrected, let the plane go
hundreds of miles off course over a period of several hours into
Soviet air space.
   After the six jurors and three alternates were chosen and sent
home for the day Monday, KAL lawyers asked U.S. District Judge
Aubrey Robinson to limit presentation of the conclusions of a report
on the shootdown by the International Civil Aviation Organization.
   The ICAO said Flight 007 had been off course for nearly 5{ hours
before it was destroyed.
