<HEAD>Bush Urged to Veto Aid Restriction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush should veto legislation that
would block him using money from other countries for activities that
the U.S. Congress refuses to bankroll, according to Sen. Jesse Helms.
   ``This doesn't even make good nonsense because Congress doesn't
have the authority to do that,'' Helms, R-N.C., said Monday as
debate opened on an amendment offered by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., to a State Department authorization bill.
   Moynihan's proposal arises from the Iran-Contra investigation,
when it was revealed that the Reagan administration solicited funds
from foreign nations to aid the Contra rebels in Nicaragua at a time
when Congress had barred using U.S. funds to provide such aid.
   During the hearings the countries were referred to by code names
such as ``Country One'' and ``Country Two'' and the like. But it was
clear that nations like Saudi Arabia and Brunei had contributed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
