<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-ChunAide     07-18 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Chun Aide,0255</SECOND>
<UNK>Former Aide To President Chun Sentenced to 10 Months in Prison</UNK>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former director of the nation's
intelligence agency was convicted today and sentenced to 10 months
in prison for abusing power during the rule of disgraced former
President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Chang Se-dong, 52, was convicted by a three-judge panel of
building an opulent private residence for Chun with public funds
while serving as Chun's chief bodyguard from 1981 to 1984, a
politically powerful position.
   Chang headed the Agency for National Secuity Planning, the
country's intelligence agency, from 1985 until 1987, Chun's last
year in office.
   The residence was allegedly for use by Chun after retirement and
has been returned to the government for use by a foundation.
   In handing down the sentence in Seoul District Criminal Court,
Presiding Judge Hong Suk-chae said Chang had acted out of excessive
loyalty to Chun rather than being faithful to his job as chief
presidential bodyguard.
   Chang had maintained he was doing his job.
   The prosecution, which had demanded four years imprisonment, said
it would appeal the sentence. Defense lawyers also indicated they
would appeal.
   Chang was among dozens of Chun's former aides, relatives and
others who have been arrested on charges of influence peddling,
corruption and violations of human rights during the former
president's authoritarian seven-year rule.
   Chun, accused of misrule and human rights violations, apologized
to the nation in November and has been living in rural exile at a
Buddhist temple.
</TEXT>
