<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-18 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell sharply.
   The dollar ended trading at 142.35 yen, up 0.82 yen from Monday's
141.53-yen close. The index started at 141.55 yen and moved between
141.43 yen and 142.50 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues shed 112.49
points, or 0.34 percent, closing at 33,343.73. The index has lost
more than 400 points since last Wednesday.
   The index fell as market players remained on the sidelines ahead
of the major national election for the upper house of Japan's
parliament Sunday, dealers said.
   Nomura Securities analyst Yoshiro Inoue said the number of issues
sold markedly outnumbered those purchased ``mainly because of
concerns over the elections, and the yen's losses against the
dollar.''
   A series of recent polls have predicted that the governing
Liberal Democratic Party will lose badly in the upcoming election.
Although senior party leaders say they will win at least 54 seats of
the 126 to be decided Sunday, analysts see that as a tough goal.
   The governing party has lost its popularity due to an
influence-peddling stock scandal, an unpopular sales tax and reports
about Prime Minister Sousuke Uno's affairs with women.
   In currency dealings, yen-selling pressure remained strong since
the dollar's higher opening Tuesday, but many market participants
were also reluctant to make major moves before the U.S. trade report
for June, traders said.
   The U.S. trade figure, which the U.S. Commerce Department is to
release later Tuesday in Washington, is considered an important
indicator of the health of the U.S. economy.
</TEXT>
