<DOCNO> AP890718-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PriestsCrusade Bjt   07-18 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Priests Crusade, Bjt,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priests Crusade Against Drug Paraphernalia Sold Next to Bread, Candy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Death threats to a pair of Roman Catholic priests
are a daily ritual now. They say it is proof that their crusade
against the sale of drug paraphernalia is paying off.
   At hundreds of stores throughout the city, an elementary school
pupil looking for candy can find himself shopping side-by-side with
an addict buying a new crack pipe, the priests say.
   ``You go in a store and what you see right off is bread, candy
and drug paraphernalia,'' said the Rev. Michael Pfleger. ``This is
teaching children that drugs are an ordinary part of life.''
   And death.
   ``Drugs are the No. 1 killer I've had to deal with,'' said
Pfleger, a white priest who for nearly 15 years has ministered to
the all-black congregation at St. Sabina's.
   Between them, Pfleger and the Rev. George Clements, whose
parishes are in the city's South Side, have attended hundreds of
funerals for junkies, drug pushers and bystanders killed in drug
warfare.
   ``In my neighborhood, it's an epidemic, a raging epidemic,'' said
Clements. ``Virtually no family has been left untouched.''
   Finally, it became too much for the priests, both of whom have
the added worry of their own adopted sons being exposed to and
possibly lured into drugs.
   ``Our effort is really to heighten the contradiction in a society
which says that it's legitimate to buy drug paraphernalia, but
illegal to take drugs,'' said Clements. ``That's the height of
hypocrisy.''
   That may stop soon.
   A bill outlawing the sale of drug paraphernalia was recently
passed by the state General Assembly. Gov. James R. Thompson is
expected to sign it.
   The priests say they've been meeting with local congressmen as a
first step toward a national ban.
   Their efforts have brought confrontations with store owners and
misdemeanor arrests for refusing to leave shops in Chicago and, in
Clements' case, in Shreveport, La.
   Each Saturday, Pfleger and 100 or so parishioners fan out to the
neighborhood liquor stores, groceries and video shops that openly
sell the drug gear. From Clements' Holy Angels Church, the priest
and parishioners make daily forays.
   Some of the stores have scales for weighing cocaine and
substances for diluting the drug. Most have the user's tools, such
as pipes, glass vials and capsules.
   In the last two months, about 400 stores have taken the
paraphernalia off shelves, the priests say. Those that don't readily
agree get repeated visits and threats of boycotts.
   Some doubt the usefulness of the priests' work.
   ``We pulled it off the shelf, no problem,'' said Ali Saleh, who
agreed to remove the paraphernalia from shelves at the F&amp;G Liquor
and Food Mart he manages. ``But there has to be a law against it or
people can just go down a block or two and they'll be selling the
same thing there.''
   As the priests' efforts have progressed, so have the threats.
   Not a night goes by without a half dozen telephoned threats,
usually between 2 a.m. and 6 a.m., said Pfleger.
   Written death threats have been flung through church windows with
rocks.
   Clements, who is one of the nation's best-known black Catholic
priests and who officiated at last year's wedding of heavyweight
boxing champion Mike Tyson and actress Robin Givens, said someone
recently smashed his car window and tore out the radio and air
conditioning.
   A note read, ``The first of many. From your friendly drug
dealer.''
   ``Obviously, we're having an effect,'' Pfleger said.
   The priests now plan to take their fight against drugs further _
to the doorsteps of pushers.
   ``We want people to tell us where drugs are being sold,'' he
said. ``And when we find out, we'll put a sign up saying a drug
dealer lives here and the neighbors want him to leave the
neighborhood.''
   Pfleger acknowledged it could be dangerous.
   ``But fear is not going to do anything to stop us,'' he said.
``The only thing we're afraid of is not doing anything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-GanderCrash     07-18 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gander Crash,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review Accepts Report Blaming Gander Crash on Icy Wings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judicial review has accepted an investigation
that found that icy wings, rather than a bomb, caused a 1985 plane
crash that killed 256 U.S. servicemen and crew in Gander,
Newfoundland, a newspaper said today.
   The review found no need to reopen the case, the paper said.
   The Canadian Aviation Safety Board probe was controversial
because five board members said icy wings caused the crash, while
the other four theorized that a bomb was to blame.
   Some board members also charged that evidence pointing to a
terrorist attack was withheld.
   Sources at the safety board and Department of Transport said the
review, ordered in March by Transport Minister Benoit Bouchard,
generally exonerates the board's staff investigators, the Toronto
Globe and Mail said.
   The newspaper said in today's editions that the review, written
by Justice Willard Estey, a former Supreme Court of Canada judge,
will be released Friday.
   The five-member majority on the investigatory board found that a
thin layer of ice reduced the lifting capacity of the wings of the
Arrow Air jet, causing the chartered aircraft to crash on takeoff on
Dec. 12, 1985.
   The paper quoted sources as saying the review gives no credence
to the bomb theory or to claims that evidence was withheld.
   The dissenters suggested a coverup by Canadian and U.S. agencies
sought to hide what they argued was a terrorist attack on the aging
DC-8 that was taking U.S. troops home for Christmas after a
peacekeeping tour in the Middle East.
   No evidence of a bomb has ever been presented, although the
dissenters say its absence demonstrates the wide-ranging nature of
the coverup.
   Safety board Chairman Ken Thorneycraft refused Monday to discuss
Estey's review. He said he was unaware of its findings, but added
that he had always been confident that any independent assessment of
the agency's investigation would conclude it was conducted
thoroughly and reached reasonable conclusions.
   Critics of the icing finding, including the U.S. Airline Pilots
Association, have accused the board of fabricating evidence in a bid
to blame the plane's pilots. Both pilots, six other crew members and
all 248 U.S. servicemen on board died in the crash _ the worst ever
in Canada.
   The Globe and Mail also said Les Filotas, one of the board's
dissenters, sent a letter to Estey saying Arro Air may have been
involved in ``arms-for-hostages exchanges conducted secretly on
behalf of highly placed individuals in the American administration
(and that) if so, there would have been strong motivation for
attempts to confound aspects of the investigation.''
   The letter, obtained through the Access to Information Act,
suggests the unsubstantiated link could also have been a motive for
targeting Air Arrow for a terrorist attack, the newspaper said.
   It said Estey returned the letter, dated April 2, unread to
Filotas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
