<HEAD>Pilot Dismissed by Arizona Co.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Sonrise is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUN CITY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot who survived an unconscious
800-mile flight and crash has been dismissed by an Arizona
corporation that he represented as a lawyer, a spokeswoman for the
company said.
   Thomas Root's Sonrise Management Services Co. had been
representing Sun Health Corp. in its effort to obtain a license from
the Federal Communications Commission to operate a FM radio station,
said Madeline Lutz, the corporation's education director.
   Sun Health, which owns and operates hospitals in Sun City and Sun
City West, dismissed the Washington attorney after his plane
splashed down Thursday into the ocean off the Bahamas, Ms. Lutz said
Monday.
   ``We were advised to hire him and he performed all of his
functions as our attorney well. But we felt that because of his
injury he might not be available to fully represent us,'' she said.
   The 36-year-old lawyer from Alexandria, Va., remained in a
Florida hospital in stable condition Monday; a hospital spokeswoman
predicted he would be there for another week.
   He planned to fly his small plane from Washington to Rocky Mount,
N.C., but told air traffic controllers he was having trouble
breathing, and apparently passed out until his plane ran out of fuel
and plunged into the sea near the Bahamas.
