<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0504EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ApolloAnniversary     07-18 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apollo Anniversary,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>First American in Space Opposes Joint Soviet Missions; Rocket Scientists
Meet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto HON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's first astronaut in the 1960s
space race with the Soviet Union opposes joint missions today, but
not for political reasons.
   ``I think it would be a step backwards to go that route,'' Alan
Shepard said Monday during a visit to the Space and Rocket Center
for Space Celebration '89 festivities. ``I would rather see us
develop the technology to have planetary travel _ manned and
unmanned.''
   A separate celebration of the 20th anniversary of the 1969 moon
walk, meanwhile, included some bitterness.
   About 40 aging German rocket scientists who helped build
America's space program expressed disappointment that one of their
brethren was not present for a reunion of the 20th anniversary
celebration of Americans landing on the moon.
   Arthur Rudolph, project manager for the Saturn 5 rocket at the
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, remained in voluntary
exile in his native West Germany, under threat of prosecution for
alleged Nazi war crimes if he returned to the United States.
   ``It's a shame for the United States to send out a man who did so
much for the United States,'' said scientist Konrad Dannenberg.
``Everyone here should be ashamed this thing happened.''
   Rudolph, now 84, retired in January 1970 after helping send two
spaceships to the moon and moved to San Jose, Calif., where he lived
in relative obscurity for 14 years.
   His tranquil retirement ended when the Justice Department's
Office of Special Investigations raised allegations that during
World War II he was involved in the deaths of thousands of
concentration camp prisoners who were forced to work in a V-2 rocket
factory where he was technical director. Those allegations were
backed up by some survivors.
   Rudolph left the country and returned to Hamburg, West Germany,
where a two-year investigation found no offense against Rudolph. His
West German citizenship was returned.
   Shepard, one of 12 Americans to walk on the moon, disagreed with
Apollo 11 moonwalker Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin, who said during a trip
to Huntsville Saturday that America should pursue joint missions
with the Soviet Union and possibly Japan.
   ``I think our space technology level, in general, is ahead of the
Soviets,'' Shepard said.
   Shepard, now 65, rode a Huntsville-built Redstone rocket into
space on May 5, 1961, as the American space program rushed to catch
the Soviets, who had sent Yuri Gagarin into space on April 12.
   He returned to space in February 1971 on Apollo 14 and became the
fifth man to walk on the moon _ a feat never matched by the Soviet
Union. Shepard is now is a commercial real estate developer in
Houston.
   Meanwhile, children who weren't alive when man first landed on
the moon got a chance to guide another ``spacecraft'' to a lunar
landing Monday.
   Fifteen students worked at the Challenger Center's mock Mission
Control in Houston, while another group of children were ``flying''
in a simulator at a second Challenger Center in Greenbelt, Md. They
were helped by flight controllers who were in NASA's Mission Control
during Apollo 11's historic landing.
   The youths talked through headsets and completed checklists
before giving the go-ahead for the mock landing.
   The centers, built as a memorial to the seven astronauts who died
in the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger, offer youngsters a
chance to learn by participating in simulated missions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0047 </DOCNO>
