<SECOND>PM-Marcos Suit,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allows Philippine Attorneys to Question Imelda Marcos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge will allow Philippine government
lawyers to question Imelda Marcos in connection with a $50 billion
civil racketeering lawsuit that also names her husband, former
Philippine leader Ferdinand Marcos.
   U.S. District Judge Mariana Pfaelzer on Monday lifted a
two-year-old stay to allow lawyers to take a deposition from Mrs.
Marcos, although attorneys from both sides concede they are unlikely
to get many answers.
   The couple's attorney, John J. Bartko, said he would advise Mrs.
Marcos to invoke her right against self-incrimination. No date has
been set for the deposition.
   Marcos, who is gravely ill in a Honolulu hospital, is unable to
communicate with his attorneys or otherwise take part in the
proceedings, Bartko said.
   Attorneys representing the Philippines also amended their
complaint on Monday, adding charges that the Marcoses embezzled
money and property from the Philippine government and got kickbacks
from both foreign and domestic companies doing business in that
nation.
   Mrs. Marcos and her husband are accused of running their nation
as a personal enterprise, looting the country of billions of dollars.
   The couple left the Philippines in February 1986 as Marcos lost
control of the country amid allegations of voter fraud in his
election campaign against Corazon Aquino, who replaced him as
president.
