<FIRST>r a PM-BrownTrial     07-18 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brown Trial,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Opens for Man Charged in Murder of Church Worker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROLLA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged in the murder of a church
volunteer was a small-time burglar, but no murderer, a defense
attorney said during the first day of John David Brown's murder
trial.
   Brown, 34, went on trial in Circuit Court Monday, more than two
years after a slaying that touched off an intensive two-month
manhunt.
   Brown's flight from the law inspired songs, T-shirts and other
local folklore, but the state regards him as a murderer and is
seeking the death penalty.
   In his opening remarks, Brown's court-appointed attorney, Brad
Kessler, portrayed Brown as someone who had a penchant for stealing
guns. But he said Brown was no murderer.
   However, Assistant Attorney General Tim Finnical said tests from
four ballistics experts showed that the .357-caliber Magnum revolver
Brown carried when he was arrested at a motel in Oklahoma was the
same gun used to kill Claude Long, 56.
   Long was shot and his car stolen shortly after he opened the New
Life Apostolic Church, near Doolittle in south-central Missouri, for
evening services on April 1, 1987.
   At the time, dozens of police officers were manning road blocks
and searching the surrounding Ozark hills for Brown, who was wanted
for wounding a Rolla police officer with a rifle two days earlier.
   Brown had been at large since escaping from the Ozark
Correctional Center near Springfield in June 1984. He was serving a
four-year term for burglary and possessing explosive weapons.
   Two hundred law officers from across the state, including
National Guardsmen, were involved in the two-month search for Brown.
   ``The evidence will be that this man deliberately took a life to
steal a car'' to avoid capture, Finnical said.
   Kessler said that the state was relying on circumstantial
evidence. No one saw Long killed, and police did not find Brown's
fingerprints in the church, he said.
</TEXT>
