<FIRST>r a PM-MontrealerReturns     07-18 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Montrealer Returns,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amtrak Train Returns to Northern New England Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRATTLEBORO, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From cornfields and the backs of pickup
trucks, hundreds of people waved at Amtrak's Montrealer passenger
train as it snaked through northwestern New England for the first
time in more than two years.
   The Washington-to-Montreal train resumes end-to-end service for
the public beginning today, following Monday's special train that
left Amherst, Mass., and ended in Montreal.
   The Montrealer has been a fixture in New England since 1972, but
the train stopped running north of Springfield, Mass., in April
1987. Amtrak said 49 miles of track had deteriorated so badly that
the train could only inch along at 5 mph in spots.
   The former owner, Guilford Transportation Industries, and Amtrak
couldn't agree on payments for repairs, and Amtrak finally asked the
Interstate Commerce Commission to condemn the line. The ICC agreed,
and another railway bought the line and fixed it with a
congressional appropriation.
   Money has also been set aside to fix another 50-mile stretch in
Massachusetts. In the meantime, the train is running on an alternate
route in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
   About 400 politicians, rail buffs and train executives were
aboard Monday's train.
   A fife and drum corps greeted them in Claremont, N.H., where
passenger rail service returned for the first time in 23 years.
   ``My wife and I are going to go to Montreal on this train in a
couple of weeks,'' said Tom Burnham, one of 300 to welcome the train
in Claremont. ``This is great for the area. It's the only stop in
New Hampshire, but I think it's excellent _ an opportunity we can't
afford to miss.''
   The politicians took turns engineering the train, with Vermont
Gov. Madeleine Kunin in the driver's seat as the train pulled into
Montpelier.
   ``We look at passenger train service as a nostalgic look into the
past. But I really think it's a look into the future,'' she said.
``If you're worried about the ozone layer up there, here's one
alternative.''
   Mike Brazinski, an assistant conductor from Waterford, N.Y., saw
another reason to make the trip.
   ``It's a beautiful way to go,'' he said.
</TEXT>
