<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Lyon     07-18 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Lyon,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Lyon, AP Photo Editor, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT KISCO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F. William Lyon, an editor in the photo
department of The Associated Press, has died at age 60.
   Lyon underwent brain surgery two months ago and died Monday at
the Northern Westchester Hospital Center in Mount Kisco.
   Lyon joined the AP in 1983 after nearly 40 years with United
Press International, where he had been head of photo operations.
   At the AP he undertook the editorial direction of LaserPhoto II,
the news agency's satellite-operated system of delivering
photographs to newspapers.
   Lyon had been vice president of news pictures for UPI after
holding a variety of editorial positions.
   As photographer and photo editor he covered the early days of the
space program, the civil rights movement, sports and politics.
   Lyon was born in Atlanta and was a resident of Montrose, north of
New York City.
   He is survived by his wife, Deborah; a daughter, Anne; and two
sons, Scott and David.
   Plans for a memorial service were not finalized.
   The family requested contributions to the Arthritis Foundation in
lieu of flowers.
</TEXT>
