<HEAD>Lauder Spent Record $8 Million on Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restransmitting to change category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Lauder has spent $8.5 million so far in
his quest to become mayor, more than any mayoral candidate in New
York history, according to a report.
   All the mayoral candidates filed campaign finance reports
Tuesday, and Lauder's dwarfed that of five other strong candidates.
   Former U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, Lauder's opponent in the
Republican primary, has raised between $1.2 million and $1.4 million.
   Ninety-three percent _ $7.9 million _ of Lauder's campaign money
came out of his pocket, according to The New York Times in today's
editions.
   Lauder, an heir to the Estee Lauder cosmetics fortune, had an
income last year of $30 million and reported his net worth at $227
million.
   The Republican primary turnout is expected to be about 100,000,
campaign aides told the Times, so Lauder has already spent about $85
on each potential voter.
   The bulk of Lauder's spending has gone for television ads _ $5
million worth.
   The finance reports indicate that all the candidates except
Lauder are having trouble raising money, and as a result, public
matching funds for their campaigns is likely to be lower than
anticipated.
   Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins has raised nearly $1.9
million.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch also has $1.9 million to spend.
   City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin has between $1.4 and $1.7
million.
   And former Metropolitan Transportation Authority chairman Richard
Ravitch has raised $1.2 million.
