<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     07-18 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Sri Lankan Tamil Leader Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following report was submitted to a
government censor, who ordered several paragraphs deleted.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tamil leader with close links to
India was shot and killed by unidentified assailants in Colombo,
police said today.
   Uma Maheswaran, 44, was killed on Sunday, said a police official,
speaking on condition of anonymity. The leader's body, which had a
gunshot wound in the head, was identified late Monday, the official
said.
   Last week, two other Tamil leaders, also considered pro-India,
were shot and killed in their Colombo residence. Witnesses
identified the assailants as members of the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam, a rebel group fighting the 40,000 Indian soldiers
deployed in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
   The Tigers denied the charge.
   In Madras, India, a spokesman for Sri Lankan Tamils said
Maheswaran had been attacked by Tiger assailants at least three
times in the past. The spokesman, Ponnudurai Ravinesan, said
Maheswaran was targeted because he broke away from the Tigers in
1975 to form his own militia.
   Maheswaran headed the People's Liberation Organization of Tamil
Eelam, a former rebel group that accepted an Indian-sponsored accord
in 1987 aimed at ending the insurgency by members of Sri Lanka's
Tamil minority who seek greater autonomy.
   The Tigers rejected the agreement and turned their guns on the
Indians. Since May, the Tigers have been holding talks with the Sri
Lankan government and both sides have called for Indian soldiers to
pull out by the end of July.
   India has refused, saying a hasty withdrawal will enable the
Tigers to attack rival Tamil groups and escalate violence on the
island nation.
   The issue has soured relations between the Colombo and New Delhi,
and both sides have exchanged sharply-worded letters on the subject.
   Meanwhile, a spokesman for the Tigers said 16 members of the
group left Colombo on Monday after concluding a round of talks with
the government. The talks started in May, the fist direct contact
between the two sides since the insurgency began in 1983.
   Both sides say they are satisfied with the progress in the
negotiations. Another round of talks will be held soon, the Tiger
spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed in the Tamil insurgency,
which was launched by at least a half-dozen guerrilla groups. The
victims have included many Tamils caught up in internecine fighting.
   India became involved in Sri Lanka's problems because of the
sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils for the rebel cause.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
allege they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up
75 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
