<FIRST>r a PM-FatalVision 1stLd-Writethru a0528 07-18 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fatal Vision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0528,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Best-Seller Reprinted With Author's Comments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling to McGinniss, sted McGinnis, throughout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new paperback edition of ``Fatal Vision,''
about a physician convicted of murdering his family, includes author
Joe McGinniss' response to charges that he misled his subject, The
New York Times said today.
   Signet New American Library is to begin shipping 100,000 new
copies of the book Wednesday.
   ``Fatal Vision'' tells about Jeffrey MacDonald, a physician and
former Green Beret convicted in 1979 of the murders of his wife and
two young daughters.
   McGinniss befriended MacDonald, even after he was convinced the
doctor was guilty.
   In an article in The New Yorker magazine earlier this year,
writer Janet Malcolm argued that McGinniss deceived MacDonald by
continuing their friendship. She went on to suggest in
``Reflections: The Journalist and the Murderer'' that all
journalists deceive their subjects somewhat.
   In an epilogue to the new edition of the nonfiction book,
McGinniss wrote that ``There was no commitment, indication or even
hint that my book would portray MacDonald as innocent.''
   He said that he did not hide his doubts about MacDonald's
innocence and never intended to deceive him.
   ``I liked MacDonald when I was with him during his murder trial.
I felt sorry for him for months afterward and wrote him letters
genuinely expressing that sorrow, even after I'd formed my opinion
as to his guilt,'' McGinniss said.
   The book was published by G.P. Putnam in 1983 and put out in
paperback by Signet the next year. It also was made into a
television miniseries.
</TEXT>
