<FIRST>r a PM-HorseFraud     07-18 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Horse Fraud,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Goat Trader Gets 18-Month Prison Term in Horse Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas goat trader was sentenced to 18 months
in federal prison for his role in a failed scheme to collect
insurance money on eight horses that were killed in a staged
accident.
   Rocky Beene, the last of four defendants sentenced in the case,
received the longest prison term for trying to defraud an insurance
company of $83,000 through phony claims involving the horses. He was
sentenced Monday in U.S. District Court.
   The animals, six of which were old and had little resale value,
were put inside a horse trailer and driven off a cliff in May 1983
near rural Jacumba in eastern San Diego County.
   The insurance company never paid the claim, but its investigation
and a subsequent lawsuit prompted authorities to file criminal
charges last year against Beene and five others.
   U.S. District Judge J. Lawrence Irving allowed Beene, 48, of
Junction, Texas, to begin serving his 18-month term Sept. 15. Beene
requested the delay so he can help finish blood testing on his goats
under an experimental AIDS research program.
   His attorney, Ronald Waska, in Houston, asked the judge to place
Beene on probation, arguing that his client didn't profit from the
scheme.
   However, Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Hayes said Beene admitted
he stood to receive $2,500 of the insurance proceeds if the company
had paid on the claims.
   The owner of the horses, Raymond Paul, 53, of Keyes, Calif.,
surrendered to authorities Monday to begin serving the one-year
prison term he received last month.
</TEXT>
