<FIRST>r a PM-StealthCharacteristics 1stLd-Writethru   07-18 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth Characteristics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0484,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomber Represents Revolutionary Technical Advances</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The flying ...' to restore dropped zero in 1940s;
SUBS last graf to CORRECT attribution to Couch, sted Hinds.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Stealth Test-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-2 stealth bomber is a
revolutionary advancement in intercontinental bombers that was in
development for 18 years, Air Force officials say.
   The B-2 was designed to evade detection by sophisticated enemy
air defenses with an unorthodox design of curves and contours.
   The stealth technology does not elude enemy radar so much as
absorb it, reflecting little radar energy back to ground receivers.
   ``We're talking about an aircraft now that basically negates the
air defenses built up in many many places around the world over many
years,'' said Gen. Bernard P. Randolph, who directs research,
development and testing of aerospace systems for the Air Force.
   The flying wing design was first conceived in the 1940s by
Northrop Corp. founder Jack Northrop, although the YB-49 aircraft he
built was scrapped by the government in 1948 in favor of more
conventional bomber designs.
   A factor leading to the demise of the YB-49 was a crash that
killed air force test pilot Glen Edwards. The Mojave Desert air
force base that now bears his name has become a focus of advanced
flight test research.
   The history of the flying wing came full circle Monday, as the
B-2 successfully completed its maiden flight and landed smoothly at
Edwards.
   The bomber is about 17 feet high and 69 feet long, only slightly
longer than an F-15 fighter.
   The wingspan, however, is about 172 feet, almost the span of a
B-52 bomber.
   It is powered by four General Electric engines mounted on top of
the wing. The Air Force says the engines were derived from those
used in F-16 and F-14 fighters.
   The bomber flies at subsonic speeds and is capable of hugging the
terrain closely or flying as high as 50,000 feet, the Air Force said.
   The B-2 has an operational range of more than 6,000 nautical
miles at high altitudes and more than 10,000 nautical miles with
aerial refueling capability.
   The aircraft will carry both nuclear and conventional weapons,
the Air Force said.
   The two-hour test flight was conducted with the landing gear
extended during the entire flight.
   Northrop test pilot Bruce J. Hinds, 50, and copilot Air Force
Col. Richard S. Couch, 42, said they flew the bomber at three speeds
and guided it through numerous turns to test its stability.
   Couch described the B-2 as ``a very nimble aircraft'' and said
the landing approach was ``rock'' steady.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0492 07-18 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede BANGKOK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Authorities Threaten Protesters; Pilgrims, Police Clash At Shrine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with warnings to martial law violators
on eve of protest; picks up 3rd pvs, `Radio Rangoon...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today threatened people who
join a major anti-government rally with death sentences in a
crackdown a day after monks reportedly clashed with security forces
at a Buddhist shrine.
   Ten people were arrested in the confrontation Monday at the
capital's Shwedagon Pagoda, the country's most famous shrine,
official Rangoon Radio reported.
   Opposition groups have said they will mount a mass pro-democracy
rally Wednesday during the annual Martyrs Day, which commemorates
the 1947 assassination of seven leaders to helped Burma achieve
independence from Britain. Burma became independent in 1948.
   Today, trucks equipped with loudspeakers moved through Rangoon
warning people to stay away from Wednesday's protests, diplomats
said. Public gatherings of more than five people are illegal under
martial law.
   ``There are trucks going round with loudspeakers telling people
that if there is any trouble on Martyrs Day, if there are any
demonstrations, people must not go out and join in,'' said a Western
diplomat speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``It looks as if they are trying to head off a big showdown,'' he
said.
   The martial law decrees have been in force since September, when
military commander Gen. Saw Maung seized power. Thousands of people
were killed in last year's crackdown of a popular nationwide
movement demanding an end to a quarter century of military rule.
   Radio Rangoon announced today that all cases of defiance of
government orders would be tried exclusively by military tribunals.
People found guilty will receive at least three years imprisonment
or a maximum penalty of death, the radio said.
   Rangoon residents and Western diplomats have predicted a showdown
between the ruling military council and the most popular opposition
party, the National League for Democracy, on Wednesday.
   The National League, headed by Aung San Suu Kyi, has announced
that it will not participate in the government plans for Martyrs Day
and will instead lead 104 opposition parties in a rival march to the
Martyrs Mausoleum in Rangoon.
   Ms. Suu Kyi is the daughter of Aung San, a national hero and one
of the seven independence leaders slain in 1947.
   Political dissent has swelled in Burma in the past month with Ms.
Suu Kyi denouncing military rule before large crowds in Rangoon.
Strong warnings have come from the government to end political
confrontation.
   On Monday, military authorities announced that three members of
Ms. Suu Kyi's party had been arrested in connection with a bomb
attack at a government oil refinery. Three people were killed and
two were wounded in the July 7 attack, they said.
   Monday's clash at the shrine occurred during the Waso festival,
one of the most holy in the Buddhist calendar. Waso marks Buddha's
first sermon to his followers after attaining enlightenment.
   Rangoon Radio said monks and pilgrims began chanting protests
after about 100 monks were refused entry to the pagoda because they
were not carrying identity cards.
   Monks began ``protesting loudly'' when the gates of the eastern
part of the pagoda were locked, the radio said.
   ``As the chants were going on, lay people ... arrived and joined
in the chants,'' the radio reported. ``Security forces appealed for
calm ... (but) as the appeal went unheeded, (they) chased the people
and the crowd dispersed.''
   Ten people were detained for ``further legal action'' the radio
said.
   The Shwedagon pagoda has been the site of numerous political
protests in Burmese history. During last year's upheaval,
pro-democracy demonstrators used it for a time as a headquarters for
their movement.
  
</TEXT>
