<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CalifQuake     07-18 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Calif Quake,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Shakes Northern California Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLISTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake jolted Hollister and
nearby Northern California communities early today but there were no
reports of damage.
   The earthquake measured 3.6 on the Richter scale of ground motion
and was centered 5 miles northeast of Hollister on the Quien Sabe
fault, said Lu Page, spokeswoman for the U.S. Geological Service in
Menlo Park.
   ``We had a few calls and felt it right here in police
headquarters,'' said a Hollister police dispatcher who declined to
give her name. ``It was a pretty good shake.''
   The earthquake, which struck at 4:07 a.m., was felt in Salinas 25
miles away.
   ``I was in a water bed and felt it so it had to be a pretty good
one,'' said Tom Lee, city editor with the Salinas Californian.
   Hollister is 120 miles south of San Francisco.
   The Richter scale is a measure of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a seisomograph.
   Each increase of one number, as in a jump from magnitude 5.5 to
6.5, means a tenfold increase in magnitude. A quake of 3.5 can cause
slight damage in populated areas; a 6.0 quake can cause severe
damage.
   The San Francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the
Richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the Richter
scale.
</TEXT>
