<FIRST>r a PM-BabyAbandoned     07-18 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Abandoned,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newborn Baby Found Alive Four Days After Being Abandoned In Woods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBERTY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newborn baby boy who survived almost five
days in a cardboard box in the woods was suffering from frostbite,
swelling and respiratory problems, but is a ``real fighter,''
authorities said today.
   The infant, known as Baby John Doe, was in stable but critical
condition when he was transferred from the Community General
Hospital in Harris to the Westchester County Medical Center.
   ``It is a miracle. We never expected to find the baby alive,''
said Liberty Police Chief Edward Eisley. ``Temperatures were
extemely cool here and we had a period of rain that the baby was
exposed to.''
   The infant's mother, a 17-year-old who concealed her pregnancy
from her family, was arraigned Monday night on charges of
first-degree assault and first-degree reckless endangerment, both
felonies.
   Police refused to release the name of the girl, who was granted
youthful offender status by Village Justice David Schiff and sent
without bail to the Sullivan County Jail in Monticello.
   The teen-ager told police she abandoned her son because she
thought he was dead when born about 6 a.m. last Thursday, Eisley
said.
   The girl delivered the baby herself at her parents' home and may
have thought the baby stopped breathing and died after birth, Eisley
said. Her parents learned that she had been pregnant when police
called to question them.
   The girl was distraught but ``happy to hear the baby was alive,''
he said.
   The baby, which weighed 6 pounds, 3 ounces, was wrapped in a bed
sheet, placed in the box and left in the woods behind an apartment
complex in Liberty, located about 70 miles northwest of New York
City.
   Temperatures dipped into the 50s during the five days that the
boy went without food, Eisley said.
   Police found the boy Monday after receiving several tips that the
teen-ager had abandoned her baby. He will be turned over to county
social workers when he recovers, Eisley said.
   ``It looks like he might be a real fighter,'' said a nursing
supervisor at Community General who requested anonymity. ``I'd say
he's in rather good condition, considering. I'm surprised he's
alive.''
</TEXT>
