<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Fire Flares Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA VERDE NATIONAL PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews battling a stubborn
wildfire reinforced their air power today and continued to struggle
to cut a containment line through steep terrain.
   The fire, which flared up over the weekend after experts thought
it was defeated, has burned 3,000 acres of pinyon trees and juniper
brush, but has spared Anasazi Indian cliff dwellings in the park in
the southwestern corner of the state.
   Firefighters planned to double their capacity to dump
fire-retardant slurry on the flames by setting up a depot in the
park to load the chemical mix into three helicopters working the
blaze. They previously had to shuttle to Durango or Grand Junction,
20 and 120 miles distant, respectively.
   The staff on the fire lines was tripled Monday, to 260, said fire
information officer John Pasquantino, and fire bosses were hoping to
contain the blaze Wednesday.
   Officials estimated the blaze was 85 percent contained and there
were about 3{ miles of fire line left to build. The remaining 15
percent, however, was on extremely steep terrain, Pasquantino said,
and containment wasn't expected until Wednesday afternoon.
   Elsewhere in the West:
   _The U.S. Bureau of Land Management launched a renewed attack
against a week-old lightning-caused blaze in pinon, juniper and sage
that was estimated at 1,000 acres outside Rangely in northwestern
Colorado. BLM spokesman Mike Rieser said the blaze approached a
ranch and a cow camp, but firefighters moved engines in and prepared
to back-burn an area to protect them.
   _Decreasing winds helped turn a wildfire away from summer homes
and a fish hatchery in southwestern Utah, but officials doubled
their manpower in case the 6,500-acre blaze explodes today. Forest
Service officials added 10 more pumpers and 400 fresh firefighters
to the lines Monday night in anticipation the blaze, burning in the
Dixie National Forest east of Cedar City, would grow to 8,000 acres.
   The fire is one of five uncontained blazes in southern Utah.
