<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneDemise     07-18 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Demise,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hand-Crank Phone Network to Lose Link to Outside World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH FORK, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progress is about to claim another
victim _ the Depression-era ring-down telephone system that has been
serving 18 homes in the canyon of Idaho's Salmon River.
   On Dec. 15, the operator keeping the customers of the North Fork
Telephone Co. in touch with the outside world will be replaced by an
AT&amp;T computer.
   The new equipment will no longer make the link between the
world's communications system and the crank-operated canyon
telephones that run on batteries and magnetos. Residents will be
able to talk to each other but won't be able to connect with the
outside world.
   The system is the last of its kind in Idaho and one of the last
in the United States.
   ``It hit us so unexpectedly. We've always been assured we would
have this service,'' said Marsha Smith, who with her neighbors is
accustomed to living without electricity and only seasonal running
water in the central Idaho canyon cut by the wilderness river.
   Century Telephone Co., which has been providing the operator,
offered to help solve the problem, but since it is becoming simply
the local exchange, company manager Frank Barsalou said there was
little his company could do.
   The system's users are linked to the world beyond by a single
wire connected to insulators hanging from rocks, poles and trees.
Calls to and from the outside must go through a local operator, who
buzzes the proper phone with a coded ring.
   The system originally served the U.S. Forest Service, and it was
bought by the resident cooperative in 1952 when the government
switched to radio communications.
   The canyon is too curvy for antenna radios to work, and while
residents of the 18 homes strung along a 31-mile stretch of the
canyon could hire their own operator, it would cost more than $1,600
a week.
   Because the Salmon is a wilderness river in that area west of
North Fork, the Forest Service refuses to allow new above-ground
telephone lines, and burying the phone cable could cost $600,000.
   Neither is economical, and canyon residents don't want to change
anyway.
   ``We would much rather have this for a wilderness area,'' North
Fork Vice President John Booker said.
   Idaho Public Utilities Commissioner Perry Swisher said he
believes phone service can be saved if everyone cooperates until a
technological answer can be found.
   But, Swisher said, ``What's bothered me, personally, is that I
haven't seen much imagination by the telecommunication people in how
to get down that canyon with service.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
