<FIRST>r w PM-FugitivesTaskForce 1stLd-Writethru a0459 07-18 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fugitives Task Force, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marshals Task Force Arrests 456</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fugitive Arrests Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, William J., to include that local police agencies
also involved.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Marshals Service task force that
arrested 456 fugitives over eight weeks was designed to target
people wanted in drug-related crimes in a region hard hit by the
violent narcotics trade.
   William J. Bennett, director of the Office of National Drug
Control Policy, said the $1.3 million federal program that teamed
the marshals with local police proves ``the bad guys can be
apprehended and brought to justice.''
   The U.S. Marshals Service led the Street Terror Offender Program,
or STOP, which captured 25 fugitives charged with murder in the
Washington-Baltimore area. Some fugitives were arrested as far away
as California and Florida, officials said.
   The program, which began May 22, targeted those with an active
drug felony warrant and at least three felony drug arrests or
convictions. Also targeted were suspects with an active warrant for
a drug-related homicide.
   Among those arrested was Herbert Douglas Jr., a suspect in three
Washington homicides.
   Douglas had been sentenced to 146 years in prison after being
convicted in a 1981 shootout with police during an armed robbery,
but he was paroled after serving less than six years. He is charged
with murder in a 1987 killing and a 1989 double homicide.
   Authorities also said they arrested Tony Miller, an alias for
Sean Henry, while he was trying to hide in the Marines.
   On the day Henry's trial was to begin on charges of distribution
of cocaine, the court received a death certificate for him. He was
subsequently arrested under another name and released, but a
fingerprint check revealed his identity. He was arrested at Parris
Island, S.C., while attending Marine Corps boot camp.
   STOP targeted 840 fugitives, arrested 456 and filed detainers on
155 already jailed on other charges. A total of 229 remain at-large,
said the Marshals service.
   The program involved 56 federal marshals and 34 local officers.
Officials lauded the cooperation between federal and local agencies.
   Of those arrested, 172 were wanted for crimes in the District of
Columbia, 154 in Baltimore and 130 in suburban Maryland and Virginia.
</TEXT>
