<FIRST>r a PM-MarriageMistake     07-18 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marriage Mistake,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Re-Married After Court Ruling Cancels First Vows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSSELLVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wanda and Henry Brannam lived in
marital bliss for 17 years, until they discovered they weren't
really married.
   Mrs. Brannam found out a week ago when she heard a news report
about a May 1 state Supreme Court ruling that declared a marriage
invalid because a divorce decree from a previous marriage wasn't
filed until after the second ceremony.
   ``I was not going to let any grass grow under my feet before I
could get things taken care of,'' she said. ``My husband at first
thought it was funny, but when I told him he was sleeping on the
couch because we weren't married, he started to pay attention to
me.''
   Mrs. Brannam was divorced March 2, 1972, and married Henry
Brannam on March 12. Her divorce papers weren't filed until March 31.
   She fretted the ruling could endanger the legal rights of her
14-year-old daughter.
   So the Brannams tied the knot, again, on the courthouse steps
last week, with the bride decked out in white satin.
   ``I hope it's better the second time around,'' she said.
</TEXT>
