<DOCNO> AP890718-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Findings     07-18 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Findings,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Blames Mismanagement For Nation's Worst Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's worst oil spill resulted
from ``arrogant and complacent'' managers who failed to prevent the
accident and then failed to move quickly to contain the spreading
ooze, a state study concluded.
   Robert LeResche, who heads the state's inquiry into the grounding
of the Exxon Valdez, said in a report issued Monday that poor
management by Exxon Shipping Co., not ``a berserk captain,'' is to
blame for the spill.
   ``Exxon Shipping's failures and lapses in management were so
numerous and pervasive that it is a wonder the Exxon Valdez was the
first tanker grounded,'' LeResche said.
   He described Alyeska Pipeline Service Co.'s response after the
spill in similar terms, calling it a ``total _ massive _
incredible'' failure and likening it to something out of the
Keystone Kops.
   The Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24 shortly after leaving
Valdez, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil into Prince
William Sound.
   ``The real causes of the Exxon Valdez disaster were not heroic,
but only pedestrian,'' LeResche said. ``There was not a berserk
captain waving a bottle on the bridge, there was not an autopilot
device run amok, there was not a broken radar, or a storm.
   ``There were simply arrogant and complacent people at the top
levels of Exxon Shipping Co. and Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. who
did not pay attention to their responsibilities.''
   LeResche's comments were contained in 110-page document submitted
to the National Transportation Safety Board. The document is the
state's proposed findings and recommendations based on the NTSB's
week-long hearings in Anchorage in May. The NTSB will issue its own
findings later.
   LeResche was the state's representative during the hearings.
   Calls for comment to Exxon Shipping offices in San Diego and
Thousand Oaks, Calif., and Houston, Texas, were not returned Monday.
   But Alyeska, a consortium of seven oil companies _ including
Exxon _ that operates the trans-Alaska oil pipeline and the Valdez
tanker terminal, rejected LeResche's conclusions.
   ``We totally disagree with the findings,'' said Alyeska spokesman
Tom Brennan.
   ``Nothing Alyeska could have done in the first 24 hours of the
spill would have significantly affected the course or environmental
impact of the spill,'' Brennan said. He repeated the company's
contention that the spill was simply too big to manage, ``even if
all the resources in the world had been instantaneously available.''
   Alyeska also renewed its claim that its response was hamstrung by
the unwillingness of the state and the Coast Guard to allow the use
of chemical dispersants and burning to dissipate the spill. The
state and the Coast Guard repeatedly have dismissed Alyeska's
argument in the past.
   LeResche chided Exxon Shipping for its ``amateurish and
bumbling'' attempt to monitor and assist skipper Joseph Hazelwood
after his 1985 treatment for alcoholism.
   The report also accused Exxon Shipping of failing to plan for
crew rest and alertness on trips from Valdez, trying to reduce
manning levels aboard tankers with little regard for crew safety,
and failing to provide the ship's officers with needed management
skills and a stable work force.
   As for Hazelwood, the report said his judgment was impaired at
the time of the accident, he left the bridge when he should have
been on it and he endangered the ship further after the grounding by
trying to free the Exxon Valdez from a reef.
   Hazelwood has been charged with three misdemeanor and three
felony crimes, and is scheduled to stand trial this fall. Hazelwood
pleaded innocent to all charges.
   The state report includes 13 recommendations for the NTSB,
including increased drug and alcohol testing for tanker crew members
and enhanced navigational aids in Prince William Sound.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
