<FIRST>r i PM-SovietSub     07-18 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Sub,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unexplained Radiation Found Near Site Of Soviet Submarine Mishap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traces of radiation were found in the air
filter of a Norwegian ship that shadowed a stricken Soviet nuclear
submarine near the Norwegian coast, scientists said today.
   The tiny amount of radioactive Iodine 131 could have been left
over from a previous accident or other ships that the Norwegian
vessel trailed, said researcher Gunnar Saxeboel of the Norwegian
Institute on Radiation Hygiene.
   Soviet officials had denied radioactivity was released from the
Alfa-class sub that surfaced Sunday and released clouds of black
smoke 75 miles east of the Norwegian coast in the Barents Sea and 30
miles north of Soviet territorial waters.
   Norwegian officials thought the smoke was from a fire, but Moscow
said it came from auxiliary diesel engines the sub had to start up
after a short circuit in a battery forced the shutdown of the
reactor.
   ``Preliminary tests don't prove any radioactivity that can be
traced to the submarine reactor,'' said a statement from the
institute. But it did not rule out the submarine as the source.
Water samples from the area proved free of radiation.
   ``The filter may have been on the ship for a long time and the
amount of radiation is so small that there is no danger of
contamination,'' said Saxeboel.
   Saxeboel speculated the isotope could have come from a Soviet
power plant on the Kola Pennisula or from another Soviet ship.
   The Norwegian ship, the Mariatta, was in the Norwegian Sea on
June 26 when a fire broke out on another Soviet submarine. The
Soviet Tass news agency reported four sailors suffered radiation
poisoning but later said the four were healthy.
   Norway complained of Soviet tardiness in reporting three
accidents aboard Soviet nuclear submarines near its shores in less
than four months.
   The supreme commander of the Soviet fleet, Adm. Vladimir
Chernavin, said in an interview published in the Soviet newspaper
Pravda today that warnings will be promptly issued in the future,
the Norwegian news agency NTB reported from Moscow.
   ``If there ever is a problem with radiation, information will
immediately be provided,'' the admiral was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
