<FIRST>r a PM-MacArthurFellows 1stLd-Writethru a0525 07-18 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MacArthur Fellows, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0525,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twenty-nine People Receive MacArthur Fellowships up to $375,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to move up reference to `The Thin Blue Line,''
SUBS 25th graf, `_Errol Morris ...' to include reference to movie.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school teacher and author who has
developed a technique for young children to act out their
classmates' fantasies has been awarded $355,000 by a philanthropic
foundation.
   Vivian Gussin Paley, 60, a teacher at the University of Chicago
Laboratory School, will receive the money with no requirements. She
can do with it whatever she wants.
   Mrs. Paley is one of 29 people awarded fellowships, ranging from
$150,000 to $375,000, by the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur
Foundation. Also among the recipients was the producer of the
documentary ``The Thin Blue Line,'' that movie that led to the
release of a Texas inmate convicted of murder.
   ``She deserves every accolade she gets,'' a colleague, Lucinda
Katz, said Monday after Mrs. Paley's award was announced. ``She's a
wonderful teacher.''
   Mrs. Paley has spent 32 years in the classroom _ 18 at the Lab
School _ and is the author five books on her teaching experience.
   She believes that children solve their problems through play, and
her technique of ``storyplaying'' allows children to tell stories
and the classroom to act them out.
   A total of 283 fellows ranging in age from 18 to 82 have been
named since the program began in 1981.
   There is no way to apply for a MacArthur Fellowship. Potential
recipients are proposed to the foundation by a group of more than
100 designated nominators throughout the country, who serve
anonymously and come from a variety of professions.
   Other recipients, and the sums awarded, were:
   _Martin Puryear, 48, a Chicago sculptor schooled in the history
of modern sculpture and non-Western traditions of the craft,
$295,000.
   _Anthony G. Amsterdam, professor of law at New York University,
$320,000.
   _Byllye Avery, founder and director of the National Black Women's
Health Project in Atlanta, $310,000.
   _Alvin J. Bronstein, director of the National Prison Project in
Washington, $360,000.
   _Leo William Buss, associate professor of biology, geology and
geophysics at Yale University, $230,000.
   _Jay Cantor, professor of English at Tufts University and an
author, $255,000.
   _George D. Davis, executive director of the Commission on the
Adirondacks in the 21st Century, Wadhams, N.Y., $285,000.
   _Allen Grossman, professor of poetry and general education at
Brandeis University in Lexington, Mass., $340,000.
   _John Harbison, professor of music at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology, $305,000.
   _W. Keith Hefner, founder and publisher-executive director of
Youth Communications in New York, $225,000.
   _Ralf David Hotchkiss, rehabilitation engineer and proponent of
independent living, Oakland, Calif., $260,000.
   _John Rice Irwin, founder and director of the Museum of
Appalachia in Norris, Tenn., $345,000.
   _Daniel H. Janzen, professor of biology at the University of
Pennsylvania, $305,000.
   _Aaron Lansky, founder and director of the National Yiddish Book
Center, in Holyoke, Mass., $225,000.
   _Jennifer Alice Moody, an archaeologist and an exponent of
interdisciplinary research in historical ecology, Anopolius, Crete,
and Cypress, Texas, $235,000
   _Errol Morris, an independent documentary filmmaker who produced
``The Thin Blue Line,'' New York, $260,000.
   _Richard Powers, a writer of fiction, Heerlen, Netherlands,
$215,000
   _Ellendea Catherine Proffer, author, translator and co-founder
and director of Ardis Publishers, Ann Arbor, Mich., $275,000.
   _Bernice Johnson Reagon, founder and director of Sweet Honey in
the Rock, a women's a capella quartet, and a curator at the National
Museum of American History at the Smithsonian Institution, where she
founded a program in black culture, Washington, D.C., $275,000.
   _Theodore Rosengarten, an independent historian whose work
focuses on the lives of slaves and freed blacks in the 19th and 20th
centuries, McClellanville, S.C., $275,000.
   _Margaret Rossiter, a historian of science who helped establish
the history of women in science as a scholarly field, Ithaca, N.Y.,
$280,000.
   _George Russell, a jazz composer, band leader and theorist who
teaches at the New England Conservatory, Cambridge, Mass., $375,000.
   _Pam Solo, co-director of the Institute for Peace and
International Security, Cambridge, Mass., $280,000.
   _Claire Van Vliet, a graphic artist, papermaker, printer and
bookmaker, West Burke, Vt., $330,000
   _Baldemar Valasquez, co-founder and president of the Farm Labor
Organizing Committe, Toledo, Ohio, $265,000.
   _Bill Viola, an artist who uses video to stretch the boundaries
of the video field, Long Beach, Calif., $245,000.
   _Eliot Wigginton, a high school English teacher, Rabun Gap, Ga.,
$285,000.
   _Patricia Chapple Wright, assistant professor of anthropology at
Duke University and director of the Ranomafana National Park in
Madagascar, Durham, N.C., and Madagascar, $275,000.
