<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     07-18 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Kill 30 Rival Rebels in Power Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fundamentalist guerrilla group today
acknowledged killing at least some fighters of a rival faction after
reports it ambushed and executed 30 fighters of the competing force.
   Rebel sources said the two groups are locked in a power struggle
that could hinder efforts to overthrow the Soviet-backed Afghan
government.
   Reacting Monday to the earlier reports of the killings on July 9
in Takhar Province about 140 miles north of Kabul, Bush
administration officials deplored the attack but said U.S. support
to the Afghan guerrillas would remain intact.
   ``Our commitment to support the mujahedeen is very clear and the
nature and character of our support is unchanged and it will
continue,'' said State Department spokesman Richard Boucher. The
guerrillas call themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors.
   The dead, including seven key commanders, belonged to the
fundamentalist Jamiat-e-Islami guerrilla group. Jamiat-e-Islami said
the ambush was carried out by the rival Hezb-e-Islami group, which
is led by Gulbaddin Hekmatyar.
   Jamiat spokesman said Mohammad Shaoib said five people were
killed in the ambush, and 25 others were later executed. Spokesman
Qaribur Rehman Saeed, of the Hezb-e-Islami group, denied anyone was
executed, but he acknowledged at least some of the killings.
   Saeed did not say how many guerrillas were killed, and he said
his group was still investigating what happened.
   Hekmatyar is a hard-line, anti-American fundamentalist. Despite
his anti-U.S. stand, the United States has backed him and other
guerrilla commanders who are trying to overthrow President Najib's
government in Afghanistan.
   The struggle for power between the guerrillas has been waged
almost since the outset of the decade-old war. It has left scores of
Afghan rebels from both groups dead, guerrilla sources said today.
   The forces killed in the latest attack were from Afghanistan's
northern provinces of Badakhshan, Kunduz, Takhar and Baghlan. They
were returning from a strategy meeting with Jamiat commander Atmad
Shah Masood, said Shaoib.
   Shaoib gave no details of the attack or executions.
   ``It is a great loss for all Afghanistan, especially for the
north,'' he said.
   ``In the northern provinces, there are only two powers, Jamiat
and Hezb,'' said Saeed. ``Many of our commanders have been killed by
Masood's people.''
   Masood formed a northern council to incorporate guerrillas
belonging to the seven rebel parties with headquarters in Pakistan's
border city of Peshawar. In a message to his headquarters in
Pakistan more than one year ago, Masood said he was consolidating
forces and establishing an Islamic army.
   Saeed said, ``The conflict started right from the beginning when
Masood wanted the upper hand in the north.''
   ``Masood wanted to clear the area of Hezb mujahedeen,'' he said.
   He said had Masood agreed to temporary cease-fires with Soviet
troops during their nine years of Afghan military intervention
ending in February. Rival clashes broke out when Hezb-e-Islami
forces refused to recognize those arrangements, said Saeed.
   Another rebel source, who spoke on condition of anonmity, said,
``Both the sides are greedy .... They want more and more control.''
   Rebel sources independent of either group, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said they fear the latest round of killings could
cripple guerrilla efforts to gain control of government-controlled
cities in the north.
   Sources within Jamiat said Masood's strategy has been to
concentrate on northern cities, particularly Kunduz, Baghlan and
Badakhshan.
   A moderate rebel who spoke on condition anonymity, said Masood's
troops could not approach the Afghan capital, Kabul, even if they
wanted because they are blocked by Hezb-e-Islami forces in central
Parwan province.
   In Stockholm, Sweden, officials said today that senior U.S. and
Soviet officials will meet there on July 31 for talks on Afghanistan.
   Swedish news reports said the talks likely will focus on U.S. and
Soviet arms supplies to the opposing sides in the civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
