<FIRST>r i PM-Panama     07-18 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government, Opposition, List Agenda for Further Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said more talks are planned
between the government and opposition despite the government's
insistence that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega will not step down.
   The two sides announced an agenda Monday after the first meeting
to include military representatives since the May 7 election that
intensified the country's political crisis.
   Diplomats from the Organization of American States who arranged
and were mediating the talks were to leave today for Washington. On
Wednesday, they report to the OAS on the progress of their effort.
   Negotiations will resume when opposition representatives return
from the OAS meeting, a government representative said.
   Noriega, who chief of the Defense Forces and de facto leader of
the country, did not attend the Monday meeting. Instead, he attended
a session of the State Council, which is studying a proposal for
forming a junta after Sept. 1, when the civilian government's term
ends.
   Asked about the country's political situation, he said nothing
but reached into the seat of his car and, smiling, took out a police
club and waved it at journalists.
   In addition to Noriega's departure as chief of the Panamanian
Defense Forces, the opposition agenda includes: defining what is
meant by transfer of power; the elections, which international
observers say the opposition won by a 3-1 margin, and human rights
violations.
   Government and military representatives listed: an end to U.S.
aggression and military threats against Panama; withdrawal of
additional U.S. troops sent to Panama; an end to economic aggression
and return of Panamanian funds held by the United States; strict
compliance with the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties, and no U.S.
interference in Panamanian political affairs.
   Under the treaties, Panama is to take full control of the canal
at the end of 1999.
   International observers say Noriega rigged the presidential
election in favor of his candidate, Carlos Duque, and had it
annulled when the fraud and opposition victory became obvious.
   The opposition and the United States have insisted for a year and
a half that Noriega step down as chief of Defense Forces. Noriega
refuses.
   Noriega was indicted in the United States on drug-trafficking and
money-laundering charges, but he denies the charges and says they
are part of a U.S. attempt to retain control of the canal.
   As part of its effort to force Noriega to leave, the United
States froze Panamanian government deposits in U.S. banks, barred
payments to the Panamanian government and increased its military
strength in the Canal Zone.
</TEXT>
