<FIRST>r a PM-RadioactiveLemonade     07-18 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radioactive Lemonade,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worker Who Intentionally Drank Radioactive Lemonade Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCRIBA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear plant supervisor who deliberately
drank lemonade laced with radioactive material is under
investigation, but officials said today they had no ready
explanation for the act.
   The dose of radioactive material swallowed by the supervisor at
the James A. FitzPatrick plant was not life-threatening and was
equal to the amount of radiation in five chest X-rays, officials
said. He didn't require hospitalization or medical treatment.
   ``There are a lot of questions unanswered and we are attempting
to get the answers,'' said Cliff Spieler, spokesman for the New York
Power Authority, which runs the plant.
   The authority released a statement Monday saying the worker told
investigators that he had put radioactive material in a bottle of
lemonade before drinking the liquid. Spieler refused to say what
reason the man gave.
   The supervisor was idenitified by the power authority only as a
worker for Institute of Resource Management, a Maryland company
under contract to provide short-term workers at the Lake Ontario
plant.
   Wayne Schmidt, senior resident inspector for the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission, said he was a radiation supervisor on the
plant's refuel floor, an area where fuel is loaded and unloaded from
the reactor.
   A radiation detector alerted officials to the presence of
radioactive cobalt inside the man's body as he walked through the
whole-body detector while leaving the plant Friday, Schmidt said.
   In addition to cobalt-60, the man also swallowed cesium-137 and
manganese-54, Schmidt said.
   The man's estimated dose of radiation was between 50 and 100
millirems, he said. A single chest X-ray has 10 to 20 millirems.
   He man was given laxatives and cranberry juice and was detained
at the plant until the material had passed from his system and could
be analyzed, officials said.
   The plant did not have to declare an ``unusual event,'' the
lowest of four types of public emergency warnings, because the
radiation dose was so low, he said.
</TEXT>
