<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-18 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Dies of Injuries in Mistaken Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab teen-ager died after the car she was
riding in overturned after being stoned by Palestinian activists who
may have attacked the vehicle because of its Israeli plates, a
hospital official said today.
   Raeda Issa Suleiman, 14, of Beit Safafa in the Jerusalem area,
died of head injuries she suffered when the car she was riding in
was stoned Sunday in the West Bank town of Bethany. Three others in
the car were injured.
   Police and residents said her car apparently was mistaken for an
Israeli vehicle because it had yellow Israeli license plates instead
of blue West Bank tags.
   Hadassah Hospital spokeswoman Ruth Mekel said Ms. Suleiman was
declared dead Monday night.
   Her death brings to 566 the number of Palestinians killed in the
19-month uprising. Thirty-six Israelis have also have been killed in
the uprising.
   Army prosecutors meanwhile filed charges against two Palestinian
shepherds, Fahem Ramadan Shihan Ali and Mustafa Othman Omar Al-Haj,
both 21. They are accused of stabbing to death Steven Rosenfeld, a
Jewish settler who immigrated from Washington, D.C.
   He was killed June 17 while hiking near the suspects' West Bank
village of Burkin.
   A third, unidentified Palestinian shepherd is suspected of
participating but has not yet been charged, the army said.
   Ali and Al-Haj were accused of membership in the outlawed Fatah
group, Yasser Arafat's mainstream faction of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
