<FIRST>r i PM-Bush-DutchLeaders     07-18 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Dutch Leaders,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Praise, Criticism from Dutch Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush won praise from
Dutch government officials today for his knowledge of European
affairs, mixed with criticism from an opposition leader over the
environment and other issues.
   Duth Foreign Minister Hans van den Broek said the first visit by
an American president to the Netherlands had established ``a new
marker'' in the two centuries of close ties between the two
countries.
   Joep de Boer, a parliamentarian for Premier Ruud Lubbers'
Christian Democratic Appeal party, called Bush ``the most European
oriented president there has been for years.''
   Bush conferred with 11 Dutch politicians over breakfast before
departing for Washington at the end of his four-nation, 10-day trip
to Europe.
   Bush also met privately for 30 minutes before breakfast with
Dutch opposition leader Wim Kok, leader of the opposition Labor
party and a likely winner of elections scheduled for Sept. 6.
   Aboard Air Force One, Bush told reporters the Dutch politicians
had expressed strong views on the environment and other issues that
at times bordered on argument.
   Kok told reporters after the meeting that he had argued for
U.S.-Soviet negotiations on elemininating both superpowers' arsenals
of short-range nuclear missiles.
   Kok also criticized Bush for not endorsing a Dutch government
plan to enlist United Nations help in setting up monitoring rules to
protect the atmosphere's delicate ozone layer.
   ``The attitude of the Americans towards strenghtening the United
Nations in environmental matters is too reluctant,'' said Kok.
   During his Dutch visit, Bush reiterated the NATO position that
the allies must first press for substantial reductions in
conventional troops and weaponry in Europe before seeking a treaty
with the Soviets on short-range nuclear weapons.
   ``As regards his attitude towards the Soviet Union, Bush is more
cautious then we are. We can do a lot more ... to give the process
of economic and political reform a chance,'' said Kok, whose party
helped orchestrate nationwide opposition to basing 48 U.S.-built
cruise missiles on Dutch soil in the early 1980s.
   Although the Lubbers' government decided to go ahead with the
plan, the missiles never came, because of the 1987 U.S.-Soviet pact
to ban all intermediate range nuclear wapons.
   Van den Broek, in a radio interview, called the Bush visit
``extremely gratifying and successful.''
   ``In the uninterrupted relations between our two countries this
is a new marker in a long era of mutual friendship,'' the foreign
minister said.
   Joris Voorhoeve, leader of the right-wing Liberals, junior
partner in the coalition government, said Bush had offered ``the
American prescription'' of lower taxes to speed up economic growth
as a cure for the Netherlands' economic woes.
   Although Dutch economic growth is above average for the 12
nations of the European Economic Community, the nation still suffers
a crippling 14-percent unemployment rate.
   De Boer, his party's foreign affairs spokesman, said he had
warned the president about the resurgence of ``nationalism'' in West
Germany. ``I'm totally reassured. They are aware of the problem,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
