<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 4thLd-Writethru a0532 07-18 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0532,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Announces Candidacy For Presidency; Transit Strike Erupts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Solidarity delegates meeting,
lawmakers saying Jaruzelski won't get their support; picks up 11th pvs,
`The state-run...' Minor editing thereafter to TRIM.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leader Wojciech Jaruzelski
reversed himself today and said he will be a candidate for
president, which the National Assembly is to elect Wednesday.
   Also today, bus and tram drivers in the country's most populous
province of Katowice went on strike for higher pay, a sign of
growing public dissatisfaction with the beleaguered economy a new
president will face.
   Gen. Jaruzelski had declared June 30 that he was not a candidate,
saying he was too closely linked to the 1981 martial-law crackdown
that attempted to crush Solidarity and not closely enough with
democratic changes now sweeping Poland.
   He proposed the candidacy of a longtime loyalist, Interior
Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak. But Communist leaders asked Jaruzelski to
reconsider and he appeared in the last few weeks to be leaning
toward running.
   A victory hinges on how whether the Communist coalition, which
has a majority of the seats in the National Assembly, will stand
behind its leader.
   The presidency, whose powers include control of the military and
foreign relations, was a result of government-Solidarity talks in
the spring. The negotiations also brought elections in June in which
Solidarity candidates were limited to winning a minority number of
seats in the National Assembly.
   On Monday, Jaruzelski met with Solidarity lawmakers and submitted
to nearly six hours of questioning in an attempt to win votes.
   But as the Solidarity delegation convened this afternoon to
decide how to vote, the opposition lawmakers indicated they doubted
there would be any support among them for Jaruzelski.
   ``I feel he is responsible for all of the mistakes. He is
responsible so I cannot support him,'' said Zofia Kuratowska, a
deputy speaker of the Senate.
   The new president will seat a government that must deal with
worsening consumer shortages and inflation that, based on a new
statistics for the first six months of 1989, appears headed for an
annual rate of 160 percent.
   The vote Wednesday is to be a roll call, which should make it
easier for coalition leaders to insist that each lawmaker vote for
Jaruzelski.
   The state-run PAP news agency said Jaruzelski, announcing his
candidacy today at a meeting of Communist lawmakers, said he was
``driven by a sense of duty'' in heeding the urging of party leaders
that he run.
   To win approval, Jaruzelski would need the votes of nearly all
coalition lawmakers because the coalition holds a 54 percent
majority in the National Assembly. The president is to be chosen by
a simple majority during a joint session of the 100-member Senate
and 460-member Sejm.
   Some members of the Communist and affliiated Peasant Party were
elected to in June's balloting with Solidarity support and it is not
clear if they could support a Jaruzelski candidacy.
   Under the April agreement that reinstated Solidarity, the free
trade union movement was only allowed to field candidates for 46
percent of the 560 seats in the two-chamber assembly. It won all but
one of those seats.
   On Friday, Solidarity chief Lech Walesa said he would cooperate
with Jaruzelski if the general is elected. He said political
conditions require that the president come from within the Communist
coalition.
   There are fears that a non-Communist president would provoke a
dangerous reaction from hard-liners at home and elsewhere in the
Soviet bloc.
   Solidarity lawmakers who met with him on Monday said Jaruzelski
did not sufficiently repudiate the 1981 crackdown or Poland's
participation in the 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed ``Prague
Spring'' reforms in Czechoslovakia.
   Jaruzelski was defense minister at the time. He has led Poland
for 8{ years and this year presided over the reinstatement of
Soldarity. Under a revamped constitution, the new president is to
serve up to two six-year terms.
   Senator Karol Modzelewski of Wroclaw, speaking for the Solidarity
lawmakers, stressed Monday that Walesa's endorsement of Jaruzelski
does not mean they feel bound to vote for the general.
   It appeared virtually certain that the Solidarity group would
feel bound to somehow register their dissatisfaction with Jaruzelski.
   Walesa's statement and words of praise for Jaruzelski from
President Bush during his trip to Poland July 9-11 are considered to
have helped persuade Jaruzelski to run.
   If Jaruzelski becomes president, he said Monday, he would give up
the post of party chief, according to Solidarity lawmakers.
</TEXT>
