<FIRST>r i PM-Karajan     07-18 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Karajan,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conductor Buried In Quiet Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert von Karajan, the brilliant
Austrian maestro and long-time conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic,
was buried in a small ceremony in his hometown near Salzburg, a
spokesman at the Salzburg Festival said today.
   Karajan, who died Sunday of heart failure at 81, was buried
Monday night in the family crypt in Anif, said the spokesman on
condition of anonymity.
   A religious service in the local parish church attended by few
family members and guests preceded the burial, he said.
   ``It was the wish of his wife Eliette Mouret and his daughters,
Isabelle and Arabelle, that the ceremony be held without a furor in
a small circle of relatives and friends,'' the spokesman said.
   Karajan was to have opened this year's festival July 27 with
Giuseppe Verdi's Opera ``A Masked Ball,'' starring Placido Domingo.
   Festival officials said the celebrations to follow the premier
would be canceled and the festival would hold a formal memorial
ceremony for Karajan on July 30 with the Vienna Philharmonic and the
Vienna state Opera choir. Riccardo Muti and Sir Georg Solti are to
conduct, festival officials said.
   The Festival directorate said Solti would replace Karajan
conducting the Verdi opera at the premiere and three planned
performaces after that.
   However, it was not yet known who would conduct the remaining
three performances of the opera and a concert with the Vienna
Philharmonic in August that was to have been conducted by Karajan.
</TEXT>
