<FIRST>r a PM-DetroitSymphony     07-18 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Symphony,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Payless Payday Threatened for Orchestra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit Symphony Orchestra says it will be
unable to pay regular biweekly salaries to 155 employees this week
because of worsening financial problems.
   Symphony Chairman Robert S. Miller announced Monday there was
``no way'' the orchestra would be able to come up with the $200,000
needed to give 97 musicians and 58 other staff members their full
checks Thursday.
   The Detroit Federation of Musicians, which represents the
symphony members, agreed to continue performing if the symphony
could issue one-week paychecks. Symphony finance committee chairman
Alfred R. Glancy III said he expected to learn today if that was
possible.
   Miller said last month that the symphony would close in mid-July
unless the state, city and businesses pledged $18.2 million for the
next four years to help it overcome chronic financial problems.
   Since then, state, city and corporate leaders have given hopeful
signs of additional funding but no hard commitments, spokeswoman
Mary Loiselle said today.
   ``We have made a lot of progress and we are encouraged by that,''
Lioselle said. ``But in the mean time, the cash is running out.''
   The symphony has an $8 million debt that officials have said will
reach $16 million by 1993.
</TEXT>
