<HEAD>Victims of Gas Disaster Launch Campaign Against Union Carbide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victims of the Bhopal gas disaster will
launch a weeklong campaign in August to ban Union Carbide Corp. from
India, an activist said today.
   Abdul Jabbar Khan, organizer of the Bhopal Gas-Affected Women's
Organization, said the group will hold public meetings beginning
Aug. 9 to support its demand and urge shopkeepers not to sell Union
Carbide products.
   The main product sold by the chemical company in India is
batteries. It also sells flashlights and other products in India.
   A gas leak in December 1984 from a pesticide plant operated by
the U.S. multinational's Indian subsidiary left at least 3,100
people dead and more than 20,000 injured.
   Khan said the campaign will end with an attempt by protesters to
enter the plant and demands that it be declared a national monument
in memory of the victims.
