<FIRST>r a PM-BuriedBodies     07-18 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Buried Bodies,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Cause of Death Found in Boardinghouse Bodies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No cause of death could be determined
for the seven bodies dug up in the yard of a boardinghouse operator
who has been charged with killing her tenants, the Sacramento County
coroner says.
   Coroner Charles Simmons issued a statement Monday saying that
although drugs were found in all seven, their significance could not
be determined because of decomposition. Also, no other traumas that
might have caused death were detected.
   Boardinghouse operator Dorothea Puente, 60, remains in jail
without bail on charges of murdering the seven, plus two others
whose bodies were found elsewhere. She has pleaded innocent. A
preliminary hearing is scheduled for Sept. 12.
   Puente is accused of doing away with residents of her downtown
boardinghouse in order to cash their Social Security checks.
   Her attorney, Assistant Public Defender Peter Vlautin, said the
coroner's results ``are consistent with all we know about the case.
Dorothea Puente is innocent of any allegation of murder, and these
results just confirm that.''
   Simmons' report said that in all seven cases the drug flurazepam,
a sleeping pill sold under the brand name Dalmane, was found. An
anti-convulsant called Degratol was found in two cases.
   In three of the bodies, Elavil, an antidepressant known as
amitriptyline, was found. And the tranquilizer Valium, painkiller
codeine, tranquilizer Haldol, tranquilizer loxapine and
anticonvulsant Dilantin were found in one or two other cases.
</TEXT>
