<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--BridgeCollapse-Body     07-18 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bridge Collapse-Body,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body Found In Mohawk River Confirmed As Victim of Bridge Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A body found in the Mohawk River has
been identified as the last missing victim of the 1987 collapse of a
bridge on the New York State Thruway, police said today.
   A boater spotted the body in the river near Schenectady on
Saturday, said Sgt. Ralph Reichert of the Schenectady County
Sheriff's Department.
   Relatives of Edward Meyer tentatively identified the body late
Monday from keys, jewelry and clothing found on the remains, said
state Trooper Edward F. Dyer.
   Meyer was one of 10 people killed when rain-swollen Schoharie
Creek eroded away bridge supports and six cars and one truck fell
more than 80 feet on April 5, 1987. The nine other bodies were
recovered.
   Meyer, 50, a chief gas mechanic for Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.,
was returning to Albany with two co-workers from a bowling
tournament in Syracuse when the bridge collapsed.
