<HEAD>14 Killed, 28 Injured as Buses Collide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two buses collided in the northern state
of Punjab on Tuesday, killing 14 people and injuring 28 others,
police said.
   The buses crashed into each other on a curve outside Tarn Taran,
15 miles south of this Sikh holy city, said senior police officer
Baldev Singh.
   There were few casualties among the passengers, but many people
walking or waiting along the road were crushed to death when the
buses flipped over, Singh said.
   Many people were riding on the roof of one of the buses, a
privately owned coach that had 72 people inside. About 60 people
were in the other bus, operated by state-owned Punjab Roadways,
Singh said.
