<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissidents     07-18 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Dissidents' News Conference Breaks up in Disarray</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A news conference called by exiled Chinese
dissidents broke up in disarray Tuesday as student leaders arrived
late and then fled, apparently in fear.
   Held at a hotel off the Place de la Republique, the dissidents
were supposed to announce the formation of the ``United Democratic
Front'' to oppose authorities in Beijing.
   But no one showed up. The hotel management asked the 30
journalists who had gathered to leave.
   As they dispersed, two taxis pulled up, the first bearing Wu'er
Kaixi, one of the best-known leaders of the student-led movement for
democracy, and three compatriots.
   Reporters said Wu'er appeared confused and frightened and sped
off immediately.
   A second taxi arrived carrying Yan Jiaqui, onetime adviser to
Zhao Ziyan, former secretary-general of the Chinese Communist Party,
and Liu Bin Yan, a Chinese author exiled in the United States. They
spoke between themselves in Chinese outside the hotel.
   Asked for a translation, another dissident said only that they
were calling for the non-violent overthrow of ``the tyrannical
regime in power in Beijing.''
   Reporters said Yan and Liu also appeared nervous and confused.
   Wu'er, 21, and eight other Chinese dissidents surfaced in France
two weeks ago after escaping China to Hong Kong through a secret
underground network.
   Both he and Yan Jiaqi, the leader of the dissident intellectual
movement, have said they have neither asked for nor received special
protection from French authorities.
   The dissidents held their first news conference in Paris on July
12, calling for the United Nations to investigate the June 3-4
killing of unarmed demonstrators in Beijing.
   China has repeatedly protested France's granting refuge to the
dissidents as an ``unfriendly action.''
   Hundreds of Chinese students wearing headbands with Chinese
characters reading ``Liberty, Equality, Fraternity'' rode bicycles
in the Bastille Day parade through Paris on Friday, and carried a
banner saying ``We Carry On.''
</TEXT>
