<FIRST>u a PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0575 07-18 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Sees Shift in Abortion Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The Supreme ...' to CORRECT title of ruling
to Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services, sted Webster vs. Missouri.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle predicted the
Supreme Court's recent ruling on abortion will focus debate not on
whether abortions should be legal but under what circumstances they
should be performed.
   ``Most people in America support the right of a woman to have an
abortion,'' Quayle said Monday at a breakfast with reporters. ``But
that's not going to be the argument. ... The argument is going to
be, how are the abortions going to be performed in this country?''
   Quayle, on a California tour and campaign stop for Republican
Sen. Pete Wilson's gubernatorial bid, said he foresees such future
restrictions as parental consent required for minors, bans on
abortions in public hospitals and bans on abortions performed solely
because the fetus a woman is carrying is not the sex she wanted.
   The Supreme Court, ruling in Webster vs. Reproductive Health
Services earlier this month, granted more authority to the states to
regulate abortions.
   Quayle, who said he personally favors abortion only if a woman's
life is in danger, said a so-called ``Human Life Amendment'' is
likely to be approved by Congress. Such a Constitutional amendment
would let states decide if abortions should be legal.
   Quayle said President Bush would support such a measure.
   Quayle's remarks drew criticism from those on both sides of the
issue.
   Democratic consultant Ann Lewis suggested the vice president was
trying to boost the Republican Party's appeal to voters who believe
women have a right to have abortions.
   Susan Carpenter-McMillan, the spokeswoman for the Los Angeles
chapter of Right to Life, responded, ``Read our lips. We will not
accept a change in the pro-life policy from the Bush
administration.''
   Later in the day, Quayle told the Western Governors' Association
meeting in Long Beach the nation needs to renew its enthusiasm for
the space program and chart a course for the future that includes
manned space exploration.
</TEXT>
