<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     07-18 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Urge Bush Not to Meet De Klerk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 members of the House have asked
President Bush not to meet with a prominent South African politician
unless that nation's white-minority government frees political
prisoners, lifts the state of emergency and allows dissident
political groups to form.
   The request was made in a letter dated June 29 and released at a
news conference Tuesday.
   One of the signers, Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., said he had seen
reports that Bush was considering meeting with F.W. de Klerk, leader
of South Africa's National Party, later this month.
   Wolpe is the chairman of the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee
on Africa.
   The letter said that ``to meet with the National Party leader and
anticipated president of South Africa without any significant change
by the white-minority regime would send a terribly wrong signal
concerning the direction of U.S. policy during the Bush
administration.''
   The letter commended Bush for meeting with South African
Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other opponents of the racial policies
of the South African government.
   As for Bush's meeting with de Klerk, congressmen said they
opposed such a session unless the South African government took
these steps:
   _Releasing all political prisoners jailed because of their
opposition to South Africa's racial policies.
   _Ending the state of emergency, extended into its fourth year
June 9, along with abolishing restrictions on leaders of
organizations outside parliament.
   _Removing bans on all political organizations.
