<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-18 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis and Allied Militia Intercept Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers and their allied militia
in south Lebanon shelled and intercepted a squad of guerrillas
Tuesday, killing one and wounding three, police reported.
   Police also said Syrian soldiers and the Christian army units of
Gen. Michel Aoun fought intermittent artillery duels in and around
Beirut. No casualties were reported.
   A police spokesman said an armored force of the South Lebanon
Army militia moved north from Israel's south Lebaon ``security
zone'' to intercept guerrillas ``encircled by Israeli shellfire.''
   He said the militiamen ``fought a one-hour confrontation with the
guerrillas'' about two miles north of the security zone, a strip
that varies in depth from six to 10 miles just inside south Lebanon.
   An Israeli ``observation post spotted the guerrilla squad north
of the zone before daybreak,'' the spokesman said. ``Israeli gunners
hammered the guerrillas with about 200 howitzer shells until shortly
after daybreak, when the SLA patrol was sent out of the zone to
intercept them.
   ``One guerrilla fighter was killed in the confrontation and three
others were wounded. SLA militiamen were seen carrying the dead
person into one of their T-54 tanks.''
   The wounded guerrillas managed to withdraw north to
Syrian-controlled territory in the Bekaa Valley, he said. No
casualties were reported among the militiamen
   Police did not identify the guerrilla group involved.
   Israel established the zone in June 1985, when it withdrew most
of its forces from south Lebanon after three years of occupation.
The South Lebanon Army, a predominantly Christian militia financed
and trained by Israel, helps patrol the zone.
   In the capital, Syria's 130mm howitzer batteries along the
seaside boulevard in west Beirut opened fire at 1 a.m. on the
Christian-held coast north of the city.
   Syrian gunners have shelled the coast since the artillery war
began March 8 in an attempt to keep supply ships from landing at
Christian ports.
   Shells landed around the ports of Jounieh and Byblos, causing
damage but no casualties, the police spokesman said.
   Jounieh and Byblos have been the main destinations for ships
bringing food and fuel to the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
north and east of Beirut, which the Syrians and allied Moslem forces
have under siege.
   Aoun's 155mm made howitzers bombarded the Syrian artillery
emplacements in west Beirut, police said.
   Artillery and rocket exchanges began two days after Aoun imposed
a land and sea blockade on illegal ports run by Moslem militias.
Druse militiamen responded with artillery fire and Syria soon joined
the Druse.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate issued in 1976, the year after Lebanon's
sectarian civil war began. Aoun calls the Syrians an occupation army
and has sworn to drive them out.
   Because of a political crisis that arose last September, Lebanon
has two competing governments: a Christian one led by Aoun and a
Moslem Cabinet headed by Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</TEXT>
