<FIRST>u i PM-Mandela 2ndLd-Writethru a0602 07-18 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0602,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandela 71, Receives Family in Prison, Says He Won't Be Freed Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with more comments from Mrs. Mandela;
picks up 3rd pvs, `Mrs. Mandela...' Minor editing thereafter to TRIM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAARL, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black nationalist leader Nelson
Mandela says he will not be freed from prison this year, his wife,
Winnie, reported after a five-hour birthday visit today.
   ``His exact words were: `There will be no release, definitely not
this year,''' Mrs. Mandela told reporters outside the Victor Verster
prison farm north of Cape Town.
   The African National Congress leader, jailed for life for
plotting against white-minority rule, observed his 71st birthday
today with an unprecedented visit by 16 members of his family.
   His July 5 meeting with President P.W. Botha has sparked
speculation that the government might release him after September
parliamentary elections for whites, Indians and people of
mixed-race. The black majority of 28 million has no vote in national
affairs.
   Subsequent statements by spokesmen for Botha's National Party
suggested that the government was seeking a formula to free the ANC
leader as a prelude to possible white-black negotiations.
   Mrs. Mandela said that National Party leader F.W. de Klerk, who
is designated to succeed Botha as president after the elections was
``fully aware'' of the July 1 meeting. De Klerk has not commented on
it yet, and observers in South Africa had speculated that Botha,
facing forced retirement, took the action to upstage his successor.
   Mrs. Mandela said her husband's release has always been the last
item on his agenda. ``His own freedom is of no consequence. It is
the freedom of the people he went to prison for,'' she said.
   She said he had briefly touched on his meeting on Friday with
five African National Congress colleagues who were sentenced with
him in 1964 for founding and participating in activities of the
ANC's armed wing.
   She said he told her there was no specific significance to that
meeting but Mrs. Mandela added, ``Whatever Comrade Mandela does is
in full consultation with the leadership behind bars and the ANC
outside.''
   Mrs. Mandela and her daughter, Zindzi, wore black, underlining
the solemnity of the day that they had previously marked by fasting
and praying at home. Some relatives came from the United States, and
Mrs. Mandela said it was the first time Mandela's extended family
joined him since his arrest.
   Some family members wore symbols of the campaign for
black-majority rights.
   A grandson was draped in a vivid garland of roses and carnations
in yellow, black and red _ colors of the United Democratic Front,
South Africa's main anti-apartheid alliance before it was banned
last year.
   A son held up a fruit basket with ribbons in green, black and
yellow _ colors of the outlawed ANC guerrilla movement.
   About 20 supporters of Mandela shouted, ``Viva ANC!'' and, ``Viva
Mandela!'' as relatives arrived in five cars at the gates of the
prison farm. Mandela was transferred there from a Cape Town prison
after he recovered from tuberculosis last year.
   Well-wishers stood in the rain in near-freezing temperatures on
one of the coldest days in recent years.
   Mandela has been in prison since 1962, and he is serving a life
term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white government.
   Mrs. Mandela said she brought birthday cards and greetings from
various anti-apartheid groups, including United Democratic Front
affiliates and the National Union of Mineworkers.
</TEXT>
