<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Trade     07-18 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Gap Swells as America Brings in Record Imports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Budget, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday the U.S. trade
deficit widened sharply to $10.24 billion in May as America brought
in record imports, sold less goods abroad and lost ground in its bid
to shrink the trade gap.
   May's imbalance was the biggest in five months and represented a
23.6 percent increase over the $8.29 billion deficit registered in
April, when the nation had its smallest monthly trade gap in more
than four years.
   Analysts predicted April's figure was the low point for the year,
and said May's increase dealt a blow to hopes that the U.S. trade
deficit would improve significantly this year.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher called the latest report
disappointing but said he was ``encouraged by the continuing
strength of exports,'' which declined slightly in May from a record
high in April.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said the report was
``consistent with our expectation that the trade deficit will
continue to improve at a modest pace in 1989.''
   For the first five months of the year, the trade gap was running
at an annual rate of $111.1 billion, compared with an actual 1988
deficit of $118.53 billion. Last year's figure was a 22.1 percent
improvement over 1987.
   ``The trade deficit, over time and on average, is improving, but
only slowly,'' said economist Allen Sinai of the Boston Co. ``We are
light years away from anything resembling balance in our trade.''
   The nation's best chance for trade improvement ``probably awaits
a significant turn for the worse in the U.S. economy,'' which would
cause American businesses and consumers to purchase fewer imports,
he said.
   In May, imports shot up 4.3 percent to a record $40.71 billion,
boosted by a big increase in America's foreign oil bill and stronger
spending on foreign agricultural products, capital goods, and
industrial supplies.
   Petroleum imports surged 17.3 percent to $4.75 billion as both
the price and volume of foreign oil purchases rose. The average
price for a barrel of oil rose for the sixth straight month and
reached $18.40 in May; the volume of oil imports rose for the second
straight month to 8.33 million barrels a day.
   Exports, meanwhile, dropped off 0.9 percent to $30.47 billion,
reflecting slower foreign demand for U.S. products in almost every
major catogory, led by a 5.7 percent drop in purchases of
American-made consumer goods.
   Analysts said exports are likely to decline further as the
strength of the U.S. dollar against other currencies increases the
price of American goods on foreign markets.
   Economist Michael Evans, head of a Washington consulting firm,
said May's trade figure in part represented a bounceback from an
artificially low April deficit, but he predicted the monthly trade
figures are likely to gradually increase for the rest of the year.
   ``I wouldn't say this was just a fluke or that it's going to get
better again,'' Evans said. ``We are going to see pretty sluggish
exports this year, and that is the result of the higher dollar.''
   Bruce Steinberg, economist for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in
New York, said the United States might make some modest progress on
the trade gap later this year if the nation's slowing economy pulls
in fewer imports, but nothing like the $34 billion improvement
recorded in 1988.
   ``I would describe the trade environment as intractable,''
Steinberg said. ``It's difficult to get a lot more improvement than
we've seen.''
   The latest report showed increases in the U.S. trade imbalances
with most major trading partners.
   As usual, the United States posted its largest trade deficit in
May with Japan, a $4.28 billion shortfall that was up from $3.89
billion in April. The nation posted a small $78.3 million deficit
with Western Europe after registering surpluses in both March and
April.
   The imbalance with Canada, the largest U.S. trading partner, was
$739.3 million in May, up from $174.8 million in April. Other large
deficits in May were recorded with Taiwan, $1.09 billion; South
Korea, $503 million; and Mexico, $452 million.
</TEXT>
