<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Negotiator: Superpowers Make Progress But Treaty `Long Way Off'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with comments from U.S. chief negotiator
in disarmament talks. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The superpowers have made some recent progress
toward a global treaty banning chemical weapons but the chief U.S.
negotiator in the talks today said ``there is no reason to be
euphoric.''
   The New York Times reported in today's editions that the United
States and the Soviet Union have reached agreement on key elements
of a draft treaty that would ban the development, production,
possession and transfer of chemical weapons.
   Ambassador Max Friedersdorf, the head of the U.S. delegation to
the Geneva conference, told The Associated Press that some progress
was made in the latest round of U.S.-Soviet talks, ``but that's a
long way from completing a treaty.''
   Friedersdorf said the two sides agreed to a document on spot
inspections of chemical weapons sites, and the paper has been sent
to Washington for approval.
   But he called the issue ``just one aspect of the verification
problem,'' referring to the complex anti-cheating provisions widely
considered to be the most difficult issue in negotiations that began
more than 20 years ago.
   He also said agreement was reached earlier on a paper involving
exchange of data of the two superpopwers before the conclusion of a
treaty but that there were still ``fundamental differences'' on when
this information should be exchanged.
   ``Verification involves a lot more than the conduct of a
challenge inspection and bilateral data exchange,'' Friedersdorf
said. ''I dont think there is any reason to be euphoric.''
   The New York Times quoted a State Department official as saying
that the two sides had agreed in principle on ``a mathematical
formula'' prescribing the amounts and types of chemical weapons to
be destroyed over a 10-year period. But President Bush, national
security adviser Brent Scowcroft and White House chief of staff John
Sununu all said they had no information to confirm the Times' report.
   ``I'd like to see that (reported agreement) in writing before I
get euphoric about it,'' Bush told reporters aboard Air Force One en
route home from Europe this morning. `It would be a pleasant
surprise.''
   He said the problem of verifying compliance with the treaty ``is
what has thwarted an agreement all along.''
   The United States and the Soviet Union have the largest arsenals
of such weapons.
   The Geneva Protocol of 1925, adopted after poison gas in World
War I produced 1.3 million casualties, prohibits the use of chemical
weapons, but not their manufacture or stockpiling.
   Discussions on a chemical weapons treaty have been conducted on
and off in Geneva for eight years.
   The 40 members of the disarmament conferene include Iran, Egypt
and Morocco. Twenty-eight observers to the conference include Iraq,
Syria and Libya.
   Soviet authorities say they have no more than 55,000 tons of
chemical warfare agents, but Western intelligence agencies estimate
they might have as much as 300,000 tons.
</TEXT>
