<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     07-18 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Limps Toward Weekend Parliamentary Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the governing Liberal Democratic Party,
plagued by scandals and unpopular policies, gave bleak predictions
for this weekend's elections for the upper chamber of Parliament.
   Prime Minister Sosuke Uno, his image damaged by reports of a
relationship with a geisha, planned his first election appearances
outside the capital since the campaign began.
   ``I feel we hit bottom on Saturday,'' party Secretary-General
Ryutaro Hashimoto told reporters. ``Since then, things have been
looking up ... but I can't say there has been a change in the
overall mood.''
   Hashimoto said Liberal Democratic candidates have been hurt by
public anger over the Recruit influence-buying scandal, which forced
Uno's predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, to resign June 2, and by a new
3 percent consumption tax, which the party backed.
   Hashimoto, the party's No. 2 leader after Uno, refused to comment
on public opinion polls and media forecasts that suggest his party
will suffer a major loss of seats in the 252-member upper chamber in
the election Sunday.
   But the mass-circulation Mainichi Shimbun newspaper Tuesday
quoted senior party member Michio Watanabe as predicting the party
will win only 37 of the 126 contested upper house seats, falling
short of the 54 it needs to win to maintain a majority.
   Watanabe reportedly said the party will be defeated in rural
areas, where moves to open up Japan's agricultural markets have
alienated farmers, traditionally an important source of the party's
support.
   The Liberal Democrats, who have dominated Japanese politics since
1955, hold 66 of the contested seats and 73 more which are not up
for re-election until 1992. The leading opposition Socialist Party
has 43 upper house seats, 11 of which are being contested.
   A serious setback at the polls could force Uno to resign,
although he has said he hopes to remain in office until his term as
party president expires Oct. 31. Due to the party's majorities in
both houses of Parliament, the party president concurrently serves
as prime minister.
   After Uno's return Tuesday from the Paris economic summit, party
officials said he is scheduled to travel to Osaka in western Japan
for his first election-related appearance outside Tokyo since the
upper house campaigns began July 5.
   Party leaders have distanced Uno from campaigns because of
reports he paid a geisha to be his mistress for several months in
1985. Uno has denied doing anything immoral.
   In Osaka, Uno will speak at a local university and travel to
nearby Kyoto for meetings with business leaders. On Thursday, he
will visit his home constituency in Saga prefecture, also in western
Japan.
   Uno's wife, Chiyo, will attend a Liberal Democratic women's rally
in Yokohama, just south of Tokyo, on Wednesday, a local party
official said. Mrs. Uno has avoided comment on the geisha scandal,
but in one interview said she trusts her husband.
   Due to fears the sex scandal would cost votes, the party's Tokyo
chapter asked Uno to stay away from campaigns for the Tokyo
Metropolitan Assembly earlier this month. At one rally he did
attend, party supporters scuffled with women carrying
anti-prostitution placards and calling for him to resign.
   When campaigns for the upper house seats began, Uno gave only a
short speech in the parking lot of the party's Tokyo headquarters.
Before leaving for Paris, where he attended bicentennial ceremonies
of the French Revolution and the three-day summit meeting of major
industrialized countries, Uno made no campaign appearances and party
spokesmen said his future schedule had not been decided.
   In the Recruit Co. scandal, the publishing conglomerate sold
stock at cut-rate prices to politicians and bureaucrats it hoped to
influence. Stockholders made handsome profits after the stock went
public.
</TEXT>
