<FIRST>r w AM-KALFlight     07-18 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-KAL Flight,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Defending KAL Disputes Finding of Probe of Flight 007</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney defending Korean Air Lines on
Tuesday disputed an international investigation of Flight 007 which
found the plane was significantly off course for hours before it was
destroyed by the Soviet Union.
   In opening statements in a civil jury trial, George Tompkins
refused to concede that the KAL jumbo jet was off track so early. It
was blown out of the sky over Soviet air space in 1983 by a
heat-seeking missile, killing all 269 people aboard.
   The best evidence is that the crew of the KAL jumbo jet was
flying its correct route until shortly before it was destroyed on
Sept. 1, 1983, Tompkins said.
   Tompkins said the crew sent radioed position reports periodically
to Anchorage, Alaska, and Tokyo pinpointing the plane's location as
being on course for the first four hours of its flight.
   U.S. air traffic controllers who tracked the earliest parts of
Flight 007 before it went out of radar range reported nothing
abnormal, Tompkins said.
   Families of 132 of the passengers killed when Flight 007 was
destroyed are suing KAL, alleging willful misconduct by the plane's
crew and seeking to collect in excess of a $75,000-per-passenger
limit in damages imposed under international treaty.
   The last radioed position report, in which the crew said it was
on course over the North Pacific, was about an hour before the plane
was shot down.
   What happened after that, only the Soviet Union can answer
because its radar tracked the KAL 747 and it was Soviet planes that
``shadowed'' the jumbo jet and destroyed it, said Tompkins.
   ``It certainly was willful misconduct on the part of the
Russians,'' the lawyer for KAL said.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization, which probed the
disaster, concluded that Flight 007 was off course for nearly 5{
hours and intruded into Soviet territory for several hours before it
was shot down with at least one heat-seeking missile from a Soviet
fighter plane. The report's conclusions were based on data from the
U.S. government, Japan and the Soviet Union.
   Tompkins labeled as ``theory, ... conjecture, speculation'' the
explanation offered by families of the dead passengers that the
plane's crew knew it was off course shortly after leaving Anchorage,
Alaska, due to an error in programming a computerized navigation
system aboard the craft.
   Tompkins said there was no proof of any programming error by the
crew.
   The three-member crew didn't want to turn back to correct the
problem because it would have had to dump much of the plane's fuel
and face disciplinary action, suggest lawyers for families of the
victims. Therefore, the crew may have sent incorrect position
reports and navigated without the use of the shipboard computer
system, the families' lawyers have suggested.
   Flight 007's crew ``literally ran four straight red lights'' by
being off course at various position checkpoints, Donald Madole, an
attorney for the families, told the jury.
   The plane was more than 300 miles off track when it was shot
down, said Milton Sincoff, who also represents the families.
   ``How could an airplane get 300 miles off course if they were
following procedures?'' asked Madole.
   Tompkins said that if the highly experienced crew aboard Flight
007 had made an error in programming the pilot's navigation system,
it would been aware of it immediately.
   Tompkins disputed the families' contention that the plane would
have had to return to Anchorage, Alaska, to correct the problem,
saying ``you can update it in the air.'' A crew member would simply
have to ``reach up'' and ``throw a switch'' to a second automatic
pilot and the plane ``would have turned and gone back on the
course,'' Tompkins said.
   KAL lawyers have asked U.S. District Judge Aubrey Robinson to
limit presentation of the conclusions of the ICAO report on the
shootdown. Robinson said he would decide as the trial progresses
what material from the report may be introduced. He said any
analysis from the report the families' lawyers want to present to
the jury must be buttressed by an adequate factual foundation.
   Numerous pieces of wreckage from Flight 007 were recovered in the
Sea of Japan in the days following the shootdown, but the cockpit
voice recorder and flight data recorder were never pulled up from
the submerged wreckage of the plane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PhoneDemise Bjt   07-18 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Demise, Bjt,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Fighting To Save Depression-Era Phone System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH FORK, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progress is about to claim another piece
of history, the state's last crank telephone system, and cut off 18
customers who live in the rugged Salmon River canyon from the
outside world.
   But the North Fork Telephone Corp. customers strung along 31
miles of the wilderness river in isolated central Idaho are not
going to give up without a struggle.
   ``I don't know what's going to become of it, but I know the
people are not going to take it lying down,'' store owner Donna
Myers said Tuesday. ``They're going to fight for it.''
   The system's party-line users of crank-operated telephones
running on batteries and magnetos are linked to the world beyond by
a single wire connected to insulators hanging from rocks, poles and
trees. Such systems were common in rural America decades ago but
only a few still operate.
   They can ring each other, but calls to and from the outside must
go through a local operator. On incoming calls, the operator alerts
the proper customer with a coded ring _ Mrs. Myers is three longs.
   But earlier this month, the North Fork customers were notified
that the operator will no longer be so handy.
   The operator service based in Salmon, 20 miles to the southeast
by air, is handled by the local exchange company, Century Telephone
Co., under contract to AT&amp;T. On Dec. 15, AT&amp;T is consolidating
operator services for the area to Salt Lake City.
   Computerized switching equipment that will handle long-distance
calls for Century Telephone customers can't handle a ``ring down''
system like the North Fork's. Placing calls through the Salt Lake
operator would run up long-distance charges.
   Century manager Frank Barsalou said there's no reason to keep on
an operator ``because all they'd do is handle the (canyon) calls.''
   North Fork customers could hire their own operator, but it would
cost more than $1,600 a week for round-the-clock service.
   A study is being made to see if service hours could be curtailed
and a switcher, someone less skilled than an operator, hired to
route calls in and out of the canyon.
   Canyon residents are accustomed to living without electricity and
only seasonal running water. But Marsha Smith said the phone
announcement ``hit us so unexpectedly. We've always been assured we
would have this service.''
   A letter-writing campaign to public and telephone industry
officials has been started in hopes of bringing attention to the
problem.
   ``This old phone, it might have its ups and downs, but by golly
it's been a life-saver in a lot of cases,'' said Mrs. Myers. ``We
have things from people who were hurt and needed ambulances to cars
breaking down.''
   The system, originally used by the U.S. Forest Service, was
bought by the resident cooperative in 1952 when the government
switched to radio communications.
   Because the Salmon is a wilderness river in that area west of
North Fork, the Forest Service will not allow installation of new
above-ground telephone lines, and burying the phone cable has been
estimated to cost $600,000.
   But, Barsalou said, ``They're really not interested in a modern
system. They want to keep their old crank phones.''
   ``We would much rather have this for a wilderness area,'' said
North Fork vice president John Booker.
   Idaho Public Utilities Commissioner Perry Swisher believes
service can be saved if everyone cooperates until a technological
answer is found.
   ``What's bothered me, personally, is that I haven't seen much
imagination by the telecommunication people in how to get down that
canyon with service,'' Swisher said.
   Mrs. Myers thinks a solution will take some time, but ``one way
or another they're going to work it out. They all know we need that
phone system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-CoalStrike 3rdLd-Writethru a0627 07-18 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0627,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Sides Resume Talks In Pittston Coal Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts first 3 grafs to move up reference to mediator, date
of last talks; Picks up 4th graf, `The agreement ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUFFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers and The Pittston Co.
agreed today to resume contract talks under supervision of a
mediator in an effort to end a bitter strike that has idled
thousands of coal miners in several states.
   UMW President Richard Trumka and Pittston Vice President Joseph
Farrell signed an agreement to hold negotiations Wednesday morning
for the first time since June 8.
   Under the agreement, a federal mediator will meet with each side
separately and deliver proposals to the other party.
   The agreement also said Pittston can continue to claim that talks
are at an impasse, and the union can still claim that Pittston has
failed to bargain in good faith.
   The agreement was a result of a four-hour meeting with U.S.
District Judge Glenn Williams.
   In the coal fields, more than 4,000 UMW miners failed to report
for work at Alabama's two largest coal companies today, a day after
they ended a four-week walkout. But a union official told them to go
back for tonight's shift.
   Trumka was joined at the meeting by UMW Vice President Cecil
Roberts, District 28 President Jackie Stump, and Judith Scott and
Michael Buckner from the union's headquarters in Washington.
   Joining Odom at the table was Joseph Farrell, vice president for
The Pittston Co., the coal group's parent company.
   The walkout at Pittston, one of the few coal companies not to
sign a UMW contract last year, led to unauthorized sympathy walkouts
beginning last month that affected up to 46,000 miners in 10 states.
   Most of those miners have since gone back to work, but wildcat
strikes still affect several thousand miners in West Virginia, and
two mining companies in Alabama reported that about 4,000 miners
failed to show up this morning. A union official told them to go
back for tonight's shift.
   Negotiations between the two sides broke down June 8. The
governors of Virginia and West Virginia had issued similar offers to
mediate talks, but Pittston officials had declined them.
   About 1,900 UMW members are striking Pittston in a dispute over
benefits and job security issues. The strike began April 5 in
Virginia and West Virginia before spreading to Kentucky. Hundreds of
miners have been arrested for a variety of violent incidents as well
as civil disobedience tactics.
   Federal statistics released Friday gave an indication of how
wildcat strikes that began June 12 are affecting coal production.
   The data showed that during the third week of the walkout, coal
production had dropped by 57 percent in the eastern half of the
country and 42 percent nationally, compared with pre-strike levels.
   Some miners in southern West Virginia remained on wildcat strikes
today, awaiting the outcome of today's meeting. Trumka last Friday
asked the wildcat strikers to return to work, and most appeared to
be doing so on Monday.
   ``It was time to come back,'' said Ron Airhart, president of UMW
Local 1412 at Keystone Coal Mining Corp in Indiana County, Pa.
   ``We made an important statement. We got the country's attention.
Now we'll get to work again and hope we've made a difference.''
   ``They have a full complement of people out there today and
everything seems to have started up very well,'' said Carl Heldt,
director of human resources for Old Ben Coal Co. in Oakland City,
Ind.
   ``They're in good spirits. I've been told by the mine management
that people seemed delighted and eager to be there. They've been
without paychecks for about a month.''
   In West Virginia, pickets continued to idle mines.
   ``There were pickets out there today, scattered all over the
highway,'' said Fred Jarrell, president of Local 1330 at
Consolidation Coal Co.'s Rowland Mine in Raleigh County, about 60
miles southeast of Charleston.
   ``I stood up there yesterday and preached for two hours telling
people to go back to work. I don't think it did any good.''
   Some scattered violence was reported Monday in southern West
Virginia, with coal trucks serving non-union Elk Run Coal Co. in
Boone County hit by rocks and other projectiles.
   Mark Polen, vice president of the West Virginia Coal Association,
blamed a ``radical minority'' within the union for keeping the mines
idle, primarily in Charleston-based District 17, whose 8,000 working
members are among the most militant in the nation.
   ``District 17 is the root, as usual, of the problems,'' Polen
said.
   Some 200 Island Creek Coal Co. workers also were off the job in
western Kentucky on Monday evening, company spokeswoman Julie Accola
said. She did not immediately return a telephone call this morning
on whether they returned today.
   In Alabama, 4,000 miners failed to report for work at the state's
two largest coal companies, Jim Walter Resources and the Drummond
Co., just one day after they ended a four-week wildcat walkout,
company officials said today. Union officials declined to comment on
reports that the walkout stemmed from the firing of several miners.
</TEXT>
