<FIRST>r w AM-Deaver     07-18 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaver,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deaver, Citing $1 Million Legal Bill, Seeks to Reduce Fine to $25,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Michael K. Deaver,
citing a $1 million legal bill, is seeking to reduce to $25,000 the
$100,000 fine he was ordered to pay for lying under oath about his
lobbying business.
   But the independent counsel who had sought a prison term for
Deaver suggested the former White House aide could pay the fine by
selling his family's home at a large profit.
   Independent counsel Whitney North Seymour said that the value of
Deaver's house has risen from its 1985 purchase price of $990,000 to
$1.45 million.
   ``Any reduction in the fine should be viewed against the
background of the leniency the court has already exercised toward
this defendant,'' Seymour said in response to the request Deaver
made last month.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who imposed the
$100,000 fine and ordered Deaver to perform 1,500 hours of community
service, has not ruled on the defense request.
   In their June 16 filing, defense lawyers said Deaver had not made
any payments on the fine because his expenses _ which include an
$8,250 monthly mortgage payment _ continue to exceed his income.
   Until he recently took a public relations job, which pays $6,500
a month, Deaver was ``without virtually any means of support for his
family other than borrowing money against his home to pay for
monthly living expenses,'' the defense said.
   Deaver, who was deputy White House chief of staff for President
Reagan until 1985, also has legal bills of more than $1 million
resulting from the investigation and prosecution that ruined his
lobbying business, the defense said.
   As a condition of probation, Jackson barred Deaver for lobbying
the government for profit for three years.
   Deaver, a close friend of the former president and his wife
Nancy, was convicted of three felony counts of lying to a House
subcommittee and a federal grand jury that investigated his lobbying
business for possible ethics-law violations.
   Seymour, who disclosed that federal probation officers suggested
that Deaver be sentenced up to 10 months in prison, said the former
lobbyist was ``in a better position to pay the fine than he was at
the time it was imposed.''
   ``Among other things, Deaver is now earning a healthy salary,
which was not true when this court imposed the sentence in question
here,'' Seymour said in his June 22 court filing.
   But the prosecutor said the appreciation of the value of Deaver's
house by $460,000 was ``the most significant disclosure'' in the
financial statement submitted to the judge.
   Deaver's share of the equity in his home ``more than doubled''
since his sentencing ``in an ammount more than sufficient to pay off
the fine in full,'' Seymour said.
   The defense said in a reply to Seymour's filing that ``it is
extremely doubtful that Mr. Deaver's home would bring anything near
its appraised value in today's real estate market, especially if he
was forced to sell.''
   Defense lawyers said ``Deaver's fine should be reduced to an
amount that, while substantial, can be paid without requiring him to
sell his home or go substantially further into debt.''
   Besides his outstanding legal fees, Deaver must pay the balance
of his $871,464 mortgage in three years, the defense said. His
monthly expenses are more than $12,000.
   The financial statement attached to Deaver's court filing did not
detail the earnings of his wife, Carolyn, who works as a real estate
agent.
   Deaver, who abandoned efforts to appeal his case earlier this
year, has begun counseling alcoholics at a downtown shelter for the
homeless.
   Under the terms of Jackson's order, Deaver, a recovering
alcoholic, will be required to spend nights and weekends at the
shelter. Deaver's work involves interviewing prospective patients
for the 25-bed clinic, leading Alcoholics Anonymous meetings, and
counseling individuals.
   He is also helping a Georgetown University medical professor
devise a course to teach medical students to spot the symptoms of
alcoholism.
   Deaver declined through his attorney, Randall J. Turk, to discuss
his community service, saying publicity would jeopardize his
attempts to win the trust of the street alcoholics he is counseling.
</TEXT>
