<HEAD>April and May Trade Figures with Selected U.S. Trading Partners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at trade figures for May with
selected U.S. trading partners, compared with the April figures.
   A deficit means that imports from the country exceeded U.S.
export sales. A surplus means that American exports were larger than
imports.
   Canada: May deficit of $739.3 million, compared with April
deficit of $174.8 million.
   Japan: May deficit of $4.28 billion, compared with April deficit
of $3.89 billion.
   Britain: May deficit of $52.6 million, compared with April
surplus of $450.9 million.
   West Germany: May deficit of $530.8 million, compared with April
deficit of $718.5 million.
   Total for Western Europe: May deficit of $78.3 million, compared
with April surplus of $231.5 million.
   Taiwan: May deficit of $1.09 billion, compared with April deficit
of $840.4 million.
   South Korea: May deficit of $503 million, compared with April
deficit of $544.6 million.
   Hong Kong: May deficit of $223.9 million, compared with April
deficit of $32.9 million.
   Singapore: May deficit of $213.2 million, compared with April
deficit of $129.3 million.
   Total for four newly industrialized countries: May deficit of
$2.03 billion, compared with April deficit of $1.55 billion.
   Mexico: May deficit of $452 million, compared with April deficit
of $318.2 million.
   Soviet Union: May surplus of $401.4 million, compared with April
surplus of $395.4 million.
   China: May deficit of $461.6 million, compared with April deficit
of $323.3 million.
