<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Strikes     07-18 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Strikes,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikes Halt Trains, Subways and Royal Carriage Procession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes shut down the railways, London subway, 37
ports, city libraries and day-care centers Tuesday, and even caused
Queen Elizabeth II to cancel a royal carriage procession for a
visiting Arab leader.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government, trying to reduce
the 8 percent annual inflation rate, faces labor unrest from local
government employees, longshoremen, bus mechanics, ambulance crews
and others seeking seeking higher pay and other concessions.
   Two royal parks, Hyde Park and Regent's Park, were turned into
emergency parking lots for commuters suffering through the fifth
one-day railway and subway strike in five weeks. Trains and subways
carry nearly 5 million daily.
   Peak traffic periods started at 5:30 a.m. and midafternoon,
causing huge traffic jams on some routes.
   Sheik Zayed bin Sultan al-Nahyan, president of the United Arab
Emirates, began a four-day state visit without the splendor of the
customary royal carriage procession to Buckingham Palace. The queen
called off the glittering procession because it would have closed
some of London's busiest roads.
   The sheik traveled from Heathrow Airport in a fleet of
limousines, battling heavy traffic, but arrived at the palace on
time.
   On Monday night, the 75,000-member National Union of Railwaymen
rejected a revised 8.8 percent raise offer from state-owned British
Rail. The 17,500-member Associated Society of Locomotive Engineers
and Firemen had accepted the offer, which was increased from 7
percent, earlier in the day.
   In the House of Commons, Mrs. Thatcher castigated the socialist
Labor Party for not criticizing the striking rail workers. The
opposition party ``would rather inconvenience the consumer and
traveling public,'' she declared.
   Michael Meacher, the Labor spokesman on employment, said
government threats to ban strikes against essential public services
threatened ``fundamental democratic rights.''
   Rail workers are among Britain's lowest-paid industrial
employees. Average earnings, including overtime, are $471 a week for
drivers and $325 for others.
   The 10,500 striking London subway workers want a weekly raise of
$102 to operate subway trains without conductors. Management has
offered $48 plus extra vacation.
   Ports management said Tuesday a strike of 9,400 longshormen that
began at 60 ports July 10 was crumbling. Iain Dale, spokesman for
the National Association of Port Employers, said 23 of the ports
were operating normally.
   Dock workers are striking because the government abolished a
guaranteed-work plan in force at the 60 ports since 1947. Britain's
other 102 ports are not affected by the strike.
   More than 500,000 members of the National and Local Government
Officers Association began a three-day strike Tuesday, halting
municipal services that range from care for children and the elderly
to local tax offices, museums and libraries.
   Union leaders agreed Tuesday to informal talks tentatively set
for Thursday. The employees earn an average of $16,000 a year. They
want a 12 percent pay raise and have been offered 7 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
