<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-18 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even in this day of runaway home prices,
Larry Austin can't give his house away.
   Austin wants the three-room bungalow off his lot to make room for
a new mobile home, so he put an ad in a local newspaper offering the
20-by-30-foot building free to anyone willing to have it moved.
   Five hundred people have called and at least 50 have looked at
the house in the outskirts of Augusta, but there have been no
takers, Austin said Tuesday. Perhaps its the estimated $2,500 moving
cost.
   ``Some people want me to move it, or pay them $1,000 to take
it,'' Austin said. ``I say `Jeezum, I'm giving it away.'''
   The house, which was built in the 1940s as part of a cedar
shingle mill, has been home to Austin, his wife, Tari, and their two
daughters for 10 years.
   Although it has a sagging roof and the floor is less than level,
Austin says it has new wiring and good plumbing. ``It was cozy, it
was warm, it was dry,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten pounds of chocolate chip cookies and
many persuasive letters later, Carolyn Goldston got her wish when
her 25th anniversary was mentioned in the nationally syndicated
comic strip ``Pogo.''
   Pogo and Porky Pine were shown in Monday's strip lying in their
boat discussing the hot weather. On the side of the boat are the
words ``A silver for the Goldstons.''
   Mrs. Goldston campaigned for several months to persuade ``Pogo''
writer Larry Doyle and artist Neal Sterneky to send a special
anniversary message to her husband.
   ``First she wrote a very funny letter, and said she'd send
cookies,'' Doyle seid. ``We asked what kind, and we proceeded to get
about 10 pounds of chocolate chip. Please tell her not to send any
more _ we're getting fat.''
   Mrs. Goldston said that in her letters to Doyle and artist Neal
Sterneky she used enough insider jokes and reference to show that
she was a dedicated fan. In fact being fans of the original ``Pogo''
strip helped draw the couple together in the 1960s, she said.
   ``I don't want anybody to think they can get on the boat by
that,'' Doyle said. ``This is the one time we put an anniversary on
the boat, and we won't be doing it again.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a player goes under in this Monopoly game, it
doesn't necessarily mean he's lost.
   That's because the contestants are scuba divers taking part in a
marathon relay attempt to set a record for underwater Monopoly. The
game, being played in a cylindrical tank 10 feet deep and 10 feet in
diameter, is set to last 50 days, ending during the Jerry Lewis
telethon for muscular dystrophy on Labor Day.
   ``We'd played the game for 48 hours last November, and I thought
48 hours would be plenty for a world's record,'' said Bob Evans,
president of Venture Out, one of the Atlanta dive shops helping with
the record attempt. ``Then I found a dive club in Buffalo, N.Y., had
gone 48 days.''
   Volunteer divers must line up at least $50 in pledged donations
to join a game. They play on a weighted table, with the board
laminated to the top, and plastic-encased money and cards for Chance
and Community Chest.
   ``Physically, it's no problem at all, other than getting prune
fingers, and hungry,'' a slightly wobbly Rebecca Steele of Smyrna
said after a three-hour stint at the game board.
</TEXT>
