<FIRST>r a AM-AntarcticaExpedition 2ndLd-Writethru a06Wewon'tknowthecauseuntilthetankistotallyoutofservice
07-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antarctica Expedition, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0639,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antarctic Expedition Sled Dog Dies of Apparent Heat Stroke</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT this would be first unmechanized
crossing of Antarctica sted first unmechanized attempt.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of 42 sled dogs from the International
Trans-Antarctica Expedition died of apparent heat stroke in Havana
after the air conditioning failed on the expedition's Soviet
airplane.
   The dog named Apak was found dead in his cargo box Monday as the
animals were being taken to a zoo for temporary keeping, expedition
spokeswoman Cathy Saypol said Tuesday. Apak, who died Monday was one
of six reserve pullers being taken as backups to the expedition's 36
first-string sled dogs.
   ``The other 41 dogs were moved to a zoo in Havana and are doing
fine,'' Saypol, who spoke with expedition organizer Will Steger,
said from her New York office.
   ``It's not a good way of starting,'' Steger, of Ely, Minn., told
a St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch reporter traveling with the
expedition. ``It's the worst thing that could happen outside of
losing a person. It's a shame for the dog, and it's a shame for the
expedition.''
   The expedition originally had planned only a brief refueling stop
in Havana before flying on to Lima, Peru, where the weather is
cooler. However, the plane was held over in Havana for work on the
same problems that delayed the flight's departure from
Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport by five hours Sunday.
   The air conditioning broke down at the Havana airport and
handlers took the dogs to a cool spot at the zoo to escape humid
weather with a high temperature of 87 degrees.
   Steger and an international team of explorers plan to stop in
Peru, Argentina and Chile before finally landing in Antarctica to
start its seven-month, 4,000-mile trip across the bottom of the
world on Aug. 1.
   Others have crossed Antarctica on snowmobiles and giant snow
tractors, but if it succeeds, this would be the first unmechanized
crossing.
   The team members are Steger, co-leader Jean-Louis Etienne of
France, Soviet scientist Victor Boyarsky, Englishman Geoff Somers,
Keizo Funatsu of Japan, and Qin Dahe of China.
</TEXT>
