<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela     07-18 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC Leader Tells Family He Won't Be Released This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAL1,CPN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAARL, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid leader Nelson Mandela
told his family during a five-hour birthday reunion Tuesday that he
won't be freed from prison this year, his wife said.
   ``His exact words were: `There will be no release, definitely not
this year,' '' Winnie Mandela said outside the Victor Verster prison
farm north of Cape Town, where the black African National Congress
leader is held.
   Some of the 16 members of Mandela's family who observed his 71st
birthday gave black power salutes as they walked out the prison
gates, where about 50 youths chanted ``Viva Mandela!'' and sang
songs in the intermittent rain and near-freezing cold.
   ``On his personal agenda his release will be the last item,''
Mrs. Mandela said. ``He wants freedom for his political views.''
   She said he had asked for more freedom to discuss political
matters with other leaders and wanted contact with black trade union
officials.
   ``Whatever Comrade Mandela does is in full consultation with the
leadership behind bars and the ANC outside,'' she said.
   It was the 26th birthday Mandela has spent behind bars since his
arrest Aug. 5, 1962, and the first one he has spent with his family.
He is serving a life prison term, imposed in 1964, for sabotage and
plotting to overthrow the government.
   Mandela's July 5 meeting with President P.W. Botha had sparked
widespread speculation the government might release him after Sept.
6 parliamentary elections, in which the black majority of 28 million
have no vote.
   Mrs. Mandela also said National Party leader F.W. de Klerk,
designated to succeed Botha after the elections, was ``fully aware
of the meeting.''
   Some South African observers had interpreted de Klerk's lack of
comment as a sign that Botha, facing forced retirement, may have
held the meeting to upstage his successor.
   The family gathering included Mandela's wife, two sisters, his
son, two daughters, eight grandchildren, a great-grandson and
daughter-in-law. They came from the United States, Swaziland, the
black township of Soweto near Johannesburg, and the Xhosa tribal
homeland where Mandela was born.
   Makaziwe Mandela-Amuah, Mandela's daughter by his first marriage,
brought her three children to see her father, including her
4-year-old son Kweku who had never seen his grandfather.
   ``Although he stays in his own house he is still a prisoner and
we would like to see him free very soon,'' said Mrs. Mandela-Amuah,
who came from Massachusetts, where she is seeking a doctorate in
anthropology at Amherst College.
   ``He will be lonely, but he will be happy that he saw us all,''
she said. ``It will carry him through the rest of the year.''
   Mrs. Mandela said her husband told her there was no specific
significance to his meeting Friday with five African National
Congress colleagues who were sentenced with him in 1964 for founding
and participating in activities of the ANC's armed wing.
</TEXT>
