<FIRST>r w AM-FarmEconomist     07-18 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Economist,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hosemann Sees Threat to Growth of Agriculture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal regulatory noose threatens to choke
future growth of U.S. agriculture, an American Farm Bureau
Federation economist said Tuesday.
   John K. Hosemann of Chicago said it is not enough to have sound
monetary, tax and trade policies and then ``have a regulatory
apparatus that is going in the opposite direction by jacking up the
U.S. cost of producing food and fiber.''
   Hosemann's remarks were in a speech prepared for a meeting of the
National Economists Club at the Brookings Institution.
   ``Cases in point, farmers have been whipsawed by consumer scares
about nitrates in bacon, salmonella in chicken and milk, to Alar in
apples,'' he said. ``All of these with little conclusive scientific
basis but costly to farmers nonetheless.''
   Hosemann said that each of the scares has ``fanned the fire''
that the U.S. food system is unsafe.
   ``To the extent that all of the hype over water and food purity
leads to restrictions on the production and resource decisions by
farmers, we are not likely to become a growth industry,'' he said.
   ``Right now,'' he added, ``decisions are being made in this town
about the next farm law that are very likely to increase the
farmers' cost of doing business. ``We do not have research to
respond to the simple question: Can U.S. farmers compete
internationally under alternative environmental restrictions on the
use of farm resources?''
   Hosemann said his views were personal and not the official views
of the federation.
   A new farm bill should keep the American farmer competitive in
the world market and avoid go-it-alone decisions for curbing
production, he said. The United States also should keep fighting the
European Economic Community and Japan for market access.
   Hosemann urged also that monetary, fiscal, trade and regulatory
policies be ``consistent with economic growth.''
   ``If I have a central message, it is that farming always has been
and always will be a lot more than the price of hogs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
