<HEAD>Nationalist Leader Claims Self-Defense in Shootout With FBI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIO GHIGLIOTTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a Puerto Rican
nationalist began Tuesday with the defendant saying he shot an FBI
agent to protect himself and his homeland.
   Filiberto Ojeda Rios, who took his own defense in federal court,
called the Aug. 30, 1985, FBI operation to arrest him an assault
``against a Puerto Rican home and against the Puerto Rican people.''
   However, he also said he acted in self-defense to save ``my life
and that of my wife.''
   He is charged with wounding Abelardo Alba, one of 15 FBI agents
who came to arrest him in Luquillo, Puerto Rico, for his suspected
role in a 1983 robbery of $7 million from a Wells Fargo depot in
Hartford, Conn.
   If convicted of the assault charge, he faces a maximum sentence
of 60 years in jail.
   Ojeda Rios, self-proclaimed head of the pro-independence,
clandestine Macheteros group, did not deny shooting the FBI agent
but said he was ``prudent and reasonable'' in doing so. He said the
FBI ``invaded his town with agents dressed like World War II
commandos.''
   Federal Prosecutor Daniel Lopez Romo said the federal officials
were clearly identified as FBI agents.
   Lopez Romo said the agents only shot two rounds when Ojeda Rios
raised his Uzi submachinegun to shoot. Ojeda Rios was not injured in
the exchange.
   Ojeda Rios protested to Judge Carmen Consuelo Vargas that federal
agents forced him to strip naked for a search just before the trial
began.
   The trial was expected to last at least two weeks.
