<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     07-18 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC's All-Star Game First in Ratings As Fox Moves Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's coverage of professional baseball's
All-Star Game topped the weekly Nielsen television ratings, and Fox
Broadcasting broke its viewing records to finish ahead of ABC on
Sunday night.
   The first-place game on NBC was closely followed by ABC's
``Roseanne,'' which was second for the week ending July 16. Both
were on Tuesday night but were in direct competition only in the
eastern United States.
   ``Roseanne'' and ABC's ``Wonder Years,'' both of which had
suffered the week before because of the Fourth of July, bounced back
into the Top 10.
   Fox was third in the ratings for Sunday night, coming in behind
NBC and CBS and surpassing one of the three major networks for an
entire night for the first time.
   Fox's ``Married ... With Children'' moved up to 23rd place and
``America's Most Wanted'' was 29th. Both shows had a 21 percent
share of the audience, the highest share level in Fox history.
   ``Totally Hidden Video,'' plagued by controversy and a lawsuit
after its record-breaking debut on Fox last week, fell from 21st to
34th place. Its rating, however, was off less than a point. Fox had
replaced several segments of the hidden camera show when it was
learned actors had been used. The network also fired the producer.
Allen Funt of ``Candid Camera'' filed suit on grounds that some of
the stunts were taken from his show.
   NBC posted its 56th week of domination of the prime-time ratings.
NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. chart with an average of 12.0.
CBS was second with 8.9 and ABC was third with 8.6.
   Ratings signify the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million
homes in the United States with television. The share is the
percentage of sets in use.
   Here is a list of the Top 10: NBC's All-Star Baseball Game; ABC's
``Roseanne;'' NBC's ``Cheers;'' NBC's ``A Different World;'' NBC's
``The Cosby Show;'' NBC's ``The Golden Girls'' and ABC's ``Wonder
Years,'' tied; NBC's ``Empty Nest;'' CBS' ``60 Minutes;'' and CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote.''
   ABC had the highest-rated evening news show with 8.8. CBS was
second with 8.6 and NBC was third with 7.9.
   Nearly all the Fox shows have moved up in the ratings, so that
only ``Cops in Russia'' and ``The Reporters'' placed in the overall
five lowest-rated shows.
   The lowest-rated show was NBC's ``Jim Henson Hour.'' The bottom
five among only the three major networks were: CBS' ``48 Hours,''
ABC's ``Incredible Sunday,'' CBS' ``Beauty and the Beast,'' ABC's
``Have Faith'' and NBC's ``Jim Henson Hour.''
</TEXT>
