<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ChemicalWeapons     07-18 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Weapons,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Progress on Banning Chemical Weapons Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Soviet Union have reached
agreement on key issues for a chemical weapons ban, officials said
Tuesday, but they also said a global treaty is not at hand.
   Ambassador Max Friedersdorf, the head of the U.S. delegation to
the 40-nation Conference on Disarmament, told The Associated Press
in Geneva that the superpowers made progress in the latest round of
talks, but ``that's a long way from completing a treaty.''
   Added Friedersdorf: ``I don't think there is any reason to be
euphoric.''
   At the State Department, spokesman Richard Boucher said the two
nations, which have the world's largest arsenals of chemical
weapons, are holding bilateral discussions on technical issues
relating to a worldwide ban.
   Their recommendations will be given to the multinational
conference which has been meeting in Switzerland on and off for the
past eight years.
   Boucher said Russian and American negotiators have settled
differences on spot inspections of chemical weapons sites and on the
order in which weapons would be destroyed over a 10-year period,
once a treaty goes into effect.
   Negotiators have arrived at ``joint texts'' ready for review in
the two capitals on those issues, Boucher said. Friedersdorf said
the paper on inspections has already been sent to Washington for
review.
   ``While these discussions have been productive ... there have
been no major breakthroughs and much work remains to be done,''
Boucher said.
   The New York Times, which first reported progress on the talks,
quoted an unidentified State Department official as saying the two
sides have agreed in principle on a ``mathematical formula''
prescribing the amounts and types of chemical weapons to be
destroyed over a decade.
   The task of verifying compliance with the treaty is widely
considered the most difficult task facing negotiators.
   Inspections are part of verification, but Friedersdorf said,
``verification involves a lot more than the conduct of a challenge
inspection and bilateral data exchange.''
   President Bush, who has long supported a ban on chemical weapons,
told reporters aboard Air Force One on his way back from Europe that
verifying compliance ``is what has thwarted an agreement all along.''
   Bush said he had yet to see any draft agreements, but any
progress ``would be a pleasant surprise.''
   Officials said the superpowers have yet to resolve differences on
the exchange of data. Boucher said the two sides are discussing how
far in advance of a treaty agreement they should begin to provide
each other with information.
   The Geneva Protocol of 1925, adopted after poison gas in World
War I caused 1.3 million casualties, prohibits the use of chemical
weapons, but not their manufacture or stockpiling.
   The 40 members of the disarmament conference include Iran, and
the 28 observers include Iraq, Syria and Libya, all of which are
thought to have chemical weapons capabilities.
   For any treaty to be effective, Boucher said, a ``substantial
number, all the major players, would have to be part of this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
