<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-ForeignPolicy 1stLd-Writethru a06estimes''sayslujan
07-18 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Foreign Policy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Seeks To Limit Presidential Flexibility</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 1 graf with party breakdown of vote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled Senate, reflecting
lingering political fallout from the Iran-Contra affair, voted
Tuesday to forbid a president from soliciting foreign or private
funds to carry out foreign policy activities prohibited by Congress.
   The amendment, sponsored by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
passed 57 to 42. Moynihan said the aim was to bar government
officials from bending to pressure from superiors to conduct
activities outlawed by Congress.
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., voting on the losing side,
protested that the amendment ``is a clear, bald effort to usurp the
foreign policy prerogatives of the president of the United States in
a manner not allowed by the Constitution.'' He predicted that
President Bush will veto it.
   The provision, attached to pending legislation authorizing $4.6
billion in spending for the State Department and allied agencies,
would make violators subject to fines and jail terms of up to five
years.
   Testimony before the congressional Iran-Contra committees showed
that the Reagan administration had solicited millions of dollars
from American citizens, and from such nations as Saudi Arabia and
Brunei, to circumvent a congressional ban on direct U.S. aid to the
Contra rebels battling the Marxist government of Nicaragua.
   One-time presidential aide Oliver L. North testified that he had
helped arrange such unofficial assistance to the Contras.
   ``This amendment can be summed up in three words: `Obey the
law'!'' said Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine.
   Mitchell noted that Helms contends the president is fully
empowered to pursue his policies by indirect means even when
Congress has outlawed a direct approach using U.S. government funds.
   ``The president of the United States is constrained by law just
as is any American citizen,'' Mitchell said in disagreement.
   ``This is a democracy, not a monarchy. The president is not a
king,'' he said.
   ``This is a modest, reasonable response to ensure there will be
compliance with law,'' Mitchell said. ``It will prevent officials of
the government from having to choose between loyalty to the
president and loyalty to the Constitution. This amendment says that
if the law prohibits an act, it is prohibited indirectly as well as
directly.''
   But Helms replied: ``The opposition to this amendment can be
summed up in three words: `Obey the Constitution'!''
   He said that Bush would be fully justified in vetoing the measure.
   Helms contended that in foreign policy issues Congress has the
power only of the purse, with the ability to cut off government
funds for a given activity. But Congress cannot bar a president from
pursuing foreign policy by other means, he said.
   Voting for the amendment were 53 Democrats and four Republicans.
One Democrat and 41 Republicans opposed it. One senator did not vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
