<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Escape     07-18 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Escape,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Somoza Supporters Crowd Airport, Desperate to Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Wells, now AP bureau chief in Bogota,
Colombia, reported from Managua in the last stages of the Nicaraguan
civil war.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista guerrillas were infiltrating Managua and their main
forces were only miles away.
   Anastasio Somoza had fled and those who had supported his
family's 42-year-old dynasty were desperate to do the same.
   The daily flight to Miami by the national airline Lanica, which
Somoza owned, was the only way out unless, like the departed
dictator, you had a private jet.
   Pandemonium reigned at Las Mercedes Airport. Hundreds of people
crowded around the airline counter, trying to get onto the daily
Boeing 707 flight to Miami.
   The discreet custom of slipping money to a Lanica employee for
preferential treatment had been cast aside along with normal
manners. People cursed, shouted, shoved and cried, waving handfuls
of dollars in the air to attract the attention of anyone who could
help.
   Standing quietly, apparently unworried and surrounded by more
suitcases than anyone else, was the president of Somoza's central
bank. He boarded the aircraft later, turning at the door with a wave
and slight smile to someone in the terminal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
