<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Jews     07-18 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Jews,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Officials Say They're Disturbed by Jewish Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic officials said Tuesday they
were disturbed by Jewish protests at a convent operated by Carmelite
nuns beside the site of the Auschwitz concentration camp. They also
said the convent would be moved.
   But the officials, in their first response to the demonstrations,
did not say when the convent would be relocated as Jewish leaders
are demanding.
   In Rome, leaders of a Jewish group met with Vatican officials
Tuesday and asked that Pope John Paul II intervene in the dispute.
They said their request was refused.
   The group also met with the Polish ambassador to seek the Polish
government's aid in the dispute.
   Poland's official PAP news agency quoted Bronislaw Fidelus,
deputy to Cardinal Franciszek Macharski of Krakow, as saying, ``The
Catholic community of the Krakow diocese is disturbed by the
incidents'' at the convent.
   ``It is difficult to accept that the two latest incidents were
led by a high official in the Jewish clergy,'' Fidelus said.
   On Friday, an American rabbi and six students held a five-hour
sit-in at the convent grounds. They said the protest ended when
convent workmen kicked and punched them and dragged them from the
grounds. No serious injuries were reported.
   The rabbi, Avraham Weiss of the Hebrew Institute in New York,
returned with four students Sunday. That protest ended four hours
later without incident.
   In their remarks Tuesday, church officials did not mention
Friday's scuffle.
   A church statement, carried by PAP, said land had been purchased
for a religious center farther from the death camp.The relocation
would be in line with an agreement reached by 18 international
Catholic and Jewish leaders, but the statement did not way when the
move might begin.
   Fidelus said, ``In the center there will be room, both spiritual
and physical, for the Carmelite sisters, and for any other
initiatives which will together show the religious dimension of the
memory of the Auschwitz tragedy.''
   The agreed-upon date for moving the convent from a former Nazi
warehouse that is within feet of the Auschwitz guard towers passed
Feb. 22 without any action.
   Fidelus said work on the center was about to start on a tract in
the same town of Oswiecim but away from the grounds of Auschwitz.
   An estimated 4 million people, including 2.5 million Jews,
perished at the Auschwitz camp from 1940 to 1945. About 6 million
Jews were killed in the Nazi Holocaust.
   Many Jews consider the convent an affront to the memory of the
Jews who died in Auschwitz.
   In Rome, one of the Jewish leaders who met with Vatican officials
criticized elements in the Catholic church in Poland, a
predominantly Roman Catholic country.
   ``There are some elements in the church in Poland that don't want
to settle this problem,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier. ``What is at stake
is much more than a small issue, but the entire 40-year dialogue
between the church and the Jewish people. It cannot be looked upon
as a local matter.''
   The Jewish officials who went to Rome belong to the Los
Angeles-based Simon Wiesenthal Center, which focuses on Holocaust
issues.
   They said they had sought the help of the Polish-born pope in
moving the convent.
   ``They (Vatican officials) told us the pope has made the decision
to absent himself from deliberations and that the issue should be
settled by the church in Poland,'' said Hier, who serves as dean of
the Simon Wiesenthal Center.
   Hier and three other group leaders met with Monsignor Luigi
Gatti, an official in the Vatican Secretariat of State, and
Monsignor Gerard Daucourt of the Vatican's office for relations with
Jews.
   Vatican officials confirmed the meeting took place but released
no details.
   ``The meeting was basically very disappointing,'' Hier said. ``It
was very frustrating to learn that the one person who can settle the
problem _ the pope _is not involved by his own decision.''
   The Jewish officials also said they met Tuesday with Josef
Wiegacz, Poland's ambassador in Rome, and asked for the Polish
governement to press the church on the convent issue.
   The Polish Embassy made no immediate statement about the meeting.
</TEXT>
