<FIRST>r w AM-VegetablePlantings     07-18 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vegetable Plantings,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Boost Acreage of Major Crops for Processing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vegetable farmers have boosted the acreage of
major crops for processing sharply this summer but have cut back
slightly on those grown for fresh market sales, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday.
   The planted acreage for five major processing crops was estimated
at 1.52 million acres, up 14 percent from last year when drought
reduced the harvest.
   Cucumber acreage for pickles was reported up 15 percent from
1988, while green peas were said to be up 12 percent. Increases were
also reported for snap beans, 22 percent; sweet corn, 8 percent; and
tomatoes, 14 percent.
   Fresh market plantings for harvest this summer included broccoli,
unchanged from last year; carrots, up 6 percent; cauliflower, down 3
percent; celery, down fractionally; sweet corn, down 1 percent;
lettuce, down 2 percent; and tomatoes, down 2 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
