<FIRST>r w AM-SoybeanQuality     07-18 0086</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soybean Quality,80</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Hurt by Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought took a toll of soybean quality last
year, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The department's Federal Grain Inspection Service said in an
annual report that only 14 percent of the 1988 soybeans sampled
graded U.S. No. 1, compared with 20 percent in 1987.
   Split beans, damaged kernels and foreign material also were up
significantly, the report said. The agency based its findings on a
survey of 5,449 random samples of last year's soybean crop.
</TEXT>
