<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1719EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-InfantMortality     07-18 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Mortality,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infant Mortality Could Be Curbed, Commission says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's high rate of infant deaths could
be cut, along with million of dollars spent to care for premature
babies, with a community-based program of home visitors, said a
report Tuesday by a government commission.
   The National Commission to Prevent Infant Mortality envisions a
system based on those used extensively in other countries in which
health visitors visit pregnant women in their homes to instruct them
in good prenatal care and offer support services, such as driving
them to doctor's appointments.
   The cost of a ``resource mother'' could be as low as $100 per
pregnancy, compared with $30,000 and more to care for a baby born
prematurely _ and $400,000 and more in that child's lifetime for
medical care and special services, said former Sen. Lawton Chiles,
D-Fla., chairman of the commission.
   ``We are currently operating under a misguided principle _ we
have developed the best medicine in the world to care for babies
born too early and too small,'' Chiles said in a statement
accompanying the report.
   ``Home health visitors would let us work at the front end to
prevent these babies from being born at risk,'' he said.
   An estimated one-third of all pregnant women receive inadequate
prenatal care, the commission said. In 1986, more than 70,000
pregnant women received no prenatal care at all.
   Inadequate pre-natal care is linked to high rates of infant
deaths and low birthweight babies, who are 40 times more likely to
die in their first month of life and two to three times more likely
to develop chronic, handicapping conditions, the commission said.
   A House measure includes about $14 million in fiscal 1990 for
development of new home visiting programs and support for existing
programs. Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., said he plans to offer an
amendment that would earmark $15 million to $20 million for home
visiting programs.
   Under a home visiting program, women in a community would be
trained and paid a minimum wage to go to the homes of pregnant teens
and women in their community and instruct them on the importance of
prenatal care _ including good nutrition and quitting smoking and
drug use.
   Such programs are used extensively in European countries, all of
which have lower infant mortality rates than the United States,
which ranks 19th among industrialized nations in the world, the
commission said.
   An estimated 4,500 home visiting programs are operating in the
United States, many funded by churches and community organizations.
</TEXT>
