<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     07-18 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Declare Rehearsal A Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five astronauts boarded the space
shuttle Columbia on Tuesday to wrap up a two-day dress rehearsal of
next month's planned launch that turned up no significant problems,
NASA officials said.
   The test allowed shuttle workers to check the shuttle's
electrical systems at the launch pad and gave Columbia's crew a
chance to interact with flight controllers at the Kennedy Space
Center and at mission control at the Johnson Space Center in Texas.
   ``It sets the stage for final launch preparations and the launch
of Columbia in the first week of August,'' said NASA spokesman
George Diller.
   ``This exercise is designed to be a high-fidelity test, in large
part a carbon copy of what will be occuring on launch day. We're
coming out with a very good test,'' said Diller.
   Shuttle managers will not announce a firm launch date until July
26, when they complete a flight readiness review.
   NASA is conducting the secret mission for the Department of
Defense and military space experts believe the astronauts will
deploy an advanced reconnaissance satellite.
   The practice session covers the final 24 hours of an actual space
shuttle countdown.
   ``This is as much a people test as it is a test for the space
shuttle itself,'' Diller explained. ``It is a good opportunity to
bring out any bugs in all of the procedures that will be used when
Columbia is launched next month.''
</TEXT>
