<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Congress     07-18 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Congress,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Suggests Moving Up Party Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday suggested
that a congress of the Communist Party scheduled for 1991 be moved
up to next year. That would give him another chance to remove more
oldtimers opposed to reforms.
   The official Tass news agency said Gorbachev made the proposal at
a meeting with Communist Party chiefs from the 15 Soviet republics
and from territorial and regional party committees. It said he
recommended that the 28th Communist Party congress be held in the
fall of 1990.
   Tass reported Gorbachev rejected calls to hold an emergency party
congress in addition to the one scheduled for 1991 on grounds that
many major political events are already on the calendar. Among the
events he listed are a a meeting of the party's policy-making
Central Committee, the second session of the new Congress of
People's Deputies _ the Soviet parliament _ and local elections.
   The Central Committee meeting is expected to be held this summer,
the Congress of People's Deputies session will open in October and
the elections are set for next spring.
   Gorbachev has increased the pace of political reform since taking
office as Communist Party general secretary at the last party
congress in 1985. He became president last October and could
strengthen his power base with a party congress.
   The congress would give Gorbachev an opportunity to revamp the
Central Committee beyond changes made in April at a Central
Committee meeting. At that meeting he engineered the retirement of
110 senior officials, including many holdovers from the era of the
late President Leonid I. Brezhnev blamed for leading the country
into an economic and political morass.
   In April the Central Committee promoted many non-voting members
to full voting status but was not empowered to bring in new members.
That is the exclusive job of a party congress.
   Several important party officials allied with Gorbachev are not
Central Committee members and he could bring them aboard at the
party congress. They include the party chiefs in the ethnic hotspots
of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia in the Baltics and Armenia and
Azerbaijan in the Caucasus.
   In a speech at Tuesday's meeting Gorbachev said the 20
million-member party was lagging behind the progress being made in
Soviet society and it could lose its leading position.
</TEXT>
