<HEAD>Body Found In Mohawk River Confirmed As Victim of Bridge Collapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Sullivan said ...,' to ADD comment on why body
turned up.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of the only unaccounted for
victim of a 1987 bridge collapse was found downstream, where it
apparently had been snagged since the accident, police said Tuesday.
   Relatives identified the body of Edward Meyer of Albany by using
keys, jewelry and clothing found on the remains, said Trooper Edward
Dyer.
   A boater on Saturday spotted the body floating in the Mohawk
River near Schenectady, said Schenectady County Medical Examiner Dr.
Robert Sullivan.
   It was about 20 miles downstream from where the Schoharie Creek
bridge collapsed. The creek empties into the Mohawk River.
   Meyer was the last unaccounted for victim of the April 5, 1987,
collapse. Six cars and one truck fell more than 80 feet into the
rain-swollen creek. Nine other bodies were recovered shortly after
the accident.
   Sullivan said Meyer's body may have been snagged on a branch or
some other protrusion on the river's bottom, preventing it from
surfacing. He said hot summer weather probably caused the body to
float to the surface.
   Meyer, 50, was returning to Albany from a bowling tournament in
Syracuse when the raging creek wore away bridge supports and caused
the New York State Thruway bridge to collapse.
