<FIRST>r w AM-POWs-Afghanistan     07-18 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-POWs-Afghanistan,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Seeks Links to Freedom for Soviet, US POW@MIAs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former congressman who recently returned from
Pakistan said Tuesday that members of the Afghan resistance would be
willing to link release of Soviet prisoners to the release of
Americans held in Indochina.
   William M. Hendon, chairman of the POW Publicity Fund in McLean,
Va., said the warm reception by the mujahedeen during an initial
visit to their base in Peshawar, Pakistan, led him to return with
relatives of servicemen who have been missing since as early as 1961.
   ``What we've accomplished is the biggest deal since the end of
the war,'' said Hendon, whose fund was set up to offer a $2.5
million reward to anyone who escapes, defects and brings an American
POW to freedom.
   ``They have indicated a clear desire to help ... and they are in
a position to help,'' said Hendon, from Asheville, N.C. ``That's the
exciting thing about it.''
   Hendon and the relatives have been in Washington this week to
talk about their weeklong trip, from which they returned Saturday.
   He said he would ask Congress to support further arms shipments
to fight the Kabul government although the mujahedeen did not make
that a condition of help.
   ``They said that their Islamic teaching and their genuine
compassion for our men and they view this as a humanitarian gesture
to help their friends the Americans ...,'' he said. ``We believe
that the way we can help them the most is to help them win the war
that they have fought for 11 years now, that they have suffered 1.5
million casualties, they have 45,000 of their own people disappeared
or missing.''
   Hendon said he that the idea came to him after reading an article
in the Aug. 19, 1988, issue of ``Asiaweek'' magazine during a flight
over Laos. The article about Afghanistan mentioned the strong desire
of the Soviets to recover their prisoners taken in the civil war in
that country.
   That and other news accounts mentioned how intent the Soviets
were on winning the release of the prisoners. The Soviet government
was even sending delegations of ordinary men and women to plead for
the release of the prisoners, he said.
   Hendon said he initially met in June with two fundamentalist
leaders, Burhanuddin Rabbani and Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, and other
``top leaders'' of the resistance.
   The group then met with Dr. Zabihullah Mojadeddi, general
secretary of the Afghan National Liberation Front, and others,
Hendon said.
   ``They said to us directly, `We will help,''' said one of the
relatives, Beth Stewart of Washington, D.C. ``There were no hollow
statements, no platitudes.''
   ``They've lived what we've lived for many, many years because of
their own losses,'' said Beth Bischoff of Wilson, N.C.
   Ms. Stewart's father and Mrs. Bischoff's father-in-law are
missing in Southeast Asia.
   The State Department says it has received no reports from
Islamabad about such a possibility. A small number of prisoners was
exchanged last fall, and there have been periodic meetings.
   Although nothing would be wrong with a three-way deal, a State
Department source said, POWs are considered a humanitarian issue,
meaning they should not be part of political negotiations that lead
to a settlement.
   The Pentagon had no comment on the proposal, said Lt. Col. Keith
Schneider, a spokesman. ``I have no idea what the possibilities
are,'' he said.
   The official government position is that it is unable to prove
the existence of POWs in Vietnam although it won't rule out the
possibility. The number of Americans unaccounted for in Southeast
Asia is 2,348.
</TEXT>
