<FIRST>u w AM-RedDye     07-18 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red Dye,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agriculture Appropriations Bill Leads to Red Dye Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed farm legislation Tuesday
accompanied by a report calling for further study of Red Dye No. 3
before any ban on the food additive as a cancer-causing substance.
   However, the chairman of the committee that submitted the bill
said the government was not bound to hold off on such a ban.
   Rep. Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., said his committee's report seeking
more study of the dye that gives maraschino cherries their brilliant
color does not legally require the Food and Drug Administration to
leave it on the market.
   His statements came in response to questions from Rep. Ted Weiss,
D-N.Y., during debate over the $42.1 billion appropriations bill for
rural development, agriculture and related agencies, which includes
the FDA.
   The bill, which sets spending for the fiscal year beginning Oct.
1, was approved 394-26.
   In 1960, when Congress called for a ban on foods that cause
cancer in laboratory animals, Red Dye No. 3 and others were put on a
provisional list that allowed them to stay on the market for an
additional two years pending further study.
   Weiss, who chairs a House Government Operations subcommittee that
has held hearings on the issue, said during the debate, ``Since
1962, the FDA has given the industry somewhere between 30 and 40
extensions of the provisional listing of Red Dye No. 3.''
   ``FDA scientists have concluded that Red Dye No. 3 causes
cancer,'' he added. ``The ostensible grounds for further study
outlined in the committee's report _ to test the so-called
`secondary mechanism' of the dye _ have already been studied and
dismissed in 1987 by a panel of expert government scientists in a
100-plus page report.''
   Weiss contended, ``Under the law, the FDA has no option but to
follow through with its stated intentions to terminate the
provisional listing of Red Dye No. 3. ... It is high time that it do
so.''
   Large doses of the additive have caused tumors in rats, leading
consumer groups to demand that it be banned.
   The language about further tests was put in the report on the
appropriations bill after requests by growers and canners, who would
like to postpone action against the dye.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that FDA commissioner
Frank Young said his office worked with proponents of the provision.
He has maintained that the additive doesn't pose a health threat.
   The report says the Appropriations Committee ``expects the Food
and Drug Administration to provide the technical expertise necessary
... for a long-term study to determine if the secondary mechanism
effect can be confirmed for ... Red Dye No. 3. ...
   ``The committee further expects the Food and Drug Administration
to review the results of this study, in addition to any other
scientifically based findings which may emerge, prior to making any
decision relating to changes in the provisionally or permanently
approved uses of this color.''
   The ``secondary mechanism'' refers to arguments that the dye is
not a primary cause of cancer, and causes tumors only when used in
doses higher than would ever be consumed through its use as a food
coloring.
   The appropriations bill covers spending for all agriculture
programs, including research, extension services, animal and plant
inspections, crop insurance, commodity credit corp. and conservation
programs.
   It also covers rural development programs such as the Farmers
Home Administration, Rural Development Insurance Fund and Rural
Electrification Administration. Nutrition programs, including food
stamps; women, infant and children food supplements, and food for
the needy fall under the legislation, as do foreign agriculture
service programs.
</TEXT>
