<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--HemingwayStamp     07-18 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hemingway Stamp,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stamp Ceremony Held Outside Newspaper Where Hemingway Once Worked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ceremony marking the issuance of a
25-cent postage stamp honoring Ernest Hemingway was held Tuesday
outside the Kansas City Star building where the writer once worked.
   About 50 people attended the ceremony, where Postmaster James
Wood presented an enlargement of the stamp to David Zeeck, managing
editor of The Kansas City Star. The stamp was based on a 1957
photograph by Yousuf Karsh.
   Hemingway, a Nobel and Pulitzer Prize-winning author, worked at
the newspaper for about six months beginning in October 1917 before
leaving to work as an ambulance driver on the Italian front in World
War I. He died in 1961.
   Hemingway's novels and short stories were characterized by crisp
writing. He often credited his style to the Star's stylebook, which
emphasizes conciseness, Zeeck said.
   The ceremony in Kansas City followed the first-day issue of the
stamp Monday at the writer's former home in Key West, Fla.
</TEXT>
