<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-France     07-18 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-France,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Asked to Clarify Reported Sale to Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Tuesday it has asked
France to clarify reports that Paris is seeking to sell sensitive
rocket technology to Brazil, a country with military trade links to
Libya.
   So far, the French Foreign Ministry ``has not yet said what, if
anything, has been approved for transfer to Brazil,'' said Richard
Boucher, the department spokesman.
   The Washington Times, quoting unidentified officials in a story
published Tuesday, said the French Embassy in Brasilia has notified
the U.S. Embassy there that France has granted preliminary approval
for the transfer of technology relating to the Viking liquid-fuel
rocket engine, which is used to propel the French Ariane
space-launch missile.
   The transfer could be in violation of the Missile Technology
Control Regime, signed in 1987 by several countries including France
and the United States.
   Boucher said the regime states ``there is a strong presumption
against the transfer of sensitive rocket technology, which is
classified as ``category one.''
   If France were to transfer a ``category one'' rocket, Paris would
have to require that it not be transferred without the consent of
the French government, Boucher said.
   He also said the United States has in the past raised with the
Brazilians its concerns about military trade with Libya, a country
the United States has accused of inciting acts of terrorism.
   But Boucher said, ``The supposition that French rocket technology
will flow to Libya is merely speculation.''
</TEXT>
