<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-18 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Kill Rival Insurgents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fundamentalist Afghan insurgents
acknowledged Monday they killed members of a rival guerrilla
faction. They were responding to reports that they ambushed and
executed 30 men from the other group.
   Rebel sources said the two factions are involved in a power
struggle that could hinder efforts to overthrow the Soviet-sponsored
Afghan government.
   Reacting Monday to the earlier reports of killings on July 9 in
Takhar Province, 140 miles north of Kabul, Bush administration
officials deplored the action but said U.S. support of the Afghan
guerrillas would continue.
   ``Our commitment to support the mujahedeen is very clear and the
nature and character of our support is unchanged and it will
continue,'' State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said. The
guerrillas call themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors.
   The dead, including seven field commanders, belonged to the
Jamiat-e-Islami guerrillas. Jamiat said the ambush was carried out
by the rival Hezb-e-Islami of Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, a hard-line
anti-American fundamentalist.
   Jamiat spokesman Mohammad Shaoib said five people were killed in
the ambush and 25 were executed later. Qaribur Rehman Saeed,
spokesman for Hezb-e-Islami, denied anyone was executed but
acknowledged some members of Jamiat were killed.
   Saeed did not say how many were killed and said his group was
investigating.
   The struggle for power among guerrilla groups is almost as old as
the Afghan civil war, which began after a communist coup in April
1978. Guerrilla sources say scores of men have been killed.
   Those slain in the latest incident were from Afghanistan's
northern provinces of Badakhshan, Kunduz, Takhar and Baghlan and
were returning from a strategy meeting with Jamiat commander Ahmed
Shah Masoud, Shaoib said.
   Shaoib gave no details of the ambush or executions. ``It is a
great loss for all Afghanistan, especially for the north,'' he said.
   ``In the northern provinces, there are only two powers, Jamiat
and Hezb,'' said Saeed, the Hezb-e-Islami spokesman. ``Many of our
commanders have been killed by Masoud's people.''
   Masoud formed a northern council to incorporate guerrillas
belonging to the seven rebel parties based in Pakistan. In a message
to his headquarters in Peshawar more than one year ago, he said he
was consolidating forces and establishing an Islamic army.
   ``The conflict started right from the beginning, when Masoud
wanted the upper hand in the north,'' Saeed said. ``Masoud wanted to
clear the area of Hezb mujahedeen.''
   According to Saeed, Masoud agreed to temporary cease-fires with
Soviet troops when the Red Army was involved in the Afghan war, and
the guerrillas fought among themselves when Hezb-e-Islami forces
refused to recognize those arrangements.
   Soviet military forces completed their withdrawal from
Afghanistan on Feb. 15, after nine years of involvement in the war.
   Sources independent of either group said they feared the internal
conflict would cripple guerrilla efforts to capture
government-controlled cities in the north.
   A moderate insurgent, also speaking privately, said Masoud's
forces could not approach Kabul, the Afghan capital, because
Hezb-e-Islami blocked them in central Parwan province.
   In Kabul on Tuesday, the government said soldiers sealed off and
searched the capital's southern sector Tuesday after reports that
guerrillas were planning to infiltrate.
   On Monday, air force fighter jets bombed rebel bases near the
eastern city of Jalalabad, killing at least 78 guerrillas and
wounding 114, Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani told
reporters in Kabul.
   He said the rebel bases were around Surkhdewar, 77 miles from
Kabul. The report could not be confirmed independently.
   Tanks and armored personnel carriers rolled out at dawn Tuesday
to erect road blocks around the southern district, home to about
one-fifth of Kabul's 2.5 million people.
   Amani said the search lasted five hours, but gave no details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
