<FIRST>r a AM-People-Roseanne     07-18 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Roseanne,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roseanne to Get New Job, But Not Rich, Say Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roseanne Conner, the wise-cracking mom on
ABC's hit comedy ``Roseanne,'' will be unemployed for a while at the
beginning of the new season but will eventually get a new job, the
show's producers said Tuesday.
   There were rumors that the Conners, played by Roseanne Barr and
John Goodman, would win the lottery and become rich, but that rumor
was quashed.
   Producers Tom Werner and Marcy Carsey were asked about the
``Roseanne'' lottery rumor, which turned up in a supermarket
tabloid, and Carsey said it was untrue.
   ``I don't know where they get this stuff. I really don't,'' she
said.
   Both were attending an ABC news conference on their newest show,
``Chicken Soup,'' which stars comedian Jackie Mason.
   Werner said there would be no major changes on ``Roseanne'' in
the upcoming season. Roseanne quit her job at the factory in the
last episode of last season.
   ``Roseanne's going to have a new job, we haven't even locked in
on that, but basically it's pretty much the same stories as we've
been telling,'' said Werner.
   ``We think it's a very fertile area, someone who's unemployed,
and the first few scripts we're dealing with that. Obviously, in a
family like this, you need two incomes, so pretty soon Roseanne
Conner is going to find a job.''
   Carsey said Roseanne might possibly get a more upscale job, but
there weren't even any definite plans for that.
   Carsey and Werner also produce ``The Cosby Show'' and ``A
Different World'' on NBC. Carsey said she doesn't know if Cosby will
sign for a seventh year, but she would like to see the show continue
after next season.
</TEXT>
