<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms in the Southeast and Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms drenched the Mississippi Valley and southeastern
United States on Tuesday, and showers and thunderstorms developed
ahead of a cold front in the Midwest.
   The Southeast storms were part of a slow-moving cold front, and
were clustered over Florida, southern Georgia and southern Alabama.
   In the Midwest, showers and thunderstorms fell over Wisconsin,
Iowa, southern Minnesota and northern Illinois. Strong thunderstorms
developed over central Iowa and southern Minnesota.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from northeastern Texas to
western Tennessee and southern Illinois. A few showers fell in
northern Maine. The rest of the nation had fair to partly sunny
skies.
   Temperatures topped 100 degrees in southwest Texas. In Midland by
midday, the temperature had already surpassed a previous record high
for the date of 104 degrees set in 1981.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Lompoc, Calif., to 110 degrees at Needles, Calif. The low
for the Lower 48 states was 31 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
the lower and middle Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic Coast, with
showers and thunderstorms most numerous in northern Florida, the
central Gulf Coast states, the upper Ohio Valley and the lower Great
Lakes region; widely scattered thunderstorms over Arizona; and sunny
skies in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were expected to climb over 90 degrees from Florida
to Texas and across most of the western third of the country, with
readings above 100 degrees from southern Arizona to the central
valleys of California.
   Highs were predicted in the 70s for the lower Ohio Valley, the
upper Great Lakes and along the Pacific Coast, and in the 80s
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
