<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Fernandez     07-18 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernandez,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Cite Secret Document Issue, Request Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing problems with the use of classified
material, prosecutors on Tuesday requested a delay in the
Iran-Contra case against a former CIA station chief charged with
obstruction and lying.
   The trial of Joseph Fernandez was scheduled to start July 24, but
a change in the CIA's position regarding certain classified
information ``may substantially complicate'' the case, prosecutors
said in court papers.
   The office of independent counsel Lawrence Walsh proposed that
July 24 be set aside for a hearing on the classified information
issue and that a trial begin ``as soon as practicable thereafter.''
   The prosecution didn't specify the nature of the change by the
Central Intelligence Agency, other than to describe it as ``a new
emphasis in the CIA's position.''
   Fernandez and others under indictment in Iran-Contra cases have
requested declassification of large amounts of sensitive documents
for use in their courtroom defenses. Intelligence agencies have been
reluctant to declassify much of the information out of concern for
national security.
   As CIA station chief in Costa Rica, Fernandez assisted former
White House aide Oliver L. North's secret supply network aiding the
Contras during a congressional ban on military aid to the rebel
force battling Nicaragua's Marxist government.
   Questioned by the CIA inspector general's office and the Tower
Commission in 1987, Fernandez allegedly said he wasn't certain North
was running the network and asserted that a secret airstrip
construction project had been initiated by the Costa Rican
government. In fact, the airstrip project was initiated by North,
Fernandez and others to help supply the Contras.
</TEXT>
