<DOCNO> AP890718-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HouseCups     07-18 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Cups,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Small Step for the Environment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress, which has a tough time agreeing on
ways to clean up the environment, is trying to take a small step in
that direction in its own House.
   A bipartisan group of House members has written the House
Administration Committee asking for the removal of polystyrene cups
from the restaurant system.
   ``If we are to pass and enforce new laws to ensure a cleaner
nation, we must, ourselves, be willing to take the first step,''
said the letter signed by 92 lawmakers.
   The group asks that cups made of a biodegradable material replace
the current foam ones. ``The use of such non-biodegradable products
in the House food service system is unnecessary and ill-advised,''
they said.
</TEXT>
