<FIRST>r w AM-ContraSuit     07-18 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Suit,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen File Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four members of Congress said Tuesday in a
lawsuit that President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker
III made an unconstitutional side agreement with congressional
leaders on $49.8 million in humanitarian aid to the Contras.
   The side agreement provides that the Bush administration won't
obligate funds appropriated under the law after next Nov. 30 unless
it receives unanimous consent in writing from nine congressional
leaders, said the lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court.
   The suit says the side agreement doesn't follow constitutional
procedures requiring consideration by the entire House and Senate.
   It was filed by U.S. Reps. Dan Burton, R-Ind.; Chuck Douglas,
R-N.H.; Philip Crane, R-Ill., and Robert Smith, R-N.H.
   Burton and Crane voted for the law providing the assistance while
Douglas and Smith voted against it.
   The votes by the four congressmen ``have been rendered
ineffective and substantially nullified'' and they have been
inhibited in their performance of their constitutional duties, they
said in the lawsuit.
   Bush on April 18 signed into law a bipartisan plan to give the
Contras non-military aid.
   The aid is intended to sustain the rebels until Nicaragua holds
elections early next year.
</TEXT>
