<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0681 07-18 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0681,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Victim of July 6 Bus Attack Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Foreign Ministry statement,
army confirming death of Palestinian youth. Pickup 17th pvs, `At least...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American attorney died Tuesday of injuries
suffered July 6 when a Palestinian grabbed the wheel of an Israeli
bus and drove it into a ravine, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Rita Levine, 39, of Philadelphia was the first American to perish
in the 19-month Arab uprising against the Israeli occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Ms. Levine suffered serious spinal cord injuries, broken ribs and
damaged lungs in the attack, said Ruth Mekel, a spokeswoman for
Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem.
   Her death raised to 15 the number of people killed in the attack,
in which a Palestinian from the Gaza Strip grabbed the steering
wheel of a bus, shouted in Arabic ``God is great!'' and forced it
off the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway into a 200-foot ravine.
   Two of the dead were Canadians. Of the 27 injured, eight were
holders of U.S. passports, including Ms. Levine.
   The suspect in the attack, Abdel Hadi Suleiman Rassem Ghanem, 23,
reportedly carried out the assault to avenge his friend, who was
shot in a clash with Israeli troops and subsequently paralyzed.
   The body of Ms. Levine, 39, will be flown to the United States on
Wednesday, Ms. Mekel said.
   Ms. Levine reportedly came to Israel to learn Hebrew and was
hoping to open a dual law practice in Philadelphia and in the Jewish
state.
   ``She talked about a possibility of settling here,'' the hospital
spokeswoman said.
   Israeli leaders have blamed the Palestine Liberation Organization
for the attack and criticized the Bush administration for being slow
in defining the attack as terrorism.
   Joan Levine, speaking at a July 11 news conference that was
arranged by the Israeli Foreign Ministry, said her sister had said
from her hospital bed that the incident was a terrorist attack.
   Choking back sobs, Joan Levine called her sister a ``champion of
the homeless and the handicapped'' when she practiced law in the
United States.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said in a statement to The
Associated Press:
   ``While we mourn Rita's death and send our deepest condolences to
her family, we continue to hear repeatedly contemptuous declarations
by the PLO praising this horrible terrorist act, the last of which
was made by the official PLO radio station in Baghdad few days ago.''
   Liel recalled how he visited Rita Levine in the Hadassah
Hospital's intensive care unit.
   ``She was impressive,'' he said. ``She was paralyzed, had
injuries all over, (but) she was talking that she thought about
coming to live here, thought about opening an option.''
   Ms. Levine was the first American to die in the Palestinian
revolt against Israeli rule in the occupied territorities. At least
567 Palestinians and 36 Israelis, including a U.S.-born Jewish
settler, have perished in the violence.
   Also on Tuesday, troops dispersing a stone-throwing mob in Gaza's
Khan Yunis refugee camp shot and killed Bassam Farouk Ahmed Al
Jabri, 16. Officials at Khan Yunis' Nasser hospital said the youth
was dead on arrival at the hospital with a gunshot wound to the
heart.
   The army confirmed that Al Jabri was shot by soldiers. It said Al
Jabri was in a group of youths that hurled rocks at an army unit in
the camp and he ``was known to security forces as an instigator and
participant in disturbances.''
   At least 12 other Palestinians were reported wounded in clashes
with soldiers in the Gaza Strip. Arab hospitals in the West Bank
said they treated seven wounded. The army said it was checking the
reports.
   In another development, the army unveiled its new tactic of
``camera ambushes'' in which hidden video cameras are used to
photograph Palestinian stone-throwers, much the same way police
watch traffic violators.
   A military spokesman said the tapes were used to detain
stone-throwers on the spot, and were accepted as evidence by
military courts.
   Israeli newspapers said the ``camera ambushes'' were being
concealed near markets, streets and intersections where
stone-throwing attacks are especially frequent.
   The daily Maariv said in a recent incident in the West Bank town
of Ramallah, two suspected stone-throwers who denied their
involvement in an attack were identified on the basis of a
videotape. It said the camera was set up on the city's main street.
   In the past, the Israeli army has used videotape to identify
ringleaders in mass demonstrations, the daily newspaper Al Hamishmar
said.
   Army cameramen also have secretly photographed incidents of
soldiers' brutality against Palestinians. These tapes were used to
teach soldiers to not repeat the offenses.
</TEXT>
