<FIRST>r a AM-JailWedding     07-18 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jail Wedding,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thrice-Convicted Killer To Wed in Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Trbovich is cq in 6th graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STUART, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guests are out. So is a honeymoon. But a man
convicted three times of murder is getting married _ in jail _ to a
woman he met through an ad in a supermarket tabloid.
   James Morgan, convicted and sentenced to die three times for the
1977 murder of an elderly woman, got his marriage license Monday,
said Martin County Jail Administrator John Murphy.
   Morgan, 28, will wed Rita Marie Runge, 26, of Homestead, Fla.
   ``He seems sincere about it,'' Murphy said. ``He went through the
procedures.''
   The Florida Supreme Court has overturned Morgan's three
convictions on technical grounds. He is awaiting a fourth trial for
first-degree murder in the slaying of Gertrude Trbovich of Stuart,
Fla.
   That doesn't bother Miss Runge. ``I plan to marry him because I
love him and it doesn't matter whether he stays in prison or gets
out,'' she said. ``It's not going change the way I feel about him.''
   The couple met in a jailhouse visit in November 1988, five months
after she answered his tabloid ad for a pen pal.
   Murphy said he denied Morgan's request for guests at the wedding,
a list that was to include judges, prosecutors and several of his
lawyers.
   Morgan and his bride-to-be will be allowed a 30-minute visit
after the wedding, but an officer will be with them, Murphy said.
   ``Morgan asked for a three-hour contact visit,'' Murphy said.
``But that's not allowed.''
</TEXT>
