<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WesternGovernors     07-18 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Western Governors,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Secretary Tells Governors Offshore Oil Drilling Must Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr.
said Tuesday that a proposed congressional moratorium on offshore
oil drilling is asking Americans to ``blindly reject even the
possibilities before us.''
   Democratic Oregon Gov. Neil Goldschmidt said Lujan's remarks at
the Western Governor's Conference were further evidence that
President Bush's administration is unresponsive to public concerns
about restricting drilling in environmentally sensitive areas.
   ``On the basis of what I've heard today, there isn't much
optimism ... of avoiding an environmental fight,'' Goldschmidt said,
complaining he had ``not found the administration responsive at
all.''
   Lujan said at a news conference later that his comments were not
intended to signal the administration's intent to wage a major
counterattack on the proposed one-year moratorium resolution, which
has passed the House and is awaiting final action in the Senate.
   ``It's not an all-out fight, but we will try to convince the
Senate that moratoria is not the way to go about it,'' Lujan said.
``We're not looking at drilling any of these offshore areas in the
next year or two. But we do need the opportunity to study the
environmental problems that have to be faced to determine which
areas we should not drill in, and with the moratorium as it is now,
we cannot even do the environmental studies.''
   Later, the interior secretary told reporters that, ``I don't mind
a moratorium as far as drilling is concerned'' so long as it doesn't
also ban research and environmental studies.
   Lujan's tone in his formal address to the 17 governors was
considerably less conciliatory, with several direct attacks against
Congress, which he said has displayed a ``can't-do attitude'' in its
moratorium proposal and is not facing the nation's vital need for
energy independence from foreign sources.
   ``By imposing moratoria, the Congress is saying that we should
blindly reject even the possibilities before us,'' Lujan said.
``Certainly we must assess the risks. We must realistically weigh
the dangers. We should never act recklessly. But let us never be
afraid to search for the facts and act wisely on them.''
   Lujan also said the concern about oil spills is misdirected
against offshore drilling operations, which he said have spilled
only minuscule amounts of oil since a 1969 accident in Santa Barbara.
   ``While tankers continue to spill oil into our waters, and
offshore drilling continues to provide a record of environmentally
sound production, why are we attacking offshore drilling, and
letting the tankers nestle in their harbors?'' Lujan asked.
   ``Decreasing oil pollution in our waters can best be accomplished
by decreasing the amount of oil transported by ship,'' he said,
calling for an analysis of the feasibility of developing deep-water
oil transfer facilities, where oil would be transferred to shore
from ships.
   Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper also raised oil spill questions in a
presentation that sharply criticized the federal response to the
Alaskan oil spill, the nation's worst such accident with nearly 11
million gallons of crude spilled in Prince William Sound.
   ``The federal response to the oil spill was woefully deficient,
and we must do something about it,'' Cowper said.
   ``We don't know how to clean up a major spill, ... and if we did
know how to clean it up, would we have the capability to do it? The
answer is no,'' Cowper said, asserting that current procedures lack
either a clear chain of command or assurance that cleanup equipment
will be available.
   Lujan replied that he agreed in general terms with Cowper's
criticisms. The governors unanimously adopted a resolution drafted
by Cowper to revamp their oil spill response to, among other things:
   _ Require that the Coast Guard maintain adequate emergency
cleanup plans and assure resources to carry them out for all ports
with oil spill risks.
   _ Provide guaranteed sources of money for immediate cleanup
efforts.
   _ Guarantee the states' rights to assess fees to support oil
spill cleanup supervision.
   _ Assure states the legal authority to set liability, and assess
penalties and damage claims.
</TEXT>
