<FIRST>r i AM-France-IRA     07-18 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-IRA,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Suspects Charged in France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men and a woman suspected of belonging to the
Irish Republican Army were charged Tuesday with violating explosives
laws and involvement in terrorism, the French news agency Agence
France-Presse reported.
   It said the defendants, identified as Patrick Murray, Donnogh
O'Kane and Pauline Drunns, also were charged with counterfeiting and
falsifying documents. AFP said the case was assigned to
Investigating Magistrate Gilles Riviere of the special
anti-terrorism section.
   Scotland Yard in London said British police would have no comment
about the case. ``We are referring all calls to the French police;
it's their operation,'' a spokesman said.
   In Dublin, police linked a man and woman brought before the Irish
Republic's anti-terrorist Special Criminal Court on Tuesday with an
IRA unit operating on the continent and the three people charged in
Paris. Leonard Hardy, 28, and Donna Maguire, 22, were ordered held
in custody.
   Pierre Joxe, the French interior minister, said Monday the three
people were arrested in connection with security for last weekend's
Western economic summit in Paris and celebrations of the French
revolution bicentennial. He gave no details.
   Britain's domestic news agency, Press Association, said the three
told the Paris court they were members of the IRA and had no quarrel
with France.
   Charges and other pretrial criminal proceedings are supposed to
be kept secret under French law, but judicial sources often make
them known to courthouse reporters.
   In terrorism cases, the law allows police to hold people for
questioning for four days before bringing criminal charges. They
then can be held without bail pending trial.
   The AFP report said Murray, O'Kane and Ms. Drunns were arrested
Friday while driving on a superhighway in eastern France toward the
West German border. It said police suspected Murray, O'Kane and Ms.
Drunns of preparing attacks on British soldiers in West Germany.
   A search of the house where they were staying turned up false
passports, documents relating to British army bases in West Germany
and electronic gear that could be used for remote-control bomb
detonators, the agency said.
   Press Association said Murray had been sought since failing to
appear in court in Dublin in 1986 on charges relating to a shooting
there. It said he was known as ``The Pope'' because he has the words
``God Save The Pope'' tattooed on each forearm.
   Detective Inspector Kevin Carty told the court in Dublin that
Hardy and Ms. Maguire were arrested July 12 at Rosslare as they left
a ferry from Cherbourg, France.
   They were ``part of a group who were operating and engaged in
criminal activities'' outside the jurisdiction of Irish courts, the
inspector said.
   Hardy and Ms. Maguire are from Northern Ireland, where the IRA is
fighting to end British rule and unite the province with the
republic. The IRA is outlawed in both parts of Ireland.
   Carty said the Dublin defendants had false passports, explosives,
mercury switches that detonate bombs, photographs of a military base
and a telescopic rifle sight.
</TEXT>
