<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Economy     07-18 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy Minister Implicated in Foreign Exchange Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Venezuelan judge Tuesday charged
Economy Minister and former business executive Nestor Rapanelli with
misusing public funds in a multibillion-dollar foreign exchange
fraud.
   Rapanelli was sworn into office on Saturday to succeed Miguel
Roig, who died suddenly after serving less than a week.
   The allegation involved the overbilling of grain imports when
Rapanelli directed the Caracas offices of the Argentine grain
conglomerate Bunge and Born between 1985 and 1986.
   The purpose was to gain access to U.S. dollars provided by the
Venezuelan government at preferential, lower rates, said a spokesman
for Caracas Criminal Court Judge Luis Guillermo de La Riva.
   Rapanelli said he is innocent. ``My conscience is absolutely
calm,'' he told the government news agency Telam.
   Rapanelli, 60, said the charge initially was filed against him
and executives of four other grain trading companies in the
mid-1980s, and he was formally cleared in June 1988.
   President Carlos Menem, who took office on July 8, defended his
minister.
   ``It's a lie and it's going to end like all lies: buried by the
truth,'' Menem told reporters. ``We are going to defend him
totally.''
   Judge La Riva issued an order for Rapanelli's preventive
detention. The Venezuelan government, however, did not request his
extradition.
   In the scandal, a Venezuelan government agency known as Recadi
over five years distributed $40 billion for subsidized imports.
   Recadi was created in early 1983 as Venezuela's oil bonanza began
to fade and exchange restrictions were imposed. Cheap dollars were
lavishly granted via Recadi to private and public companies for
imports that otherwise would have fueled inflation.
   But of the $40 billion distributed, $6 billion is said to have
been granted fraudulently, mostly by overbilling, personal
connections or even outright bribery, contributing to the depletion
of the nation's monetary reserves.
   The scandal involved the executives of several multinational
companies, and nearly 50 arrest orders have been issued. Most
businessmen and government figures involved fled the country, many
before the warrants were issued. Only a dozen arrests have been
made, mostly of low-level company employees.
   No government figures have been detained, although several travel
prohibitions are pending against former finance ministers under the
previous government of president Jaime Lusinchi.
   La Riva has been accused of taking bribes in exchange for
juridical immunity for executives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
