<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FootballChamps     07-18 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Football Champs,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Reformers: Football Ruling Erodes Texas `No-Pass, No-Play'
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK GODICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas' education commissioner went too far in
overturning the grade of a high school football player and declaring
his team ineligible for the state championship trophy, a judge ruled
Tuesday.
   State District Judge Paul Davis Jr., in Austin, said Dallas'
Carter High School can keep its 1988 trophy despite a challenge to
the eligibility of running back Gary Edwards, and education
reformers fear the decision will undermine the state's ``no-pass,
no-play'' standard for student athletes.
   Last fall, state investigators found that Edwards had failed an
algebra class, which would have made the school ineligible for the
high school football playoffs under Texas' no-pass, no-play law.
   The principal at Carter High, in his own investigation, found the
teacher had miscalculated Edwards' grade and said he actually passed.
   The principal's finding was overturned by state Education
Commissioner William Kirby, but the Dallas school district got an
injunction from Davis allowing it to compete for the championship.
   The judge said the commissioner should not have interfered unless
the school abused its discretion in setting the grade.
   ``This court finds that it was improper for the state
commissioner of education to set the grade for an individual student
in an individual class,'' Davis wrote.
   The Texas Education Agency will appeal Davis' ruling. Kirby said
he believes the Carter principal did abuse his discretion by
altering the grade.
   Reformers say the ruling undermines efforts to set strict
eligibility standards for school athletics.
   ``It means that no-pass, no-play becomes no-pass, no-problem,''
said Lucius D. Bunton, attorney for the University Interscholastic
League, the state's governing body for high school athletics.
   The law, which prohibits students who fail a class from
participating in extracurricular activities, is a key part of
education reforms that Texas lawmakers approved in 1984.
</TEXT>
