<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cuba-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0747 07-18 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cuba-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rangel Says Cuba Seeking Talks on Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs bgng, `Neither Kozak,' with 6 grafs, now grafs
7-12, bgng: ``A State,'' with State Dept comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban officials say they have talked with a top
State Department official about opening a dialogue on joint efforts
to combat drug trafficking, a congressman said Tuesday.
   The announcement by Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the
House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, comes less
than a week after Cuban leader Fidel Castro criticized the United
States for failing to warn him of Cuban military involvement in
cocaine trafficking and the execution of four Cuban officers for
that illegal activity.
   Rangel said he met Tuesday with Jose Antonio Arbesu Fraga, the
new chief of the Cuban Interests Section _ the Cuban substitute for
an embassy, attached formally to the Czechoslovakian Embassy _ and
Arbesu's assistant chief, Manuel Davis.
   The Cubans told him they ``have talked with the State Department
and told them that Cuba is waiting to see how Havana can better
establish a dialogue, because no matter what the political
differences are, no one can allow the drug traffickers to take
advantage,'' Rangel said.
   They also told him they had told Michael Kozak, deputy assistant
secretary of State for inter-American affairs, that they are
``willing to cooperate in any international anti-drug venture,''
Rangel said.
   Although the exact date of the meeting was not revealed, a Rangel
aide noted that Arbesu only became chief of the Cuban Interests
Section in June.
   A State Department official said Tuesday evening, ``Mr. Kozak's
met with Cuban representatives many times over the years,'' and that
Kozak has met Arbesu. This official declined to confirm or deny that
the specific meeting in question had taken place, or what might have
been discussed.
   ``We have raised narcotics with the Cubans on many, many
occasions over the years,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   However, he refused to say whether the State Department had
discussed cooperative anti-drug efforts with the Cubans or simply
criticized them for involvement in drug trafficking, accusations
that have been leveled repeatedly by the United States.
   ``We certainly think there's ample room for the Cubans to take
action,'' he said. ``We're looking for deeds rather than just
words.''
   When the United States says it is looking for deeds, it's talking
about ``interdicting drugs, stopping the flow over their
territory,'' he added.
   He declined to comment on the recent execution of four Cuban
military officers for drug trafficking.
   People who answered the phone at the Cuban Interests Section late
Tuesday afternoon said Arbesu and Davis were both gone for the day
and no one else was available to speak on the matter.
   Last week, Castro told the Cuban Council of State in a four-hour
speech, ``We need some way to communicate in this common battle. We
need to talk to the Americans about how to manage this situation.''
   The Cuban leader also rebuked the United States, saying it had
``at least two names'' of military officers involved in a
cocaine-trafficking conspiracy long before contacts in Colombia
alerted Cuban officials.
   A hero of the Cuban revolution who was a trusted advisor to
Castro, Army Maj. Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa Sanchez, and three other
military officers were executed last Thursday for smuggling tons of
drugs into the United States.
   The drug scandal stunned and embarrassed Castro and his communist
government, which for years denied U.S. accusations that Cuba was
being used to smuggle cocaine and marijuana.
   Last December, Rangel led a congressional delegation to Cuba and
met with Castro for five hours.
   Before he left, State Department and Drug Enforcement
Administration officials told Rangel that there was no official or
unofficial cooperation with Cuba on drugs, although there had been
communications on other topics, a Rangel aide said.
   Meanwhile, the Coast Guard abruptly canceled a closed briefing of
Rangel's committee regarding U.S.-Cuban drug cooperation that had
been scheduled for early Tuesday morning, the congressman said.
   Rangel said Coast Guard Commandant Adm. Paul Yost called him late
Monday to cancel the meeting, saying ``changing developments'' were
responsible.
   ``If there are new developments, why can't they be told to the
Congress?'' Rangel asked.
   ``I can only conclude until I am informed otherwise that
administration anti-communist zealots stopped this briefing, which
could have shown the Congress how the United States and Cuba can
work together to stop the common enemy of drugs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
