<FIRST>r a AM-Quayle     07-18 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Calls For Outposts In Space</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said Tuesday the
United States should commit itself to exploring and developing space
and that Congress should fully fund construction of a manned space
station.
   ``The president and I are committed to American leadership in
exploration, understanding, economic use and, yes, eventual
settlement in space,'' he said in an address to 4,000 employees of
General Dynamics Space Systems Division.
   ``We Americans have been pushing back frontiers throughout
history. Today, space is America's frontier,'' said Quayle,
appointed chairman of the National Space Council by President Bush.
   Quayle likened the first manned Apollo landing on the moon in
1969 to Columbus' discovery of the New World.
   ``The time is now at hand for Americans to be preparing for the
equivalent of 1620, the year Pilgrims landed on the shore of
Plymouth Bay and settled the New World,'' Quayle said.
   He addressed the employees after touring the plant, where General
Dynamics is building Titan Centaur rockets for use as launch
vehicles.
   Quayle said the expense of establishing colonies on the moon and
Mars would be returned many times over in the development of new
industry and jobs and the expansion of knowledge.
   ``Space is a high-yield investment,'' he said, and also urged
Congress to approve full funding for the National Aeronautic and
Space Administration's proposal to build a space station.
   Quayle said President Bush would go into more specifics about the
administration's space policy Thursday, when Bush delivers an
address to mark the 20th anniversary of America's first manned lunar
landing.
   ``We cannot afford not to go forward in space,'' Quayle said.
``Unfortunately, in the past couple of decades we've had somewhat of
a status quo approach to space. We've got to do better than that.''
   During his stay in San Diego, Quayle also visited Qualcomm, a
high-technology firm in Sorrento Valley, and met with business
leaders and officials from the University of California at San Diego.
   At Qualcomm, he used a satellite communications system to send
greetings to 4,500 truckers nationwide whose rigs are equipped with
OmniTRACS, messaging and position reporting computers.
   ``Congratulations on your use of high technology to enhance the
competitive position of the industry,'' Quayle told the truckers.
</TEXT>
