<HEAD>The Man Who Would Be Mayor _ At $85 Per Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf, `Sure thing ...,' to ADD background
on mayoral race.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He came, he saw, he spent ... and spent ... and
spent. Cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder has already dished out a record
$8.5 million in his mayoral bid, but the profits from makeup haven't
covered his campaign woes.
   ``He's got something none of the other candidates will ever have:
a very, very, very wealthy mother,'' political adviser Roger Ailes,
a former Lauder campaign worker, observed early in the candidate's
campaign.
   Lauder's mother is Estee Lauder, head of the cosmetics empire
that bears her name.
   Months later, that remains Lauder's one big advantage.
   In a year where the mayoral race is wide open, almost no one
gives Lauder a chance. Recent polls show former U.S. Attorney
Rudolph Giuliani crushing Lauder in the Republican primary. The
projections in the November general election, in which Lauder will
be on the Conservative Party line, are even uglier.
   ``Sure thing: Ron Lauder will lose by a margin so large he won't
be tempted to demand a recount,'' predicted Daily News columnist
Bill Reel.
   Lauder and Giuliani are vying for the chance to unseat Democratic
Mayor Edward I. Koch. So are Democrats Manhattan Borough President
David Dinkins, City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin and former
Metropolitan Transportation Authority Chairman Richard Ravitch.
   Yet Lauder, 44, continues undaunted, airing more and more
commercials, determined to continue his conservative,
pro-death-penalty campaign.
   Giuliani has ripped Lauder as an incompetent who ``never worked
for a living.'' Lauder has responded by calling Giuliani a liberal
in TV commercials.
   Lauder has spent $85 for each of the 100,000 or so Republicans
expected to vote in the Sept. 12 primary, double the total of five
other mayoral contenders combined.
   ``This is my money. I earned it honestly and I owe no one,''
Lauder said after Monday's revelation about his campaign spending.
``There won't be any favors to be called in with the Lauder
administration.''
   But a Lauder administration would have to overcome these bumps on
the campaign trail:
   _On a radio appearance, Lauder couldn't say how many members the
City Council has. It has 35.
   _His agenda for change included firing the schools chancellor.
The mayor has no power to do this.
   Asked why, Lauder said the incumbent hadn't done much for the
past couple of years. The incumbent had been in office for one year.
   _A recent news conference in the South Bronx was quickly changed
to a ``fact-finding tour'' when only one reporter showed up. Lauder
entertained his audience of one by incorrectly identifying the
surrounding neighborhood.
</TEXT>
