<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-SaudiArabia     07-18 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Saudi Arabia,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Fahd of Saudi Arabia Postpones a State Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia has postponed a state
visit scheduled for next week due to ``the sensitive phase'' of the
Arab League's efforts to settle the strife in Lebanon, the White
House said Tuesday.
   The visit will be rescheduled sometime after Sept. 1, it said.
   Bush had planned to hold a state dinner for Fahd on July 27.
   In a brief statement, the White House said:
   ``King Fahd of Saudi Arabia called President Bush to request that
the state visit scheduled for later this month be postponed due to
the sensitive phase of the mediation on the Lebanese situation by
the Heads of State Committee of which the king is a member.
   ``The president expressed his understanding as well as his wishes
for the success of the committee's effort to bring peace and
stability to Lebanon. Both leaders agreed that the state visit would
take place as soon as could be arranged after Sept. 1.''
   The Arab League is attempting to negotiate a truce in Lebanon
between Syrian-backed Druze forces and Christian militia and to spur
major political reforms in the embattled country.
   Bush was briefed on the initiative at the White House June 14 by
Saudi Arabia's foreign minister, Prince Saud Al-Faisal.
   The league, at a summit meeting in Morocco in May, gave King
Fahd, King Hassan II of Morocco and Algeria's President Chadli
Bendjedid the task of trying to arrange within six months a
ceasefire and a blueprint for lasting political reforms in Lebanon.
   Fifteen foreigners are thought to be held hostage in Lebanon,
nine of them Americans, including Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
