<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Ambassadors 2ndLd-Writethru a0745 07-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Ambassadors, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0745,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Lose in Bid to Control Bush Appointments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs to give the 20 opponents and one not voting member,
which will serve in lieu of a roll call.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday brushed aside complaints
that President Bush is packing the ranks of the nation's envoys with
unqualified political cronies and defeated a bid to restrict
political appointments to 15 percent of the diplomatic corps.
   The vote rejecting an amendment by Sen. Al Gore, D-Tenn., was
79-20.
   Gore said he would try again Wednesday and offered an amendment
to hold to 30 percent the number of ambassadors and senior State
Department officials nominated for their political contributions.
   Gore said the higher percentage was more in keeping with the
average of political appointments in recent administrations.
   He said he also will seek to rally opposition against nominees
whose non-political qualifications to represent the United States
abroad are thin.
   Arguing for the more restrictive 15 percent level, Gore and other
Democrats said two-thirds of the 42 ambassadorial nominations
submitted by Bush can be classified as political.
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and other senators contended that
the proposed restriction would represent an unwarranted and
unconstitutional intrusion on the president's ability to conduct
foreign policy.
   Gore said the political appointments undermine the U.S. Foreign
Service, damage its morale and represent ``an abuse for which there
is no justification.''
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., said the 14 career Foreign Service
officers nominated as ambassadors by Bush represent by far the
lowest level in any of the last six presidential administrations.
   In general, career diplomats received 60 percent or more of
ambassadorships, Sarbanes said.
   ``This is a marked, radical change,'' Sarbanes said. ``This is a
vast departure from a pattern followed by previous administrations,
Republican and Democratic alike.''
   It is a departure ``so outrageous,'' Sarbanes said, ``that
something has to be done about it.''
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the ranking Republican member of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said the right of the
president to nominate whoever he chooses as ambassador ``should not
be prohibited by law.''
   ``We are intruding on the foreign policy authority of the
president,'' Helms said.
   But Gore disagreed.
   ``This practice has reached the point where the Foreign Service
is curtailing prematurely the careers of increasing numbers of its
finest diplomats,'' Gore said.
   ``We've created a game of musical chairs in which the
professionals _ the core of expertise and continuity modern
diplomatic life demands _ lose out,'' he said.
   The 20 senators voting for the amendment to restrict political
appointees were John B. Breaux, D-La.; Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.; Quentin
Burdick, D-N.D.; Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.; Alan Cranston, D-Calif.;
James Exon, D-Neb.; Wendell Ford, D-Ky.; Albert Gore, D-Tenn.;
Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii; Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; Patrick J.
Leahy, D-Vt.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio;
Barbara Mikulski, D-Md.; Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.; Larry Pressler,
R-S.D.; David Pryor, D-Ark.; Paul Sarbanes, D-Md.; Jim Sasser,
D-Tenn.; and Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Sen. Spark M. Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, did not vote.
</TEXT>
