<FIRST>u w AM-FBI-Shakeup 1stLd-Writethru   07-18 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Shakeup, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0739,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assistant Director Named to FBI's No. 2 Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd title in 3rd graf: ``In announcing,'' investigations
sted discrimination.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William S. Sessions on Tuesday
filled the bureau's long-vacant No. 2 position by promoting
Executive Assistant Director Floyd I. Clarke to be his deputy
director.
   Clarke's promotion caps a meteoric rise in the ranks of the FBI's
high command. Clarke, 47, was named an executive assistant director
in February, making him equal in rank to Oliver B. Revell, once
mentioned as a possible director of the bureau, and John E. Otto.
   In announcing a realignment of the top FBI executive positions,
Sessions said that Otto would become associate deputy director for
administration and Revell associate deputy director for
investigations.
   The realignment was made to meet ``increasingly complex
responsibilities and the need to meet future challenges,'' Sessions
said in a statement.
   Sessions said that as deputy director, Clarke has the authority
to resolve management issues across divisional lines and will chair
the bureau's Senior Executive Service selection board.
   Clarke, Otto and Revell will continue to be part of the
director's advisory board on strategy, policy and planning, Sessions
said.
   Revell, 50, was criticized by some members of Congress for his
defense of the FBI's controversial surveillance of the Committee In
Solidarity with the People of El Salvador (CISPES) in the early
1980s.
   Revell's defense of the operation came several months before
Sessions acknowledged on Capitol Hill last year that the bureau had
overstepped its bounds by gathering intelligence on domestic
political organizations.
   Six FBI officials were disciplined as a result of the CISPES
investigation. No action was taken against Revell.
   Revell will continue to oversee criminal investigations, foreign
counterintelligence and counterterrorism programs as well as the FBI
laboratory.
   Clarke, who had been a protege of Revell, was named deputy
assistant director of the criminal investigative division in 1982
and became assistant director for criminal investigations in 1985.
   Previously, he had headed the FBI's Philadelphia field office and
had served as an administrative assistant to the attorney general
during the Ford administration.
   The No. 2 position, officially known as the associate director,
has been vacant since the early 1980s with the retirement of James
B. Adams.
</TEXT>
