<FIRST>r w AM-US-IsraelLetter     07-18 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israel Letter,250</SECOND>
<UNK>Report Bush Urged Shamir to Give Up `Greater Israel'</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush wrote a letter to Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir echoing the statement of Secretary of State
James A. Baker III that the idea of a ``greater Israel'' should be
abandoned, National Public Radio said Tuesday.
   Baker's exhortation, contained in a speech May 22, was attacked
by friends of Israel in Congress.
   The network said the president endorsed Baker's call on Israel to
give up any idea of annexation of the West Bank of the Jordan River,
occupied by Israeli troops since 1967, to stop new settlements in
that territory and to reopen Palestinian schools.
   At the White House, spokesman Robert Hall declined to say
anything about a letter from the president but added: ``That all
sounds like U.S. policy.''
   Reporter Daniel Schorr said the letter, sent at the end of June,
reiterated U.S. opposition to creating a Palestinian state, support
for secure Israeli borders, an undivided Jerusalem and assurance
that Israel's military advantage over its Arab enemies would be kept.
   He added it was designed, at the suggestion of 11 leaders in the
U.S. Senate, to help Shamir resist opposition within his own Likud
Party against the plan for an election in the disputed area of
representatives who would then negotiate with the Israeli government.
   Shamir then made a speech adopting conditions urged by other
Likud leaders: continued Jewish settlements in the area and a ban on
participation in the election by Palestinians living in Jerusalem.
   The conditions brought a threat from the Israeli Labor party to
pull out of Israel's coalition government.
</TEXT>
