<FIRST>u a AM-OilSpill 2ndLd-Writethru a0688 07-18 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0688,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tank Ruptures 15 Feet from Shore; Spills Up to 640,000 Gallons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to reflect that oil spilled from tunnel sted
storage tank; REVISES spill estimate, edits throughout to tighten. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT OESTRICHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unsealed tunnel leading from a storage
tank leaked up to 640,000 gallons of oil Tuesday, and nearly 300
gallons spilled into a waterway that leads to the Atlantic Ocean,
officials said.
   ``It wasn't sealed and why it wasn't sealed is something we are
looking into,'' said Coast Guard Capt. Robert C. North.
   Between 420,000 and 640,000 gallons of oil poured from the tank,
but most of it was contained on land by a system of earthen dikes,
said the Coast Guard and the state Department of Environmental
Protection.
   ``There's no threat to people,'' said North. ``We're concerned
about the environment if the tank should rupture.''
   Environmental department spokesman Gary Allen said the oil in the
water was confined to a 20-foot-by-80-foot area and was no more then
10 feet out to sea.
   Workers were vacuuming the oil from the Arthur Kill, the narrow
waterway separating New Jersey from the New York City borough of
Staten Island, using absorbent booms.
   ``It is free-flowing oil, so it should not take more then a day
to clean up,'' Allen said. He said the oil was fuel oil No. 6.
   The spill was reported at a tank owned by Northville Industries.
The tank is one of four near the edge of the Arthur Kill.
   North said the tunnel from which the oil leaked is used to carry
fuel from the storage tanks to barges and ships. Workers put a
makeshift clay seal at the mouth of the tunnel to cut seepage.
   Coast Guard spokesman Paul Milligan said the tank, which has a
capacity of 12.6 million gallons, was nearly full. The remaining oil
was transferred to other tanks and to barges.
   John Reiff, general manager at the Northville plant, said the
tank is 18 years old and was last inspected 7{ years ago.
</TEXT>
