<HEAD>Daughter of Newsday Editor Found Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT that Greene and his wife also have
a son, sted other daughter.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JAMES, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A daughter of a Newsday editor was found
dead in her home Tuesday, and police said she apparently had been
killed.
   The body of Lea Greene, 35, daughter of Newsday Assistant
Managing Editor Bob Greene, was found in her apartment by a neighbor
shortly before 9 a.m., Suffolk County police spokesman Randy Jared
said.
   The victim was in her bedroom and wearing nightclothes.
   ``We have definitely ruled out suicide,'' said Detective Sergeant
Kevin Cronin. ``This is a homicide we are investigating.''
   Cronin would not comment on what caused Ms. Greene's death. He
said there were no signs of a sexual assault. Jared said no weapons
were found in the house and there were no signs of a break-in.
   Ms. Greene, who was single and lived alone, was a nurse at
Community Hospital of Western Suffolk in Smithtown.
   Her father headed two teams that won Pulitzer Prizes. In 1970,
his team investigated political corruption on Long Island and in
1974 a team traced the route heroin takes from the Turkish poppy
fields to Long Island. In 1977, he won the John Peter Zenger press
freedom award.
   Greene and his wife, Kathleen, also have a son.
