<FIRST>r a AM-Bellmon-Taxes     07-18 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bellmon-Taxes,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Changes ``Revolutionary'' Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Henry Bellmon modified his day-old
school funding program that would all but abolish personal property
tax Tuesday, surrendering a plan to give a tax break on groceries.
   Bellmon proposed Monday to base school funding on a 15 percent
income tax surcharge on corporate and personal incomes and a new 2
percent school tax on goods and services.
   The governor said he made the proposal because the current
property tax is costly to administer and is not applied equally in
many counties.
   Bellmon's plan also called for eliminating the sales tax on
groceries. But the governor's office issued a statement Tuesday
saying the proposed exemption was being dropped because of
legislative objections.
   Bellmon also announced that the proposed new 2 percent gross
receipts tax earmarked for schools was being reduced to 1.9 percent.
   The plan has been called revolutionary by Education Secretary
Sandy Garrett because it eliminates local property taxes as a major
revenue source for funding schools. A drastically reduced property
tax would remain to retire any bonded indebtedness.
   The grocery tax exemption had been hailed by some as a selling
point for the program. But Bellmon said it drew objections during a
briefing session with legislators.
   He said the lawmakers were worried that some small cities, which
charge local sales taxes, could not survive the revenue loss from
exempting grocery sales.
   Oklahomans now pay a 4 percent state sales tax on grocery
purchases, in addition to municipal sales taxes. Bellmon said
grocery sales would be exempt under the new school gross receipts
tax.
   Bellmon's package also had included a 2 percent gross receipts
tax for cities, but he said that plan also will not be needed since
the grocery sales exemption was being deleted.
   He said the new program would provide an extra $245 million in
revenue, beginning in 1991, which amounts to an 8 percent increase
in the state budget.
   He has called the legislature to a special session beginning Aug.
14 to consider the plan.
   He said when it is fully implemented ``Oklahoma will be among the
leaders in educational excellence.''
   Under the Bellmon plan, the new school tax would redistributed to
counties on a per-pupil basis. The $847 million now going to schools
from the state's General Fund would continue to be distributed,
officials say.
   State Rep. Carolyn Thompson, chairman of the House Education
Committee, said legislators were ``trying to get some accurate
numbers'' to better analyze the program.
   ``There's no question it is a bold attempt to restructure our tax
policies and at this point it needs detailed analysis before public
policy decisions are made,'' she said.
</TEXT>
