<FIRST>u a AM-SpyTrial     07-18 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy Trial,0464</SECOND>
<UNK>Jury Sees Tape of Soldier Admitting Yildirim Paid Him for Secrets</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A videotape played for a jury Tuesday in a
spy trial showed a soldier telling an undercover agent that the
defendant in the case paid him ``a lot of money'' for military
secrets.
   The tape was played on the second day of Huseyin Yildirim's trial
on charges he conspired to sell U.S. defense documents to the
Soviets and East Germans. Yildirim, 61, is from Turkey and lives in
Belleair Beach, Fla.
   On the tape, Army Warrant Officer James W. Hall III is seen
telling an FBI agent, who posed as a Soviet agent named Vladimir,
that Yildirim was his only contact in the scheme.
   ``The money had increased. It was substantial,'' Hall told the
agent during a meeting near Savannah late last year. ``He was paying
me a lot of money. What I wanted to be able to do was to afford some
of the things I wanted. ... I didn't flaunt the money.''
   On the tape, ``Vladimir'' counted out $60,000 in bundles of
$5,000 each to Hall at the end of an almost two-hour meeting.
   ``Now listen, please be careful with this when you get home,''
Vladimir told Hall on the tape.
   Hall, 30, is expected to testify later in the trial. He was
sentenced to 40 years in prison and fined $50,000 after pleading
guilty during a March court-martial to charges of espionage,
attempted espionage and failure to obey Army regulations.
   Yildirim is accused of helping Hall sell secrets to East German
and Soviet agents between 1983 and 1988, when Hall was stationed in
West Germany and New Jersey. Yildirim worked as a civilian mechanic
at an Army-run auto shop in West Berlin while Hall was there.
   The trial is being held in Savannah because Hall was stationed at
nearby Fort Stewart when he was arrested last December.
   Two Defense Department experts are at the trial to ensure that no
classified material is discussed. The videotape shown Tuesday was
edited to remove references to classified information, prosecutors
said.
   On the recording, Hall complained that his spy activity decreased
after he was transferred from Germany to New Jersey.
   ``In New Jersey, I was very busy,'' he said. ``I was with my wife
and children. ... The people I worked with were counterintelligence
people. They were very suspicious by their nature.''
   Army officials began investigating the case last summer after
being tipped that Hall, who had recently been promoted from staff
sergeant to warrant officer, was living a lifestyle his salary of
$20,200 could not support.
   Hall admitted to Army officials that he received more than
$100,000 between 1983 and 1988 for classified documents.
</TEXT>
