<DOCNO> AP890718-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpacePlans 3rdLd-Writethru a0796 07-18 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Plans, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0796,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Asked to Establish Moon Base, Start Mars Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf: ``But if,'' to restore dropped ``he''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has before him a recommendation
to call for a permanent human outpost on the moon, to be used to
launch a manned mission to Mars, it was learned Tuesday night.
   The recommendation is contained in the draft of a major speech
the president is to give on Thursday, the 20th anniversary of the
day Neil Armstong took his ``giant leap for mankind'' on the moon
during the Apollo 11 mission.
   Bush said Tuesday that he had not decided what he would say on
Thursday.
   But if he accepts the speech before him, he will call for study
to begin on a multi-billion dollar project that would entail
building a permanent manned moon station and launching the first
manned flight to Mars from it, said a knowledgeable administration
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Bush also is expected to make a push for renewed funds for the
earth-orbiting space station, which is suffering congressional cuts
to the budget Bush proposed for it.
   One option that had been considered, a joint space mission with
the Soviets, is not in the recommendations Bush is reviewing, the
official said.
   Neither cost estimates nor a timetable was contained in the
moon-Mars proposal as drafted, but the venture would cost hundreds
of billions of dollars over decades.
   The source described Vice President Dan Quayle, who chairs Bush's
advisory National Space Council, as the driving force behind the
proposal, put together with the help of the council staff.
   The vice president has been briefing members of Congress and
industry leaders on what such a project might entail, the official
said.
   In California, where he is making a series of speeches, Quayle
did not divulge what Bush might say Thursday. But he fanned the
speculation by saying the Bush administration ``is moving forward to
put the pieces in place for another great leap forward in space.''
   He said the nation ``must begin to think about the voyage of a
new Mayflower _ about expanding the human presence into the solar
system _ as a long-term goal.''
   The only specifics he mentioned regarding White House plans for
space were three projects already announced _ asking Congress to
support Space Station Freedom, a new Earth observation satellite and
the national aerospace plane.
   Quayle's goal and that of other boosters of rejuvenation of the
space program is ``to give the space program a mission again, so it
gets the funding it deserves,'' the official said.
   Space boosters have been calling for the president to make a bold
proposal akin to President John F. Kennedy's 1961 pledge to put a
man on the moon by the end of the 1960s, a pledge that Armstrong
kept on July 20, 1969.
   Other sources said White House officials preparing Bush's
Thursday message on space asked for extensive briefings on plan
drafted by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration called
``Mission to Planet Earth,'' a proposal for an intense environmental
study of the planet from space.
   The Planet Earth project calls for an intensive study of the
Earth and its environment, using data gathered by sophisticated
satellites and by scientists and instruments orbiting aboard the
space shuttle.
   ``There was talk that by supporting the Mission to Planet Earth
the President could help his image as the environmental president,''
a NASA source said.
   Bush, returning from Europe aboard Air Force One, was asked
Tuesday about his space speech, but gave no indication about what
his plans were.
   The president said he did not know if his announcement would be
``a big space announcement'' or simply ``an event commemorating
those (Apollo) years.''
   Bush added: ``I'm not ready to say whether we're going to have a
new space initiative. I want to be sure that what I propose passes
any test of fiscal sanity, fiscal reasonableness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
