<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Infotainment Adv.19   07-18 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Infotainment, Adv.19,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, July 19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Re-creations' to Be Part of New NBC News Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Network news will enter the questionable world
of ``re-creations'' this coming season on CBS and NBC.
   The cast and producer of NBC's new ``Yesterday, Today and
Tomorrow,'' as well as the news division's president, argued before
a meeting of television critics that there's nothing wrong with TV
news re-creating news events, though such dramatizations have
heretofore been the bailiwick of ``infotainment'' shows like
``America's Most Wanted'' and ``A Current Affair'' on Fox and NBC's
``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   ``It's just another way of telling a story, the same way
newspapers use graphics, they use other ways to reconstruct,'' said
NBC News President Michael Gartner.
   ``When we do re-creations, we will do them, I assure you,
responsibly, clearly labeled, and very cautiously,'' said Mary Alice
Williams, one of the three co-hosts of the new show.
   ``We will only use them when there is no other way to convey the
story, when there is no other archival footage for this. We might
compare it to, as you know in a federal court, you still can't bring
cameras in, and so we have courtroom sketch artists.''
   CBS' ``West 57th'' also plans to use re-creations this coming
season as part of a revamping of the show that includes the addition
of anchor Connie Chung.
   Chuck Scarborough, another co-host of the new NBC show, along
with Maria Shriver, said he did have ``trepidations'' about the use
of re-creations, but in fact had himself once used a dramatization
in a story he did on a murder _ which elicited a letter of complaint
from an NBC executive in charge of the local New York NBC station
for which Scarborough works.
   ``I think all of us have other assignments within NBC News, and
no one wants to damage their credibility,'' said Shriver.
   Executive producer Sid Feders suggested re-creations are ``a
natural next step'' in television news. ``We have done artist's
renderings, we have done animations and drawings. I think an
audience is sophisticated enough and ready for it. People aren't
dumb out there.''
   The questioning of the ``YTT'' group followed a press conference
by Gartner, who announced that former ``Saturday Night Live''
producer and current NBC Sports President Dick Ebersol would be
taking on additional duties in the news division overseeing the
``Today'' show. Some critics in the audience felt that the No. 1
entertainment network was blurring the lines between entertainment
and news.
   ``I'm going to work for Michael,'' said Ebersol, ``I'm working
for a newsman. (Gartner is a former newspaper editor who joined NBC
last year.) And when you talk about shows and so forth, let's keep
in mind that all the network news heads today, with the exception of
Michael, did not start in news. One started in politics (CBS' David
Burke) and another one started as the pre-eminent sports producer of
our time (ABC's Roone Arledge).''
   ``The sports department of The New York Times certainly talks to
the metro desk ... I just say, I don't believe in artificial
barriers, but I believe very, very strongly in principles and
guidelines,'' said Gartner.
   Gartner said being the news division in the No. 1 entertainment
network made it harder to get news shows into prime time.
   ``Now there's no question that CBS and ABC have, let's say, a
mediocre prime-time schedule ...,'' he said. ``Those networks,
therefore, are constantly coming to the news division saying, will
you give us something? ... It's cheaper to do a news show, and
that's why they have an easier time.''
   Speaking of NBC, he added, ``The overall robustness of the
network rebounds to the benefit of the news division.''
   ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'' will premiere Aug. 2 as a
series of specials. NBC has not had a weekly prime-time news shows
since ``1986'' went off the air at the end of that year.
   CBS has ``60 Minutes,'' ``48 Hours'' and ``West 57th.'' ABC has
``20-20'' and the new ``Prime Time'' with Diane Sawyer and Sam
Donaldson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   PEACOCK BECOMING STORK? _ Sid Feders, executive producer of NBC's
new prime-time news show ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow,'' has an
unusual timing problem: Two-thirds of his three anchors are
expecting babies. Maria Shriver and husband Arnold Schwarzenegger
are expecting in December, and Mary Alice Williams and her husband
are expecting in January. The show starts Aug. 2. The third
co-anchor is Chuck Scarborough, who has not announced any impending
births.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, July 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
