<DOCNO> AP890718-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-TassInterns Adv25   07-18 1068</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tass Interns, Adv 25,1099</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday AMs, July 25, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hands-On Journalism Experience _ The Soviet Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vincent Melomo wants to be a journalist and was
thrilled to land an internship with a worldwide news agency. But
he's uneasy, even anxious.
   The news agency is Tass, the Soviet wire service.
   ``I have strong reservations about working for any government
organization that's primarily a propaganda device,'' said the
20-year-old history major. ``But that was overcome by saying, well,
I have to see it, see how it works, see what my involvement is
before I can really make such lofty decisions.''
   For the first time, the New York bureau of Tass has taken on
American university students as unpaid summer interns covering
metropolitan news. The agency hopes to spruce up its image in the
United States and help turn its English-language service into a
moneymaking enterprise.
   To that end, Tass also has hired Irene Stevenson, 28, a graduate
student of Slavic studies at the University of Texas, to edit its
English-language wire at its Moscow headquarters. She is to start
work in September.
   ``We are trying to show that we are not really the voice of the
government,'' said Igor Y. Makurin, the New York bureau chief. ``The
government told us: `You are on your own. You have to earn your
living.' We have to find means to be self-sufficient, to earn our
money, to pay our bills, to pay our lunch.''
   Tass' English-language wire has 11 U.S. customers, including The
New York Times, The Associated Press, the United Nations and several
databanks. But that isn't enough to make the service profitable. And
Makurin described two recent efforts to market the wire in the
United States as ``a disaster.''
   In 1987, Tass sent brochures and letters to 3,000 U.S. radio
stations; out of eight to 10 responses, none signed on. Last year,
it contacted 75 newspapers and eight agreed to a free two-month
subscription. All canceled after that.
   One criticism was that the English Tass was putting on the wire
was unfit for American consumption, Makurin said. ``You write a
story in Russian and then the guy in Moscow translates it into
English. And the service sometimes is very clumsy, the translation
is clumsy, and a ... lot of mistakes.
   ``Sometimes our subscribers call us and ask, `What do you mean by
saying this?' or `Something is funny.''' For example, ``Passover''
was once translated as ``Jewish history,'' he said.
   Enter the American students.
   The interns started working on Memorial Day. The three American
undergraduates and one Swedish graduate student, all of whom are
studying at local universities, were selected from six applicants.
   During their first week, the interns wrote about the Van Cliburn
International Piano Competition in Fort Worth, Texas, whose
semifinalists included three Soviet pianists; a Soviet-American
sailing expedition; and a recent anthology of Soviet and American
writers, ``The Human Experience.''
   The students hope their stories will be used by a news
organization in one of the 115 countries that have Tass subscribers.
   ``When I write a story I imagine that it might be picked up in an
African country that relies on Tass for information,'' said Sofia
Gustafsson, 29, a graduate journalism student at New York University
and U.N. tour guide.
   ``I probably don't realize the importance of the whole thing,''
said Laura Yow, 19, of suburban Philadelphia, who will be a
sophomore at Barnard College. ``It's just a place that I go and I am
working for them.''
   ``I don't look at it as a Soviet-American thing, but as a
journalism thing,'' said Miss Yow, who is working mornings at Tass
and afternoons selling crystal and china at Tiffany's, a five-minute
walk up Fifth Avenue from Tass' offices in Rockefeller Plaza.
   Miss Gustafsson agreed. ``It seems to me like any other news
service. All the big papers are here, the press releases seem to
arrive, calls are made. The things that I would expect to find in
any news organization are here.''
   But Melomo, who will be a senior at Adelphi University in the
fall, does not consider Tass just any news organization. And,
although he is reluctant to admit it, he is having second thoughts
about working there.
   ``I consider myself a progressive sort of person and I like to be
contributing to whatever societal progress we are having between the
two countries. And if I can help any way I suppose this is it.''
   And yet, he is skeptical.
   ``My father once worked for the government and he had to get a
security clearance and there's a lot that goes into that. And he
warned me to at least investigate this,'' said Melomo, whose family
lives in Knoxville, Tenn.
   ``Plus, I know in certain areas of the country, in the more
conservative South I don't know how they would welcome someone who
worked for Tass. I'm just aware of other people and other times and
how this thing would be viewed rather than just right now, when
everything seems so harmonious. Times change.''
   But for now the times are good.
   In the last few years, Soviet-American relations have changed
dramatically and so, too, has the operation of Tass, said Makurin,
who has worked in the New York bureau for nine years and been its
chief since 1987.
   Two to three years ago, most story assignments were made in
Moscow; now the bureau can file directly on the Russian wire without
editing in Moscow.
   ``We decide here what kind of story we'll write here. We've got
freedom of choice,'' said Makurin, a warm, genial man. The students
have taken to him and respect his editorial judgment. He reads their
stories and edits them.
   ``I know what is the news and I try to show them how to make
their stories readable. But I don't want to force anything.''
   What does Makurin want the Americans to take away from their
three months?
   ``Something good about Tass. That we're not bad guys.
   ``I want them to find out the way we work in the United States.
... It should be educational for them. Especially at the present
time, when relations between the two countries are not that bad.
   ``Maybe it could improve our relations, not on the official level
but on the level of common people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday AMs, July 25</NOTE>
