<DOCNO> AP890718-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-TheBushEvolution Adv23-2Takes   07-18 0980</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The Bush Evolution, Adv 23 - 2 Takes,1007</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Over Six Months, Bush Has Edged Away From Reagan Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few weeks after Ronald Reagan was shot in
1981 by a would-be assassin, he was asked if he now favored gun
control. No, he said, it doesn't do any good.
   A few weeks after a man opened fire with an AK-47 in a schoolyard
in Stockton, Calif., George Bush, who had come to office just as
adamant as Reagan on gun control, switched signals.
   His administration imposed a temporary ban, now made permanent,
on imports of semiautomatic weapons deemed to have no legitimate
sporting purposes.
   Slowly, without calling attention to the process, the Bush
administration has turned away from positions firmly held by Ronald
Reagan and warmly endorsed in 1988 by candidate Bush.
   In place of a ``Reagan evolution'' is a Bush evolution.
   Now, six months after Bush stepped into 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue,
there's evidence aplenty that the new conservative president has
parted company from the old conservative president.
   On Mideast policy, pollution issues, the minimum wage, the
defense budget, budgetary matters in general; on Star Wars and the
sale of oil leases, aid to the Contras and fuel economy standards
for automobiles, Bush has abandoned the Reagan agenda for his own
positions. Usually they are more to the left of where Reagan stood.
   Political analysts aren't surprised.
   ``Some change is inevitable,'' says C. Lowell Harris, former
executive director of the Academy of Political Science. ``After four
or eight years, there are bound to be occasions where new looks at
things _ even by people who are fundamentally sympathetic to the
earlier policies _ are inevitable.''
   Stephen Hess, a political scientist at the Brookings Institution,
says a vice president, after years in the shadows, has a visceral
need ``to show his differences, to show a streak of independence''
when he takes over as No. 1.
   ``Bush would say there is more that's alike than different, and
he would probably be right,'' Hess says, ``but what's different is
what's interesting and what makes news.''
   William Schneider of the American Enterprise Institute says each
man revealed his own character in his presidency.
   Reagan was ``an agenda president'' who appointed people like
Edward Meese III, Jeane Kirkpatrick, Elliott Abrams, Oliver North to
carry out his agenda _ and theirs, he says.
   Bush, on the other hand, is an ``in-basket president _ you figure
out what the problems are and you deal with them.''
   Here are some places where Bush has abandoned Reagan policies:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CONTRA AID. Reagan once summed up his policy toward the leftist
Nicaraguan government in two words: ``Say Uncle.'' For eight years,
he did whatever he could to help the Contras overthrow that
government. When Congress cut off funds for military aid, the
Iran-Contra affair resulted.
   Just two months into office, Bush struck a deal with Congress
that gave up Reagan's goal. The new president made it clear he was
willing to accept a future in which the leftist Sandinistas remain
in power in Managua.
   Much like a treaty between nations, a four-page agreement was
signed by Bush and congressional leaders after secret negotiations
on Capitol Hill by Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   It provided $4.5 million a month in non-lethal aid to the
Contras, chiefly intended to encourage them to return home and
battle the Sandinistas in the political rather than the military
arena. Even that limited aid would be cut off automatically if the
Contras engaged in military attacks or cross-border incursions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   STAR WARS: With great fanfare, in a television speech to the
nation on March 23, 1983, Reagan announced plans for a space-based
defense system against intercontinental missiles _ the system that
became known as Star Wars.
   ``I've become more and more deeply convinced that the human
spirit must be capable of rising above dealing with other nations
and human beings by threatening their existence,'' said a president
whose commitment to the idea was evident to anyone watching.
   Billions of dollars later, Bush appears to be edging away from
the Reagan commitment. The first clue of that came from John G.
Tower, while he was still hopeful of being confirmed as secretary of
defense.
   Tower testified that he personally did not believe ``that we can
devise an ... umbrella that can protect the entire American
population from nuclear incineration.''
   An ``umbrella'' exactly like that was the Star Wars goal that
Reagan envisioned.
   Bush cut spending on the program to $4.6 billion for fiscal 1990,
down from the $5.9 billion Reagan had proposed. Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney also announced that Bush would shift the focus of Star
Wars from deployment sometime in the 1990s to research on a more
advanced system known as ``Brilliant Pebbles,'' consisting of 3,000
to 5,000 small orbiting satellites, each capable of tracking and
destroying an intercontinental ballistic missile.
   Whether Bush will be any more willing than Reagan to use Star
Wars as a bargaining chip in arms control negotiations with the
Soviets remains to be seen.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MIDEAST: The Reagan administration opened contacts with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, but was careful to go no further
than nudge the Israelis toward seeking a settlement with the Arabs.
Substance did not change, but emphasis did in the Bush
administration.
   The nudge became a shove when Baker replaced Secretary of State
George P. Shultz.
   Two speeches show the change in tone.
   Shultz, on Sept. 16, 1988: ``Israel will never negotiate from or
return to the lines of partition. But it must be prepared to
withdraw ... from territories occupied in the recent conflict.''
   Baker, on May 22, telling Israel to ``forswear annexation'' of
the occupied territories: ``Now is the time to lay aside, once and
for all, the unrealistic vision of a greater Israel.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-TheBushEvolution Adv23-1stAdd   07-18 1002</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The Bush Evolution, Adv 23 - 1st Add,1028</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: greater Israel.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   BUDGET: A state of budgetary warfare existed for most of the
Reagan presidency between the White House and the
Democratic-controlled Congress. After months of stalemate, the
October 1987 stock market crash _ which was fed by concern over
federal deficits _ made both sides agree they had no choice but to
compromise.
   The result was a budget accord that Reagan, swallowing hard,
signed off on. It provided for new taxes that he had opposed and
cuts in defense spending.
   When Reagan left office, Bush inherited a Reagan budget proposal
that called for more growth in military spending. Bush revised it:
The Pentagon budget would stay abreast of inflation but not grow
beyond it.
   Taking a cue from Bush's inaugural address _ ``To my friends, and
yes I do mean friends, in the loyal opposition, and yes, I do mean
loyal, I put out my hand'' _ Bush's budget negotiators quickly
struck a deal with Congress.
   Bush accepted even less for the military and more for domestic
programs, bragging of a budget compromise that for the first time
was ``reached ahead of schedule and not framed in the context of a
crisis.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GUN CONTROL: Each time he was asked if the shooting by John
Hinckley hadn't changed his mind on gun control, Reagan said no. He
said Hinckley broke a District of Columbia law, and more laws
wouldn't make any difference.
   That view was shared by Bush, too, when he took office, but the
new president changed his tune. Before he did so, his wife took a
stand.
   In the aftermath of the Stockton, Calif., schoolyard shooting
that left five children dead and 29 wounded, Barbara Bush said she
``absolutely'' favored a ban on semiautomatic assault-style weapons.
   Even then, Bush held firm. But a public outcry _ joined in by
police _ over the widespread availability of semiautomatic weapons
changed the atmosphere. The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
responded. It froze, then banned, imports of those weapons which it
said were not suitable for sport.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ENVIRONMENT: Midway in his presidency, Reagan called his
environmental record ``one of the best kept secrets in Washington.''
But even Anne Burford, his first head of the Environmental
Protection Agency and herself a target of environmentalists'
criticism, became a critic of Reagan's record.
   ``We don't have an environmental policy in this administration,''
she said three years after leaving office.
   Bush said in June that it is time to ``break the stalemate that
has hindered progress on clean air for the past decade'' and
announced proposals for revising the Clean Air Act, unchanged for a
dozen years.
   Bush's program is intended to clean up the smog in most cities by
the year 2000 and sharply reduce the forest- and lake-killing
pollution known as acid rain. It provides for a 50 percent reduction
in sulfur dioxide emissions from coal-burning power plants that are
a chief cause of acid rain. It also calls for a phase-in of cars
powered by methanol and a requirement that industry use new
technology to curb the release of cancer-causing chemicals.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said the Bush proposal was
the most positive move by the United States in a decade of Canadian
complaints about acid rain.
   The Bush administration also has proposed higher fuel economy
standards for automobiles, standards that Reagan had tried to
eliminate outright.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OIL LEASE SALES: Reagan had proposed leasing three areas off the
coasts of northern and southern California and southern Florida for
oil exploration. Preparations were under way when Reagan left office.
   Bush held the leases up pending a review of the environmental
consequences. Said Bush: ``Should the task force report indicate
significant adverse environmental effects that have not been
previously identified, a decision will be made to delay further or
cancel the sale.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MINIMUM WAGE: From Franklin Roosevelt to Jimmy Carter, the
minimum wage was increased under every president until Reagan. It
was fixed at $3.35 an hour when Reagan took office in 1981 and it
remained there when he left. Reagan proposed a lower rate for young
people _ $2.50 _ but no increase for other workers.
   Bush retained the idea of a lower minimum for youth _ this time
dubbed a ``training wage'' _ but announced his willingness to accept
an increase in the minimum wage to $4.25 over three years.
   Democrats in Congress pushed through an increase to $4.55 with a
subminimum to be paid workers with less than two months' work
experience. Bush vetoed the bill and Congress failed to override.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   R. Gordon Hoxie, president of the New York-based Center for the
Study of the Presidency, thinks the nation is now seeing the real
George Bush.
   ``Prior to 1980, there was a great difference between him and
Reagan, so he had to always submerge those differences,'' Hoxie said.
   ``Bush's whole approach to things is different,'' he says. ``He's
far more of a hands-on president than his predecessor.''
   ``I think this president is much more sensitive to minority group
interests and I think he's going to make headway with blacks and
Hispanics,'' Hoxie adds, calling attention to one more area of
difference.
   Bush paid tribute to the late Martin Luther King as ``an American
hero.'' In 1983, Reagan was asked about charges by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., that King had communist sympathies. Referring to future
declassification of Justice Department records, Reagan replied:
``We'll know in about 35 years, won't we?'' He subsequently
apologized to King's widow.
   Hess says Bush, no matter how he departs from Reagan's record, is
careful to pay homage to Reagan.
   ``There will be a time when George Bush needs Ronald Reagan. In a
mid-term election, he may wish to use Reagan, or if there's a severe
economic downturn,'' Hess says.
   ``So he's got to be very attentive personally while making the
proper separations politically. That's the trick.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun July 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
