<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-18 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0860</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business sales were virtually flat in May while
inventories rose 0.7 percent, the government said. Some analysts
predicted further production cutbacks during the rest of the year.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that inventories held on
shelves and backlots climbed to a seasonally adjusted $776.9 billion
in May after a 0.8 percent rise in April.
   The pace of business sales, on the other hand, hardly moved,
rising a minuscule 0.02 percent to a seasonally adjusted $517.9
billion. Sales had risen 2.0 percent in April after holding steady
in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. will acquire 67 percent
of the stock in Marion Laboratories Inc. under a tentative
transaction that gives the drug company a stock market value of $5.2
billion.
   The deal announced Monday, if completed, will create a new
publicly traded company consisting of Marion Laboratories and
Cincinnati-based Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, which is now a Dow
Chemical subsidiary.
   The new company, although majority-owned by Dow Chemical, would
be based in Marion's hometown of Kansas City and called Marion
Merrell Dow Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has closed its office
in Spain after determining it had improperly sold to private
institutions shares in a large European oil company that were
intended for individual investors.
   Drexel, which has agreed to plead guilty to U.S. securities law
violations and revamp internal compliance procedures, said it shut
the office Monday independently of an investigation by Spanish
officials into the stock sales during a partial privatization of
Repsol SA earlier this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After canceling a full merger, Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. said it would buy the retail brokerage offices and
customer accounts of the struggling Wall Street firm Thomson
McKinnon Inc.
   The deal Monday comes one month after the investment firms
announced a merger agreement, which was scrapped late last week.
Prudential-Bache, the nation's fourth-largest securities firm, will
acquire Thomson McKinnon's retail business with 2,000 retail brokers
at 154 offices in the United States and abroad.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese government company has given an
American camera maker the right to lease 60 million square feet of
land for up to 25 years and sublease it to other foreign firms that
want to manufacture in China.
   The Concord Camera Corp. signed the unusual agreement Monday in
Hong Kong with the Wan Kong Economic Development Corp. of Baoan
County.
   The deal appears to be an attempt by China to help regain the
confidence of Western investors following the June crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators that left hundreds of people dead.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. shares fell as investors dumped the
stock on expectations the media giant would win its fight against
Paramount Communications Inc.'s $12.2 billion hostile takeover bid.
   Time's stock fell $4.25 to $141 a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Monday, after dropping $4.75 on Friday.
   Warner Communications Inc. rose $1.12{ to $65.37{ a share as
investors became more confident that Time's $14 billion tender offer
for Warner would succeed. Paramount stock fell $1.25 to $56.25 a
share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Cummins Engine Co.'s founding
family paid $72 million for Hanson PLC's holdings in the company,
ending speculation that the British conglomerate might try to take
over the diesel-engine maker, officials said.
   The family members then exchanged the shares with Cummins for $67
million in notes, the officials said Monday.
   Hanson Industries, the American arm of Hanson, maintained all
along that its purchase of 9.79 percent of Cummins stock was for
investment purposes only.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought-reduced crops and higher market prices
have helped cut sharply the government's investment in surplus farm
commodities, an Agriculture Department report said.
   The department's Commodity Credit Corp. had $13.5 billion
invested in price support loans and actual inventories as of May 31.
That included $9.1 billion in loans outstanding, and $4.4 billion in
government-owned commodities, a report issued Monday said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   London's Stock Exchange has indicated it will
conduct a routine investigation into trading of BAT Industries PLC
shares and options that took place before last Tuesday's hostile $21
billion bid for the British conglomerate.
   Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith, joined by British
investor Jacob Rothschild and Australian entrepreneur Kerry Packer,
offered the equivalent of $13.69 a share in securities for BAT. The
tobacco and retailing giant quickly rejected the bid.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices settled for a mixed showing Monday as the market's
July rally flattened out after nine consecutive gains in the Dow
Jones industrial average. The Dow Jones industrials average fell
1.33 to 2,553.49.
   The dollar declined against most major currencies except the
Japanese yen.
   Interest rates jumped as bond prices fell.
   Grain and soybeans futures prices plummeted on the Chicago Board
of Trde; coffee was sharply lower; oil prices rallied; and cattle
futures climbed.
</TEXT>
