<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EEC-UnitedStates     07-18 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EEC-United States,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Agrees To Continue U.S. Beef Hormone Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of the European
Community have agreed to continue talks with the United States
seeking to defuse the sensitive issue of the EEC's ban on
hormone-treated meat.
   Their decision Monday was a compromise between Britain's softer
line and Italy's harder one.
   Announcing the decision, the EEC vice president for foreign
affairs, Frans Andriessen, said the trade bloc would increase its
efforts to import U.S. certified, non-hormone-treated beef.
   Andriessen reiterated the EEC criticism of what it views as
unilateral U.S. action, both in the hormone dispute and in a
conflict over EEC soybean imports.
   ``We continue to contest unilateral actions taken by the U.S.,''
he said.
   Britain had proposed exempting ox-tongues, a popular food there,
from the hormone ban. British officials said that could have
restored as much as $40 million of the $100 million a year the U.S.
has estimated it is losing from the EEC ban.
   That might have enabled the U.S. to reduce its retaliatory duties
on $100 million worth of EEC goods, British officials said.
   But Andriessen said the 12 EEC foreign ministers decided against
the British proposal because it would have required a change in EEC
laws, and would have damaged the credibility of the ban on hormones.
   An Italian proposal for the EEC to erect counter-measures against
the U.S. retaliatory duties was also rejected as unwise, Andriessen
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 0236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-USSprint     07-18 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US Sprint,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sprint to Lower Long-Distance Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   US Sprint said it would lower its evening
long-distance rates 25.6 percent Aug. 1 for its new Sprint Plus
calling plan.
   Sprint also said Monday it would give up to $25 of free
long-distance calls to anyone who signs up for Sprint Plus before
Oct. 23.
   The rate reduction will apply to calls made between 5 and 11 p.m.
weekdays. Sprint said the new rates offer customers average savings
of 34 percent when compared with the Reach Out America plan provided
by American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
   Sprint said it was reducing from $15 to $8 the minimum amount of
long-distance or directory-assistance calls a customer must make to
be eligible for the Sprint Plus rates.
   The plan offers free 5 percent volume discounts when a customer
makes more than $25 in daytime long-distance calls. Free
evening-night-weekend volume discounts range from 10 percent for
bills of $25 to $100 up to 20 percent on bills of $200 or more.
   Sprint introduced Sprint Plus on June 1. MCI began offering its
own preferred-calling plan for residential and small business
customers in May, and AT&amp;T recently lowered its rates for Reach Out
America.
</TEXT>
