<SECOND>PM-Dean Witter,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brokerage Beefs Up Research Area; Some Layoffs Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dean Witter Financial Services Group Inc. says it
will expand its stock research capabilities, doubling the number of
companies it tracks, in a restructuring that will include up to 40
layoffs.
   Dean Witter said Monday the move is designed to improve the
company's retail brokerage business at its branch offices and to try
to stimulate more corporate finance activity.
   Spokesman Jim Flynn said the company, parent of the investment
firm Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., the nation's third-largest retail
brokerage, would increase the number of analysts who follow
companies to about 70 from about 45 now.
   Philip J. Purcell, Dean Witter's chairman and chief executive
officer, said in a memo to employees that Dean Witter eventually
would track 1,300 publicly traded companies, compared with about 500
now.
   ``These initiatives are designed to provide additional equity
products for our account executives and clients, enhance the support
for our corporate finance growth and provide more effective
institutional client service,'' Purcell said.
   He said Dean Witter would be ``effecting modest staff
reductions.''
   Flynn said 30 to 40 layoffs were expected in the company's
equities division over the next six months. The area now has about
500 employees, he said.
   Flynn said Dean Witter hoped that by increasing the number of
companies tracked and improving contact with those companies, it
could stimulate activity in the firm's corporate finance department.
   ``We have been building our investment banking professional staff
and capabilities and this new alignment in research will only serve
to bolster our efforts,'' Purcell said.
   Dean Witter, which is owned by Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co., has more
than 24,000 employees, including 17,000 in its investment services
operations and 7,000 in its Discover credit card operation.
