<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Spain Bjt   07-18 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Spain, Bjt,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel Closes Madrid Office Due to Improper Stock Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., which has pledged to
toughen its securities law compliance, reacted swiftly to reports of
improper stock dealing at its Spanish office by closing down the
operation.
   ``We said some time ago that the new Drexel would not countenance
improper behavior, and we meant it,'' Drexel Chief Executive Fred
Joseph said in a statement Monday.
   Drexel, which has agreed to plead guilty to unrelated U.S.
securities law violations, said it determined the Madrid office had
told Spanish securities officials it would sell stock in a large
European oil company to individual investors but sold it to a few
private institutions instead.
   Drexel said it shut the office independently of an investigation
by Spanish officials into the stock sale during the partial
privatization of Repsol SA earlier this year.
   Drexel said it had determined that its Spanish affiliate, DBL
Capital Markets Espana SA in Madrid, used the names of 400
individual investors to obtain 97,600 shares of Repsol but sold the
stock to private institutions.
   The investment firm, which has offices worldwide, said all but
17,815 of the shares went to institutional clients and the rest went
into a trading account at Drexel. The firm said it made $123,069 in
commissions and trading profits on the transaction.
   Spain's National Securities Commission alleged that Drexel
falsified documents during Repsol's offer of 79.95 million shares at
the equivalent of $14.70 each, or a total of $1.14 billion. The
shares were sold to 400,000 investors worldwide from April 20 to May
6.
   In a filing with Spanish securities regulators, Drexel requested
a block of the shares worth about $60 million and said they would go
to the 400 individual investors. But officials said that on May 11,
the first day of public trading, Drexel improperly sold the shares
to the private institutions.
   Spanish regulators said last week that some of the 400 investors,
mainly friends and relatives of Drexel employees, were unaware their
names had been used as nominees for the stock in Repsol, Europe's
eighth-largest oil company.
   Results of the investigation in Spain have not been announced.
   Drexel could be fined up to five times the profit on the
transaction in the case, according to reports from Spain. Criminal
charges also are possible if Drexel used investors' names without
their permission, the reports said.
   Drexel said DBL Capital Markets Espana officials waited 10 days
before telling the parent company that Spanish authorities had
requested information about the Repsol transaction.
   Drexel also said it was withdrawing its application for a
brokerage license in Spain. The firm said Spanish authorities had
not requested the withdrawal.
   Drexel's Madrid office, which opened in 1987, employed 27 people.
   In his statement, Joseph said there were reports in Spain that
other firms in Madrid engaged in similar transactions during the
Repsol offering but ``that is something for Spanish authorities to
determine.''
   ``For Drexel, it is behavior which we find unacceptable and
cannot condone, and is clearly not the manner in which we plan to
conduct business,'' Joseph said.
   ``We recognize that the decision to close is a drastic step ...
however prompt response was called for,'' he said.
   Drexel last year agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a
record $650 million to settle U.S. securities law violations
stemming from the government's crackdown on Wall Street crime.
Drexel also agreed to overhaul its management and toughen its
internal compliance systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
