<FIRST>r f PM-Prudential-Thomson Bjt   07-18 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prudential-Thomson, Bjt,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prudential-Bache Got Bargain With Thomson McKinnon Units, Analysts
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a period of sluggish investor activity,
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. is getting a bargain by purchasing
the retail brokerage division of struggling Wall Street firm Thomson
McKinnon Inc., analysts say.
   After canceling a full merger, the two investment firms announced
Monday the sale that will add Thomson McKinnon's 2,000 brokers at
154 offices to Prudential-Bache's sales force of 6,000.
   The deal comes during a period of retrenchment on Wall Street and
sustained skepticism about whether individual investors scared off
by the 1987 stock market crash will ever return to the market in
pre-crash numbers. Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. recently sold its
entire retail unit to Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   ``If you acquire a firm with a lot of brokers it's an opportunity
to expand for a very low cost,'' said Brenda Davis McCoy, who
follows the securities industry for PaineWebber Inc.
   A merger agreement between the two investment firms announced
June 13 was scrapped Friday after Prudential-Bache discovered
problems with Thomson McKinnon's financial records.
   ``When it became clear a merger was not feasible, rather than
parting ways, we worked together to develop this new arrangement,''
Prudential-Bache Chairman George L. Ball and Thomson McKinnon
Chairman J. Ronald Morgan said in a statement.
   Prudential-Bache, the nation's fourth-largest securities firm,
will acquire Thomson McKinnon's retail business and customer
accounts. Officials said the combined retail sales force at
Prudential-Bache, which has more than 320 offices, would be trimmed
by an undetermined amount.
   Thomson McKinnon had 4,700 employees before the sale.
   Terms were not disclosed, but people familiar with the deal said
Prudential-Bache will pay $60 million up front plus another $60
million over three years in incentives designed to keep Thomson
McKinnon brokers from leaving.
   The sale effectively marks the end 104-year-old of Thomson
McKinnon, which has struggled since the market crash and repeatedly
entered into sale negotiations with other major brokerages.
   Thomson McKinnon officials said the firm planned to sell its
remaining assets, such as its capital markets, Hong Kong and
administrative operations, in the coming months.
   Among problems that led to scrapping the merger was a reported
$80 million difference between Thomson McKinnon's liabilities and
cash reserves. Weekend negotiations yielded the retail brokerage
deal.
   Prudential-Bache is the brokerage arm of Prudential Securities,
which is owned by Prudential Insurance Co. of America.
   Prudential-Bache also said it plans to purchase about 5 percent
of Thomson McKinnon Asset Management LP, the firm's only publicly
traded entity, which operates its money and investment management
business. The partnership's unit price closed down 50 cents at $10
in New York Stock Exchange trading Monday.
   Under the deal, Thomson McKinnon brokers will not be able to sell
Prudential-Bache money market mutual funds once they join that firm.
Officials said the split was designed to prevent brokers from
selling only Prudential-Bache funds and to keep the Thomson McKinnon
asset management fund alive.
   Thomson McKinnon brokers will continue to offer other non-money
market mutual funds managed by the asset management group. Also,
Prudential-Bache brokers will not sell Thomson McKinnon mutual funds.
   Last October, privately held Thomson McKinnon, the nation's
ninth-largest brokerage, said it was looking for a buyer to purchase
the 23 percent Thomson McKinnon stake owned by the Hartford
Insurance Group, a unit of ITT Corp.
   ITT spokesman Jim Gallagher said Monday the company may have to
increase to $27.5 million from $23 million the second-quarter
reserve it expects to take from the sale of Hartford Insurance's
stake in Thomson McKinnon, reducing ITT's earnings by 19 cents a
share.
   ITT said the size of the reserve depends on Thomson McKinnon's
ability to pay Hartford for the 23 percent stake. Under the aborted
June 13 merger agreement, Hartford was to sell back all its shares
to Thomson McKinnon.
</TEXT>
