<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-18 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Again Yen; Stocks Fall Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen today,
while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged for the
fifth straight trading day.
   The dollar ended at 142.35 yen, up 0.82 yen from Monday's
141.53-yen finish. The index started at 141.55 yen and moved between
141.43 and 142.50.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues shed 112.49
points, or 0.34 percent, closing at 33,343.73.
   The index has lost more than 400 points since Wednesday.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said
market players avoided buying issues ahead of a release of U.S trade
figures later today and a major national election in Japan on Sunday.
   ``Japanese market players have been very nervous about this
election because we haven't experienced anything this big
recently,'' he said.
   Although governing Liberal Democratic Party leaders say they will
win at least 54 seats of the 126 to be decided Sunday, analysts see
that as a tough goal to reach.
   The party has lost its popularity because of an
influence-peddling stock scandal, a new and unpopular sales tax, and
reports that Prime Minister Sousuke Uno kept paid mistresses.
   The market has been inactive for an extended period because of
fears that an election loss by the governing party would lead to a
market plunge, Nomura said. The market expects the U.S. trade
deficit will rise, he added.
   Trading was thin with first section volume estimated at 300
million shares, up from 230 million the previous day.
   In currency dealings, yen-selling pressure remained strong since
the dollar's higher opening today, but many market participants were
reluctant to make major moves before the U.S. trade report for May,
traders said.
   The dollar was bought mainly by overseas investors, said
Yoshitsugu Hanada, trader with Mitsui Bank.
   ``It was largely because the G-7 (Group of Seven industrial
nations) meeting in Paris didn't specify an appropriate range of the
dollar,'' he said. ``Becuase they just agreed only that the dollar
should be stable against other key currencies, it inspired
dollar-buying,'' Hanada said.
   Japan wants the dollar to stay between 130-140 yen, he added.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told a press conference today
that a slightly higher yen would be preferable.
   ``A slightly stronger yen would make things easier from several
points of view,'' he said.
   Although U.S. officials have indicated they are satisfied with
the current level of the dollar, Murayama said he disagrees with
that assessment.
</TEXT>
