<HEAD>Dollar Firmer, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was firmer in early European trading
today as market participants moved to the sidelines ahead of the
8:30 a.m. EDT release of U.S. merchandise trade figures for May.
   Gold prices eased.
   Dealers said the dollar's short-term direction appears to be up,
and several said they sensed it could move higher right away if the
trade figures are better than expected.
   ``We're in an upward trend that I think only very bad trade
numbers can stop,'' said Manfred Totzauer, a vice president at
Citibank in Frankfurt. ``I have a feeling that the data will be
better than expected.''
   Dealers said the dollar was also buoyed in earlier Asian trading
after two reported rounds of intervention by the Bank of Japan
failed to slow the dollar's rise against the yen.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.82 yen to a closing 142.35 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 142.52 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.9198 West German marks, up from 1.9138; 1.6620
Swiss francs, up from 1.6540; 6.5130 French francs, up from 6.4890;
2.1603 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1580; 1,391.45 Italian lire, up
from 1,387.50; 1.1905 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   In London, the dollar gained slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.6053 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6075 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $370.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $372.20. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $369.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $369.75, down from $370.75 late
Monday.
   The Hong Kong Gold and Silver Exchange was closed today by a
typhoon.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.27 a troy ounce,
down from Monday's $5.29.
