<FIRST>r f PM-CumminsEngine     07-18 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cummins Engine,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Founding Family Buys Back Cummins Engine Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of the founding family of
Cummins Engine Co., worldwide maker of diesel engines, have
repurchased more than 1 million shares of Cummins stock from Hanson
USA, easing the company's fears about a possible takeover.
   J. Irwin Miller, a Cummins director and former chief executive
officer, and his sister, Clementine M. Tangeman, purchased a 1.043
million-share holding of Cummins common stock for $72 million.
   The family said Monday it paid $5 million more than the going
price, based on Cummins' stock price before the purchase, to rid
itself of the uncertainty brought by the shareholder.
   Hanson, whose parent is the British conglomerate Hanson PLC which
makes Smith Corona typewriters and Farberware cookware, bought a
9.79 percent stake in Cummins in December, raising fears that the
company might move to get control of Cummins.
   Hanson officials, however, maintained that the stock had been
purchased only as an investment.
   Miller said the purchase reflects the family's confidence in the
company's future.
   ``It also reflects our conviction that the Cummins management
must be able to maintain its traditional long-term view of the
business in order to serve its customers in an era of worldwide
competition,'' Miller said.
   ``Cummins can best meet its responsibilities to its shareholders,
employees, customers, suppliers and communities alike as an
independent company,'' said Irwin, who was chief executive officer
from 1934 to 1973 and is chairman of the company's executive
committee.
   Cummins, which also makes diesel engine components and power
systems, was founded in 1919 by Will Irwin, the great uncle of
Miller and Ms. Tangeman, and by their grandmother, Linnie Sweeney.
   ``Five generations of my family were born here,'' Ms. Tangeman
said. ``I am interested in the long-term health of the company and
in having the company headquartered in Columbus, thriving and
independent.''
   Irwin's successor as chief exeuctive officer, Henry B. Schacht,
called the couple's investment ``an extraordinary vote of confidence
in Cummins' future and further proof of the wise and farsighted
stewardship that this family has provided to the company over the
past 70 years.''
   The investment nearly triples the couple's investment in the
company, according to a Cummins statement.
   The shares were exchanged with the company for $67 million
principal amount of newly issued Cummins notes. Miller, his wife,
Xenia, and Ms. Tangeman also exchanged their previous holdings of
Cummins common stock, 580,269 shares, for new Cummins preferred
stock valued at $37 million.
   Schacht said the company would try to obtain additional equity
capital from more long-term investors. The additional capital is
neeeded, he said, because of the reduction in equity involved in
issuing notes to the Miller family, the implementation of the
company's Employee Stock Ownership Plan and the company's intent to
implement a stock repurchase plan with ESOP proceeds.
   Also, more capital is needed to meet 1991 and 1994 federal diesel
engine emissions standards, he said.
   The company's second-quarter earnings will be released next
Monday. The company posted primary earnings of $1.61 per common
share in the first quarter of 1989.
</TEXT>
