<SECOND>PM-GM-Benefits,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Denies Benefits for Laid Off GM Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed a lawsuit
claiming that more than 3,000 laid-off Detroit area General Motors
Corp. workers were entitled to $5,000 apeice in federal benefits.
   U.S. District Judge George LaPlata ruled Monday that the workers,
most of whom lost their jobs when GM phased out two factories in
Detroit in late 1987 and early 1988, were ineligible for benefits
under the federal Trade Readjustment Act.
   The Labor Department denied the benefits, saying the workers
missed a filing deadline. The United Auto Workers union, which
represented the employees, contended they were unaware of the
deadline before it passed.
   Jess Damesworth, the union's director of unemployment, said the
benefits could be worth more than $5,000 per person.
   A UAW spokesman said officials were deciding whether to appeal.
