<FIRST>r f BC-World-Steel     07-18 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-World-Steel,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Steel Producers' Output Up 2.8 Percent In June, 3.7 Pc In 6
Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude Steel production in the
non-Communist world rose by 2.8 percent to 40.1 million tons in June
from the corresponding year-earlier month, according to the
International Iron and Steel Institute.
   In the first six months of 1989, output rose by 3.7 percent to
245.35 million tons from the year-earlier period
   The June rise was led by Japan where steel companies increased
output by 5 percent to 8.96 million tons from June 1988. Production
in the United States edged up by 1.6 percent to 7.4 million tons,
while in the European Community it increased by 2.6 percent to 11.9
million tons. Among other steel producing nations, South Korea
raised output by 16 percent to 1.8 million tons.
   The 33 nations reporting their output to the Brussels-based
Institute accounted for 61 percent of world production in 1988, and
for 97 percent of world production excluding the Soviet Union and
other East bloc nations, China and North Korea.
</TEXT>
