<FIRST>r f PM-Chicken-Manure     07-18 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicken-Manure,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Country Pride' Chicken Sues `Country Pride' Manure Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The producer of Country Pride chicken has
filed suit to keep from sharing its name with a brand of cow manure
fertilizer.
   ConAgra Inc., which produces Country Pride-brand chicken, filed a
lawsuit Monday in federal court against Earthgro Inc., which
produces Country Pride-brand manure, alleging the use of the name on
fertilizer has hurt chicken sales.
   Besides cow manure, the Lebanon, Conn., company sells Country
Pride composted cow manure, dehydrated cow manure, potting soil, top
soil, peat humus and sand.
   The lawsuit says Earthgro, which owns a plant in Avondale, Pa.,
is deliberately misleading the public into associating Country Pride
cow manure with Country Pride chicken. The complaint accuses
Earthgro of infringing on ConAgra's trademark and asks the court to
prohibit the fertilizer company from using the Country Pride name.
   Timothy Sellew, co-owner of the family-owned Earthgro, said
Monday conflicting trademarks lie at the root of the disagreement.
   ConAgra received a federal trademark for the Country Pride name
in 1975, but the government also granted Earthgro the right to use
the name six years later, Sellew said.
   ``It sounds like one of those typical kind of things, the big guy
going after the little guy,'' Sellew said.
   Attorney John P. Passarelli, who represents ConAgra, said the
situation was bound to create confusion.
   ``We would simply not want our products associated with
Earthgro's product,'' Passarelli said. ``Especially considering the
nature of their product .''
   ConAgra, based in Omaha, Neb., produces such brand-name food
products as Banquet and Morton in addition to Country Pride. It had
approximately $11 billion in sales last year.
</TEXT>
