<FIRST>r f PM-InsuranceLawsuit     07-18 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insurance Lawsuit,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurance Firms Sue Nevada Over 15 Percent Auto Insurance Rollback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight auto insurance companies who contend
Nevada lawmakers were ``seduced'' into passing a 15 percent auto
insurance rate rollback law have challenged the newly mandated
premium reductions as unconstitutional.
   But a key lawmaker who led the drive for reduced auto insurance
rates to July 1, 1988 levels beginning this October said he had
expected Monday's suit and believes the new law can withstand the
U.S. District Court challenge.
   ``We knew it was coming,'' said Assemblyman Gene Porter, D-Las
Vegas, who initially proposed a 20 percent rollback in auto
insurance rates. ``But the U.S. government has had the power since
the 1930s ... to limit how much a company can make. What we did was
constitutional.
   ``We just can't drive them out of business.''
   Porter said a clause was put into the bill that included the 15
percent rollback to ensure companies wouldn't be forced to cut rates
if they weren't making a profit.
   That clause was added following a California Supreme Court
decision that said a 20 percent auto insurance rate rollback
approved by voters in that state's Proposition 103 couldn't rob
insurance companies of a ``fair'' rate of return, or profit.
   Dave Hill, a spokesman for State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance
Co., one of the firms suing the state, said that language in the law
still lets the state make sure insurance companies are barely making
a profit by unconstitutionally taking away a property right.
   ``We say the legislators were politically seduced into approving
this rollback because they thought people wanted it,'' Hill said.
   ``But during hearings on the bill we showed them that almost none
of the insurance companies operating in Nevada were making any
profits by offering auto insurance. In fact, most of the companies
are losing money in that area. We lost $3 million in 1988. There was
no reason to pass this law in Nevada.''
   Hill criticized lawmakers for bypassing other insurance reform
measures that could have lowered auto insurance premiums, including
one that would have limited damages for uninsured motorists.
   Another proposal would have given drivers a choice between
regular liability insurance and no-fault policies in which damages
are paid no matter who is at fault in an accident _ but without
costly litigation.
   Under the no-fault policies, however, the right to sue for
anything other than actual damages would have been restricted.
   Nevada Insurance Commissioner David Gates, who would have to
approve any rate rollbacks under the law, wasn't available for
comment Monday. Gates is named as the principal defendant in the
suit.
   The new law was signed July 6 by Gov. Bob Miller.
   Earlier, Gates said that it appeared very few, if any, insurance
companies operating in Nevada would be forced to roll back rates
because the firms weren't earning profits on their auto policies.
   But he said the law requires every insurance company operating in
Nevada to justify its auto premium rates by refiling with his office.
   The companies suing Nevada include the largest in-state
operators, State Farm, Allstate and Farmers, along with National
Insurance Co., National Mutual, United Services Auto Association,
Safeco Insurance and Northland Insurance Co.
  
</TEXT>
