<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time 1stLd-Writethru   07-18 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, 1st Ld-Writethru,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Stock Falls As Market Speculates on Failure of Paramount Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd and 3rd grafs to UPDATE with early stock activity today.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. stock continued to fall amid the
growing belief on Wall Street that Paramount Communications Inc.'s
$12.2 billion hostile bid for the media giant is doomed and that
Time's own $14 billion offer for Warner Communications Inc. will
prevail.
   Time stock fell $1.12{ to $139.87{ a share in early New York
Stock Exchange trading today after falling $4.25 Monday and $4.75 on
Friday.
   Meanwhile, Warner stock, transformed into a takeover issue by a
Delaware court ruling last week, was up 37{ cents to $65.75 a share
early today after rising $1.12{ Monday. Paramount stock, which fell
$1.25 on Monday, slipped another 62{ cents to $55.62{ a share today.
   Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen ruled Friday that
Time could proceed with its $70-a-share offer for Warner, refusing
Paramount's request to block the deal. Paramount and some Time
shareholders are appealing the case, but Wall Street expect the
decision to stand when it reaches the Delaware Supreme Court.
   Legal scholars agree.
   ``The only basis they would have for reversing him (Allen) ...
would be on a quibbling over a factual determination,'' said James
D. Cox, a law professor at Duke University, ``But history has borne
out that he's rarely been overturned'' on factual questions.
   ``I think the opinion is pretty set,'' Cox said, although he said
a reversal by the Supreme Court was not impossible.
   John Coffee, a professor at the Columbia University School of
Law, said, ``I think the odds are very, very small that they will
overturn'' Allen's ruling.
   Allen turned down Paramount's request for an injunction against
Time's tender offer for Warner, which Paramount said would thwart
its own $200-a-share bid for Time.
   The judge disagreed with Paramount's contention that Time's board
had put the company up for sale in March when it agreed to a
stock-swap merger with Warner. Therefore, Allen ruled, the board did
not have to seriously entertain Paramount's unwanted offer.
   However, Allen delayed Time's tender offer for Warner _ which was
scheduled to expire at midnight Monday _ for 10 days to give
Paramount and the shareholders time to appeal.
   Time and Warner amended their original stock-for-stock merger
agreement to provide for the tender offer after Paramount announced
its bid last month.
   The Delaware Supreme Court will hear the case July 24 and could
rule any time after both sides make their arguments.
   Peter Appert, an analyst with C.J. Lawrence-Morgan Grenfell Inc.,
said that on Wall Street, ``most people would be willing to assume
that the (Time-Warner) transaction is a done deal.''
   Appert said it did not seem likely Allen would be overruled, and
most arbitragers, the stock speculators who scooped up Time stock
after Parmaount announced its bid, ``are not willing to make that
bet or make a big bet.''
   Time announced Monday it had extended its tender offer for Warner
until 5 p.m. July 24 in line with Allen's ruling delaying the
expiration of the bid.
   Time is offering to pay $70 a share in cash for half of Warner's
200 million outstanding shares and later exchange $70 in cash and
securities for each of the remaining shares.
   Time said that as of noon Friday, about 14.7 million Warner
shares had been tendered. Many Warner shareholders have been holding
on to their stock pending the outcome of the court case.
</TEXT>
