<DOCNO> AP890718-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru f0028 07-18 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Differences Narrowed On Bailout Bills but Divisions Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 10 grafs new with House presenting compromise counteroffer;
picks up 8th graf pvs, The House.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators today narrowed the
issues separating them on a bailout plan for the savings and loan
industry to junk bonds, who will regulate 1,200 state-chartered S&amp;Ls
and how will the rescue be financed.
   ``We are prepared to move a very substantial distance toward the
positions you insist on,'' House Banking Committee Chairman Henry B.
Gonzalez, D-Texas, told Sens. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., Jake Garn,
R-Utah, and Alan Cranston, D-Calif.
   The House conferees had agreed among themselves Wednesday to bow
to Senate demands giving regulators more control over the activities
S&amp;Ls can engage in and ability to suspend, under certain conditions,
federal insurance coverage of insolvent institutions.
   Gonzalez today presented to the Senate negotiators the House's
broad counterproposal to a Senate plan last week that bowed to
tougher House language on making S&amp;L owners put more of their own
money at risk and making the industry pay for new low-income housing
initiatives.
   ``It looks to me to be a very constructive proposal,'' said
Riegle, who as chairman of the Senate Banking Committee is the chief
Senate negotiator in the bargaining.
   Garn said he still opposes House demands that S&amp;Ls disinvest in
junk bonds within two years and that the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., rather than the Treasury Department, be put in charge of
regulating state-chartered but federally insured thrifts.
   ``I can't find a single institution that has failed because of
junk bonds,'' Garn said, contending the House language would cause
``considerable losses'' because a fire sale of junk bonds would
lower the price that S&amp;Ls could command for them to 60 cents or 70
cents on the dollar.
   But he raised no initial objection to making M. Danny Wall, his
former aide and now the government's chief S&amp;L regulator, face new
confirmation hearings in order to keep his job, as the House is
demanding.
   With S&amp;L losses mounting at a rate of $10 million to $12 million
a day, the cost of the bailout already has mushroomed by $5 billion
since Bush outlined his proposal last February. The cost of the
biggest financial rescue since the Depression is estimated at $157
billion.
   The process was slowed last week when Senate conferees presented
a comprehensive package adopting most of the House's tougher capital
requirements on S&amp;Ls and accepting its demand for new
industry-financed housing subsidies.
   The House conferees said Monday they would offer to require that
Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, and William L.
Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., face new
confirmation hearings.
   Bush appointed Seidman to take over management of the crisis from
Wall last February when he proposed the rescue legislation to cover
some $100 billion in industry losses of government-insured S&amp;L
deposits.
   However, the president also proposed making Wall head of the new
Office of Thrift Supervision in the Treasury Department that is to
replace the Home Loan Bank Board as the industry's chief regulator.
   Although Seidman is widely praised as the best official available
to untangle the S&amp;L mess, the chief of the House negotiators,
Gonzalez proposed Monday that Seidman and Wall face new confirmation
trials.
   ``In this way, the performance of both the FDIC and Bank Board
incumbent would be subject to review, and certainly parallel
treatment is fair,'' said Gonzalez.
   As chairman of the House Banking Committee, Gonzalez has blamed
Wall as a major contributor to the escalation of the S&amp;L crisis by
underestimating its magnitude in 1987 and 1988.
   Wall, however, has support from Garn, the ranking Republican on
the Senate Banking Committee. Wall was director of the Senate
committee's staff from 1981 through 1986 when Garn was its chairman
and his wife is now the senator's personal secretary.
   House negotiators rejected the Senate's proposal to put
state-chartered thrifts _ which have been blamed for a large part of
the crisis _ under the regulation of the new office that Wall might
assume.
   Instead, they insisted Monday that Seidman be put in control of
state-chartered S&amp;Ls while the new Treasury office assumes
responsibility for regulating federally chartered thrifts.
   The House conferees also agreed Monday to adopt tougher Senate
language restricting business activities of state-chartered thrifts
and giving the FDIC authority to suspend deposit insurance if an S&amp;L
has no tangible capital.
   But they could not agree on how to reconcile the way junk bonds
are treated. The House wants to make S&amp;Ls dispose of all junk bonds
within two years. The Senate last week proposed cutting how much of
an S&amp;L's deposits can be invested in the high-yield securities from
the 11 percent now allowed to 6 percent.
   The biggest issue still dividing the two sides is over financing
the immediate $50 billion needed to pay off depositors in failed
institutions.
   Bush and the Senate would do it through 30-year private bonds to
avoid swelling the federal deficit while the House would have the
Treasury borrow the money directly but exempt it from Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction targets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
