<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-18 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0329</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts said the heavy rains soaking Iowa and parts of the upper
Midwest weighed heavily on corn prices at the opening bell and
soybeans started trending lower in sympathy.
   November soybeans flirted with the contract low set about a month
ago and prospects for improvement were not good. A wave of selling
is expected as traders move to comply with last week's BOT emergency
order requiring market players to reduce their positions in the July
contract to 3 million bushels by the close of trading today.
   The order, widely interpreted as the exchange's reaction to the
large soybean position built by Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi
SpA, calls for traders to be down to 1 million bushels when the July
contract goes off the board Thursday.
   Only wheat managed to escape the price deluge early and traders
said if corn and beans continue sliding, wheat prices likely will
give way as well.
   On the open, wheat was { cent to 3 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.87 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 9\ cents lower, with July at $2.42{ a bushel; oats were 2\ cent
to 3 cents lower, with September at $1.46 a bushel; and soybeans
were 3{ cents higher to 11\ cents lower, with July at $6.81 a bushel.
   Livestock and cattle futures opened mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .27 cent lower, with August at 72.65
cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .30 cent lower, with
August at 83.72 cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .30 cent
lower, with July at 47.50 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .45 cent lower to .13 cent higher, with July at 29.20 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
