<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CNWBuyout     07-18 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CNW Buyout,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Management Group Says it Has Financing for CNW Corp. Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors signed a pact to complete the $1.6
billion buyout of the CNW Corp. and say they have tendered offers
for 98.6 percent of the company's outstanding common shares.
   The buyout group, formed by investment banker Blackstone Group
and CNW management, said Monday it has accepted for payment up to 91
percent of all validly tendered common and preferred shares.
   Under an agreement reached in June, the buyout group, known as
Chicago and North Western Acquisition Corp., offered to pay $45.50
cash per common share.
   At the time, New York's Chemical Bank committed $585 million in
buyout financing and the New York investment firm of Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc. agreed to provide up to $475 million in
financing.
   CNW Corp. is the parent of the Chicago and North Western
Transportation Co., a 6,000-mile railroad with 8,500 employees that
operates in nine states, most of them in the Midwest. It also has
commuter lines in the Chicago area.
   The buyout group said 98.6 percent of the company's outstanding
common shares had been tendered before its offer expired on Friday.
   Officials say Blackstone's financing structure will not require
significant sales of operating assets to retire the debt caused by
the takeover. But the firm will complete CNW's previously announced
plan to sell its Chicago-area commuter operations and will divest
some real estate and surplus equipment.
   The buyout offer prompted a hostile suitor, New York-based
Japonica Partners, to withdraw its own bid to acquire CNW.
</TEXT>
