<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Brokerages     07-18 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokerages,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Rises at Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber; Down at Morgan Stanley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. said Tuesday its second-quarter earnings
jumped 31 percent while another major investment firm, PaineWebber
Group Inc., posted a $15.1 million profit after only breaking even
for the same quarter a year ago.
   Both firms cited improved market conditions.
   A third investment firm, Morgan Stanley Group Inc., said its
second-quarter fell 17.1 percent from record results a year earlier
but still was its second best quarterly performance ever.
   Merrill Lynch, the brokerage, underwriting and investment
services giant based in New York, said it earned $70.2 million, or
62 cents per share, in the three months ended June 30 compared with
$53.5 million, or 47 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Total revenue rose 26 percent to a record $3.1 billion from $2.5
billion a year earlier. Excluding interest and dividends, revenue
rose 12 percent.
   William A. Schreyer, chairman and chief executive, and Daniel P.
Tully, president, said the firm's consumer market business had solid
revenue increases in virtually all of its operations, while its
capital markets business retained the top ranking among the world's
debt and equity underwriters.
   Commission revenue rose 18 percent to $462 million, reflecting
higher equity trading volume and increased sales of money market
instruments. Revenue from trading and other activities in its own
portfolio rose 3 percent to $462 million, while interest and
dividend revenue rose to 51 percent to $1.39 billion.
   Investment banking revenue fell 8 percent in the quarter to $234
million, reflecting lower levels of equity underwritings.
   Nonetheless, Merrill Lynch said it boosted its underwriting
market share for domestic issues to 17.7 percent from 15 percent
during the first half of the year and for worldwide offerings to
10.2 percent from 9.4 percent. It said it ranked first in both
categories.
   For the first six months of the year, Merrill Lynch profit fell
11.8 percent to $107.4 million, or 93 cents a share, from $121.7
million, or $1.08 per share, a year earlier. First-half total
revenue increased 25 percent to $6.1 billion from $4.9 billion a
year earlier.
   PaineWebber, also based in New York, said it earned $15.1
million, or 33 cents a share, in the second quarter compared with
earnings of $159,000 a year earlier. There were no per-share
earnings last year after deducting preferred stock dividends.
   Revenue including interest for the quarter rose 8 percent to $433
million from $400 million a year ago.
   ``PaineWebber's results reflect better market conditions combined
with our progress in improving the fundamental economics of the
firm,'' said Donald B. Marron, chairman and chief executive.
   For the first six months, PaineWebber said it earned $24.3
million, or 44 cents per share, up 16.3 percent from $20.9 million,
or 27 cents per share, a year earlier. First-half revenue rose 19.7
percent to $1.40 billion from $1.17 billion a year earlier.
   New York-based Morgan Stanley said it earned $112.1 million, or
$2.83 a share, for the quarter, down from $135.3 million, or $3.52 a
share, a year earlier.
   Total revenue rose 44.8 percent to $1.52 billion from $1.05
billion. Net revenue after deducting interest expense rose 2.1
percent to $631.6 million from $619.4 million a year earlier.
   Morgan Stanley reported higher revenue from most of its
activities, although investment revenue for its own account fell to
$51.4 million from $124.2 million..
   But the latest results included a pre-tax revenue gain of $51.5
million from the restructuring of the firm's investments in two
companies, Essex Group Inc. and Silgan Corp., while last year's
results included a similar gain of $123.7 million from the sale of
its investment in Cain Chemical Inc.
   For the first six months, Morgan Stanley earned $193.3 million,
or $4.86 a share, down 17.4 percent from $233.9 million, or $6.07 a
share, a year earlier.
   First-half total revenue rose 36.1 percent to $2.75 billion from
$2.02 billion. But net revenue after deducting interest expense fell
1.7 percent to $1.17 billion from $1.19 billion.
</TEXT>
