<HEAD>London Shares End Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates thruout with closing figures.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended slightly lower Tuesday on the
London Stock Exchange, as the market absorbed news that the U.S.
trade deficit widened in May as did Britian's government deficit for
June.
   Trading closed at an hour earlier than usual, due to a 24-hour
strike by British public transport workers.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended down 1.8
points, or 0.08 percent, at 2,273.1.
   Volume came to 418.8 million shares, compared with 513.5 million
shares on Monday.
   The Financial Times 30-share index rose 3.1 points to 1,883.3.
The Financial Times 500-share index fell 0.39 point to close at
1,285.27.
   ``The market was weakened by the U.S. trade report but managed to
comeback slightly during the afternoon,'' one trader said.
   The U.S. trade gap widened to $10.24 billion in May from $8.26
billion in April. Analysts had expected a May deficit of about $9
billion.
   In addition, the British public sector borrowing requirement, the
most widely used measure of Britain's government deficit or surplus,
showed a deficit of 695 million pounds, or $1.1 billion, in June.
The May deficit had been 321 million pounds.
