<DOCNO> AP890718-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Phone     07-18 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Phone,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings More Than Double At MCI And Parent Of US Sprint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-distance business was good to AT&amp;T's chief rivals in the
second quarter, as MCI Communications Corp. and the parent of US
Sprint Communications Co. both reported Tuesday that profits more
than doubled.
   MCI has grabbed about 12 percent of the long-distance market and
US Sprint 8 percent as American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s share
has steadily eroded to about 68 percent. A variety of smaller
companies split the rest.
   MCI said its net income grew 142 percent on a 31 percent gain in
revenue that was helped by the availability of new services.
   MCI said it was competing more effectively in the $4 billion
operator services market because of expanded services since April 1
that enable customers to make collect, third-party-billed, and
person-to-person calls.
   MCI also began competing April 1 for long-distance customers of
pay phones, once a monopoly of No. 1 American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
Co. During the quarter it won its largest contract to date, a $150
million award from Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. for voice and data
transmission.
   Washington-based MCI said it earned $150 million, or 56 cents a
share, compared to $62 million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose to $1.59 billion from $1.22 billion.
   For the first half, MCI earned $285 million, or $1.07 a share, up
from $120 million, or 42 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose
to $3.09 billion from $2.35 billion.
   Daniel F. Akerson, MCI's chief financial officer, said the
company's $6 billion investment in its network has started to pay
off. The company has posted eight consecutive quarters of record
profit and revenue, he said.
   United Telecommunications Inc., the Kansas City, Mo.-based
majority owner of US Sprint, said the long-distance unit contributed
$48.1 million in operating income in the quarter as it posted its
first billion-dollar quarter, with $1.04 billion in revenue.
   A year earlier US Sprint, the No. 3 long-distance company, had an
operating loss of $98.3 million on revenue of $799 million.
   The turnaround at US Sprint led to a 121 percent profit increase
for the parent company, which also provides local phone service in
19 states, mostly in the Southeast and Midwest.
   United Telecom said its earnings rose to $90.5 million, or 86
cents a share, from $41 million, or 40 cents a share, a year
earlier. Companywide revenue rose to $1.85 billion from $1.56
billion.
   For the first six months, net income rose to $166.9 million, or
$1.59 a share, from $75.4 million, or 73 cents a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose to $3.62 billion from $3.05 billion.
   In coming months US Sprint should benefit from its part-ownership
of a trans-Atlantic fiber-optic cable and from its participation in
a federal government phone contract, it said. The contract will make
the U.S. government into the company's biggest customer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
