<FIRST>r f BC-LongviewFibre-Bass     07-18 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Longview Fibre-Bass,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bass Group Increases Stake In Longview Fibre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert M. Bass Group Inc. has increased
its stake in Longview Fibre Co. to 7 percent, the investor group
said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   In the filing Monday, the Bass group said it had bought 462,000
shares of the timber and paper products company between May 16 and
July 14 at prices ranging between $63.08 and $74.22 a share.
   The group now has 776,400 shares. Before the purchases, it held
2.85 percent of Longview Fibre, the filing said.
   The filing said the purchases were made for investment purposes,
and that the group may buy more shares. No takeover of the
Longview-based company was planned, it said.
   Longview Fibre's stock rose 50 cents to $72.25 a share Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange, giving the company a market value of
nearly $796.6 million. Nearly 100,000 shares were traded, more than
double the normal daily volume.
   Ray McDermott, Longview Fibre senior vice president, said the
company had no comment on the Bass group purchases. He said the
company did adopt anti-takeover provisions on March 1, but not in
anticipation of any takeover threat.
   Longview Fibre owns and operates tree farms in Oregon and
Washington that produce logs for sale, and owns a pulp and paper
mill that manufactures kraft paper and containerboard. It also owns
15 plants in 10 states that produce shipping containers and grocery
bags.
   For fiscal year 1988, Longview Fibre had net earnings of $96.33
million, or $8.71 a share, up 48 percent from the $65.17 million, or
$5.80 a share, in 1987. Net sales were $657.21 million for 1988 and
$569.4 million for 1987.
</TEXT>
