<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-18 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Higher, Soybeans Mixed and Corn Lower in Weather-Driven Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures closed higher, soybeans were mixed
and corn fell sharply Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   As in Monday's market, weather was at center stage in all three
pits.
   Because corn is in its most critical growing stage, heavy rains
in the Corn Belt were viewed as favorable to crop production and
prices in that pit opened under pressure and were lower all day.
   Wheat, however, was bolstered by forecasts for drier weather in
the Plains states and better-than-expected export business and
managed to stay on the upside through most of the session.
   Soybeans started the day lower in sympathy with the losses in
corn, but large buying by several commercial brokers enabled
old-month soybeans to rebound in light volume.
   November soybeans flirted with a contract low set last month, but
there was less selling than expected Tuesday in light of a BOT
emergency order last week requiring market players to reduce their
positions in the July contract to 3 million bushels by the close of
trading.
   The order, widely interpreted as the exchange's reaction to the
large soybean position built by Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi
S.p.A., calls for traders to be down to 1 million bushels when the
July contract goes off the board Thursday.
   On the close, wheat was 2 cents to 4 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.87{ a bushel; corn was { cent to
6\ cents lower, with July at $2.47 a bushel; oats were { cent to 3{
cents higher, with September at $1.42 a bushel; and soybeans were 9{
cents lower to 19{ cents higher, with July at $6.97 a bushel.
</TEXT>
