<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-18 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Down in U.S., Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost value against most major
currencies in U.S. dealings that were hectic at times Tuesday as
traders reacted to an unexpectedly poor report on the U.S. trade
performance.
   Earlier, on foreign exchange markets abroad, the dollar finished
mixed.
   Gold prices moved modestly higher at home after a mixed showing
overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose $1.60 to $372.60 a troy ounce. Republic National Bank
of New York quoted a bid of $371.90 for an ounce of bullion at 4
p.m. EDT, up $1.60 from Monday's late bid.
   Simon Fischer, a vice president at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said
currency trading was brisk immediately after the Commerce Department
reported the country's merchandise trade deficit widened sharply to
a seasonally adjusted $10.24 billion in May from $8.29 billion in
April.
   It had been widely predicted that the May deficit would be around
$9 billion.
   News in the report that imports grew 4.3 percent to a record
$40.71 billion in May implied that the U.S. economy remains strong
because it is drawing in vast quantities of foreign goods.
   This point fed bullish sentiment toward the dollar because it
suggested that the Federal Reserve Board might be less inclined to
drive down interest rates. High U.S. interest rates have supported
the dollar by making earnings on dollar-denominated investments
attractive.
   Tempering the bullishness was speculation that the Bush
administration might favor a lower dollar _ and wish to promote its
decline through interest rate manipulation _ to help bring the trade
deficit down.
   Trading volume dwindled as the day went by, with the dollar
finishing lower against most currencies except the Japanese yen and
the Canadian dollar.
   Fischer said in the afternoon traders started to even out their
currency holdings so they might be able to make profits Wednesday no
matter which way the dollar moves in response to the Consumer Price
Index report for June.
   Before the trade report was released, the dollar had strengthened
in Tokyo to close at 142.35 Japanese yen, up from 141.53 yen late
Monday. Later, in London, the dollar traded at 141.70 yen, and, in
New York, the dollar closed at 141.50 yen, up slightly from 141.43
yen on Monday.
   The British pound strengthened against the dollar. In London, one
pound cost $1.6255 late Tuesday compared to Monday's $1.6075.
Sterling fetched $1.6235 in New York vs. $1.6150 on Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8960 West German marks, down from 1.9030; 1.6430
Swiss francs, down from 1.6445; 6.4325 French francs, down from
6.4555; 1,372.00 Italian lire, down from 1,380.00; and, 1.19115
Canadian dollars, up from 1.19065.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Monday's late
levels included: 1.8920 West German marks, down from 1.9138; 1.6395
Swiss francs, down from 1.6540; 6.4175 French francs, down from
6.4890; 2.1505 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1580; 1,379.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,387.50; and 1.1907 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1905.
   In the gold markets, the late bid for bullion fell 25 cents a
troy ounce to $372.20 in London, but rose 75 cents an ounce to
$371.50 in Zurich.
   Gold had closed earlier in Hong Kong at $369.75 an ounce, down
from $371.05 on Monday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of $5.27 a troy
ounce, down from $5.29. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery closed at $5.242 a troy ounce, down from Monday's
settlement price of $5.263.
</TEXT>
