<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-18 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Weakens in Anticipation of More Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices fell Tuesday, weakened by trader
expectations of more crude and gasoline supplies reaching the market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate crude, the benchmark grade of oil, fell 11 cents
a barrel to $20.34.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale unleaded
gasoline for August delivery fell 1.02 cent a gallon to 56.06 cents,
and wholesale home-heating oil for August delivery fell 0.05 cent a
gallon to 50.50 cents.
   Andrew Lebow, a broker at the New York energy futures firm
E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc., attributed the weakness
partly to high gasoline production, which has led to a surplus along
the East Coast and Gulf Coast.
   ``I think what's happened is that refiners have been able to
produce much more gasoline than many analysts had figured,'' Lebow
said. Wholesale gasoline prices now have dropped by about 23 cents a
gallon from the spring high.
   Others said the market weakness reflected anticipation that the
American Petroleum Institute's weekly statistical report would
continue to show a big growth in supplies of oil and refined
products.
</TEXT>
