<FIRST>u f AM-Audi-CaseClosed     07-18 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Audi-Case Closed,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audi Ads Say Sudden Acceleration Case Closed; Class Action Plaintiffs
Say No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audi of America's full-page ads in dozens of
newspapers Tuesday triumphantly declared ``Case Closed'' on its
problems with sudden acceleration, but an attorney notes that a
related class action suit against the automaker remains wide open.
   ``These guys have a lot of nerve,'' said Robert F. Lisco of
Chicago, who represents plaintiffs in a suit covering up to 300,000
Audi 5000 owners seeking damages for lost resale value blamed on
sudden acceleration concerns. ``The case is not closed...''
   The ads ran nationally in the Wall Street Journal and USA Today
and in local newspapers serving the 34 top markets, said Audi
spokesman Joe Bennett in Troy, Mich.
   They note the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration on
July 11 officially completed its investigation of sudden accleration
involving the Audi 5000 and determined the problem did not involve a
mechanical or electrical defect.
   The agency _ which in January 1987 noted 1,750 reports of alleged
sudden acceleration resulting in 1,269 accidents, 430 injuries and
nine deaths _ said the major cause of the problem ``appears to have
been drivers unknowingly stepping on the accelerator instead of the
brake pedal.''
   Audi's ad asks, ``Is there anyone who has not heard the rumors of
sudden acceleration in Audi? We doubt it.''
   After sketching the NHTSA findings, it closes with the words:
``Audi has been vindicated. Case closed.''
   Bennett agreed that the suit pending in Cook County Circuit Court
``theoretically'' involves people around the country _ it covers
about 300,000 current and former U.S. owners of Audi 5000 sedans,
model years 1978-1986 _ but said the clearly were not about the
court case.
   ``This is the only city in America where there could have been
any thought we were talking about that case. ...and anybody who read
the ad would know that's not what we're taking about,'' Bennett
said. ``We were talking about the larger issue and not just the
Chicago issue.''
   In August 1988, a judge rejected Audi's offer to give the
plaintiffs credits of between $300 and $2,000 toward purchase of a
new vehicle. The judge noted plaintiffs only would benefit if they
bought another Audi.
   Audi decided to drop negotiations and go to trial. Bennett said
the company did not expect any action on the trial before late
summer or fall.
   Lisco said plaintiffs' attorneys have asked the judge to apply a
finding by a New Jersey appellate court, which affirmed a $100,000
judgment for punitive damages against Audi because of a design
defect allegedly linked to sudden acceleration.
   At issue was the location of the gas and the brake pedal, ``so
close to one another that a driver might inadvertently place their
foot on the accelerator thinking they're applying it to the brake,''
Lisco said.
   Bennett rejected characterization of the pedal placement as a
design defect.
   The NTHSA found that Audi recall campaigns to modify the pedals
on 1978 through 1983 models, install automatic shift-lock mechanisms
on all models and correct idle-speed controls in 1984 through 1986
models ``appear to have resulted in a very substantial reduction of
the number of sudden acceleration incidents and accidents.''
   Bennett said the shift lock ``reduced the complaint level by over
90 percent'' about the West German-made cars, distributed by
Volkswagen of America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
