<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Marion-Dow     07-18 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marion-Dow,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marion, Dow Officials Say Merger Fit is Perfect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF BUZBEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Company officials said Tuesday a
multibillion-dollar agreement for Dow Chemical Co. to acquire a
majority stake in Marion Laboratories Inc. will give Dow the solid
position in pharmaceuticals it wants and give Marion the new
products it needs.
   Under the agreement signed late Monday, Dow Chemical plans to
merge its subsidiary, Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc. of
Cincinnati, with Marion. The new company, called Marion Merrell Dow
Inc., will be based in Kansas City.
   The deal will create a new global pharmaceutical company with
worldwide annual sales of about $2.3 billion, said Fred W. Lyons
Jr., president and chief executive officer of Marion, who will
become president of the new company.
   ``We've become a major player right now,'' Lyons said.
   Joseph G. Temple Jr., executive vice president of Dow and
chairman and chief executive officer of Merrell Dow, will become
chairman and CEO for two to three years before retiring.
   The new company will have 1,500 sales representatives in the
United States and a significant marketing presence in foreign
markets, Lyons said.
   Dow Merrell and Marion both are growing rapidly. But the slightly
larger Dow Merrell has concentrated on basic research, while Marion
specializes in licensing other companies' compounds, developing
medical uses for them and then marketing the new drugs. Dow has a
much bigger overseas presence.
   ``It's really a perfect fit,'' Lyons said.
   Both Dow Merrell and Marion had been searching for possible
business partners for several months, Lyons said, and began talking
two months ago.
   For Dow Merrell's corporate parent, the deal satisfies a desire
to diversify and expand its pharmaceutical interests to protect
itself from the cyclical swings in chemicals and plastics, analysts
said.
   ``Dow has been trying to get out of the commodity chemical
business into something that's more value-added,'' said Steven
Bernard, an analyst with Edward D. Jones &amp; Co. in St. Louis.
   Marion's sales exploded in the early 1980s thanks to the drug
Cardizem, but the company had no significant new products under
development to compensate for increasing competition in 1992, when
companies can begin producing generic varieties of Cardizem.
   ``We didn't think the glory days would come back unless they came
up with a new product,'' said Jon Braatz, an analyst with B.C.
Christopher Securities Co. in Kansas City.
   Besides Cardizem, which is used to treat angina and high blood
pressure, Marion's main product is the anti-ulcer drug Carafate.
   Merrell Dow's main products are the antihistamine Seldane, an
anti-cholesterol drug Lorelco, the anti-smoking gum Nicorette and
Cepacol, a mouthwash.
   In the first step of the two-stage deal, Dow will buy 39 percent
of Marion's 150 million outstanding shares at 38 each, or about $2.2
billion.
   Later, the big chemical company will acquire about 28 percent
more of Marion's stock, giving Dow a 67 percent interest in Marion
by 1991 or 1992.
   Dow plans to pay for the newly issued shares by turning Merrell
Dow over to Marion and issuing a new class of securities that
provide for payments by Dow to Marion shareholders based on Marion's
stock price at the time.
   Ewing Kauffman, who founded Marion in his Kansas City garage in
1950, and his family support the transaction. The family will tender
their shares to Dow, Lyons said. The Kauffmans now control 23
percent of Marion stock. They would be able to sell only the same
portion of their shares as other Marion shareholders, or 39 percent.
   The Marion-Merrell Dow merger is the latest in a series of recent
consolidations in the drug business. Among the major recent deals
are: SmithKline Beckman Corp.'s planned merger with Beecham Group
PLC of Britain; American Home Products Corp.'s planned acquisition
of A.H. Robins Co.; and the purchase of Sterling Drug Inc. by
Eastman Kodak Co.
</TEXT>
