<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-18 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>July Soybean Contract Finishes Ahead as First Liquidation Deadline
Passes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed mixed Tuesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade, as the first of two deadlines requiring traders to reduce
large positions in the July contract passed without fanfare.
   On other markets, copper extended its rally on renewed fears of
terrorist action against mines in Peru and Papua New Guinea, but the
precious metals failed to shake recent doldrums despite a sharp
decline by the dollar.
   Petroleum futures were mixed and livestock and cattle futures
were lower.
   Just as it had Monday, weather again took over center stage in
the grain and soybean pits.
   Because corn is in its most critical growing stage, heavy rains
in the Corn Belt were viewed as favorable to crop production and
prices in that pit opened under pressure and held to the downside
all day.
   Wheat, however, was bolstered by forecasts for drier weather in
the Plains states and better-than-expected export business and
managed to stay on the upside through most of the session.
   Soybeans started the day lower in sympathy with the losses in
corn, but several large buys by commercial brokers helped hold the
line and enabled the July and August contracts to rebound.
   With soybean supplies expected to remain tight for the near term,
both months held their gains while contracts for the back months
closed lower.
   Traders said, overall, that there was less selling than might
have been expected Tuesday in light of a BOT emergency order last
week requiring traders to reduce their positions in the July
contract to 3 million bushels by the close of trading.
   The order, widely interpreted as the exchange's reaction to the
large soybean position built by Italian agribusiness giant Ferruzzi
S.p.A., calls for traders to be down to 1 million bushels when the
July contract goes off the board Thursday.
   Ferruzzi said it had accumulated contracts for delivery of as
much as 24 million bushels of soybeans to meet export business
commitments and ensure a steady flow of product for its processing
plants; others have suggested the company sought to corner the
soybean market.
   ``Supply tightness aside, there are two reasons the closing
prices were interesting,'' said a trader who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. ``The first is that the volume in July beans was very
thin because nobody wants to get involved. That might explain the
healthy price climb there.
   ``As for August,'' he added, ``Ferruzzi may simply have rolled
their July contracts into the next month.''
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 4 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.87{ a bushel; corn was 6\ cents lower to }
cents higher, with July at $2.48\ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3{
cents higher, with September at $1.42 a bushel; and soybeans were 9\
cents lower to 18 cents higher, with July at $6.95{ a bushel.
   July and August traditionally are the months of slowest
industrial demand for copper, but the September contract picked up
.50 cent a pound Monday on reports of trouble in Peru, and rocketed
ahead 3.8 cents Tuesday.
   Fueling the price climb was news of a strike by workers at a
copper mine in British Columbia, Canada, and reports that the state
of emergency declared by the government of Papua New Guinea _ set to
end in mid-August, when operations at the Bougainville mine were to
resume _ will be extended through mid-September.
   Also helping move prices were reports that Shining Path guerillas
in Peru who have caused disruptions at the lead, zinc and silver
mining operations of Centromin, the state-owned company, would
include copper mines in future actions.
   ``The supply picture has been bullish for some time, but the
demand is not there for much of the summer,'' said Bette Raptopolous
of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., New York. ``The threat of
terrorist activity gave it a lot more immediacy.''
   Copper settled 2 cents to 3.8 cents higher on the Comex, with
July at 109.8 cents a pound.
   Precious metals didn't fare quite as well.
   Gold, also traded on the Comex, climbed $1.60 to $1.90, with July
at $372.60 a troy ounce; silver was 1.9 cents to 2.1 cents lower,
with July at 524.2 cents a pound. Platinum, traded on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, settled $4.30 to $4.50 lower, with July at
$504.20 a troy ounce.
   Petroleum futures were mixed to mostly lower.
   Crude oil settled 11 cents to 32 cents lower on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with August at $20.34 a barrel; heating oil was
.26 lower to .07 cent higher, with August at 50.50 cents a gallon;
and unleaded gasoline was .20 cent to 1.02 cents lower, with August
at 56.06 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and cattle futures were mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .32 cent lower, with August at
72.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent lower to .05 cent
higher, with August at 83.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .18 cent
to .60 cent lower, with July at 47.47 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .75 cent to 1.1 cents lower, with July at 28.27 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
