<FIRST>u f AM-Massachusetts-Takeovers     07-18 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Massachusetts-Takeovers,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Signs Bill To Hinder Hostile Corporate Takeovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, moving to
protect Massachusetts companies and workers against corporate
raiders, signed legislation Tuesday to hinder debt-financed
takeovers.
   The law received support from a number of business and labor
groups in Massachusetts but has been attacked by some investors and
securities specialists as an effort to entrench corporate managers.
   Modeled after a Delaware statute, the law will freeze a target
company's assets for three years unless the buyer either is approved
by the company's board or obtains 90 percent of the stock not
controlled by management.
   Dukakis signed the bill at the Cambridge headquarters of Polaroid
Corp., the instant camera and film company, which earlier this year
used the Delaware law to fend off a hostile bid from a group led by
Roy Disney, heir to the Disney entertainment fortune. Polaroid is
incorporated in Delaware.
   State officials said the law was prompted by recent takeover
battles for Polaroid and other Massachusetts companies _ including
Gillette, Prime Computer and Dunkin' Donuts _ that the Dukakis
administration views as a threat to the state's economic vitality.
   More than 20 states have anti-takeover statutes, but the
Massachusetts law is among the most comprehensive, containing
provisions to protect labor as well as management, said Stanley
Keller, a corporate lawyer with the Boston firm of Palmer &amp; Dodge.
   While businesses may object to some provisions, such as a
requirement of severance pay for workers laid off during and after
takeovers, ``the corporate community has been willing to buy into
the legislation because it is well balanced,'' Keller said.
   The law also requires buyers to assume the collective bargaining
agreements of their target companies; clarifies the authority of
corporate boards to set up anti-takeover defenses; and raises the
number of shares needed to call a special stockholder meeting to 40
percent, from 10 percent.
   The law generally takes effect once a potential buyer obtains 5
percent of the target company's stock, one of the lowest thresholds
in the nation. In contrast, Delaware's statute kicks in at 15
percent and New York's at 10 percent.
   At the urging of mutual fund companies, however, the legislation
allows institutional investors to acquire up to 15 percent of a
company without triggering the anti-takeover restrictions.
   Bernard Black, a professor of securities law at Columbia
University in New York, called the measure ``basically a management
protection statute'' that could have ``perverse effects.''
   Dukakis and state Secretary of Economic Affairs Gray Hedgespeth
said the asset-freeze provision was designed to stop hostile raiders
from borrowing heavily to acquire a company, then selling off its
parts to help pay the takeover debt.
   Black contended the asset freeze would deter beneficial economic
activity.
   ``What you hope for in a business combination is some sort of
efficiency, combining the target's operations with your own and
slimming down because of economies of scale or scope,'' he said.
``The Massachusetts statute and others like it...have the potential
for preventing whatever efficiency gains may come from hostile
takeovers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-United-Europe 1stLd-Writethru   07-18 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-United-Europe, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0273,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Announces Plans for European Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes spelling of Frankfurt in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines, seeking a niche in the already
crowded U.S.-European air travel market, announced Tuesday it hopes
to begin serving the continent next spring from four American cities.
   The nation's second-largest air carier said it has filed
petitions for its proposed European routes with the U.S. Department
of Transportation.
   United Chairman and President Stephen M. Wolf said that in the
first phase of its plan, United would begin flying next spring
between its Chicago and Washington, D.C., hubs to Frankfurt and
Paris, as well as between Chicago and Milan with continuing service
to Rome.
   Last month, United said it also was seeking to begin service
between Chicago and Warsaw, with continuing service to Budapest.
   In the second phase, the airline has asked for authority to link
Paris with both San Francisco and New York. United currently holds
authority to fly between those cities and Frankfurt, but does not
fly the routes.
   ``Combined with our extensive Pacific routes and our
comprehensive domestic network, this action means that United will
be a truly global airline in the 1990s,'' Wolf said.
   In addition, United has requested government approval to fly
between London and San Francisco, Chicago, Washington, D.C., and New
York. It also seeks permission to fly between Glasgow, Scotland, and
both Chicago and Washington.
   ``Within a year, we expect to have a presence in several of the
major transportation centers of Europe, and we will build
aggressively upon that base,'' he said.
   Analysts say United's announcement that it plans to serve Europe
from its U.S. hubs is not a surprise.
   ``Basically when they ordered a number of Boeing 767s, their
intent was very clear,'' said Helane Becker, a vice president of
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Earlier this year, United announced orders for as many as 370
Boeing aircraft valued at $15.74 billion. The package includes firm
orders for 180 Boeing jetliners and options on 190 others.
   ``United's movement into the major markets of Europe, like our
recent record-breaking aircraft order, shows that we are committed
to serving the transportation needs not only of America, but also of
a growing portion of the international market,'' Wolf said.
   Seven U.S. airlines fly between the United States and Europe _
USAir, Continental, Delta, Pan American, TWA, Northwest and
American, the nation's largest carrier.
   ``It is not surprising they (United) want to serve Europe out of
major U.S. cities, that is everybody's goal,'' Ms. Becker said,
adding that the U.S.-Europe air routes are very well served.
   ``But relative to being a long-term viable competitor, you have
to look at all sorts of service.''
   The decision to expand service into Europe is the latest
indication that United has climbed out of the doldrums it wallowed
in earlier in the decade.
   In addition to acquiring aircraft, in the past year the airline
has snatched executive talent from other airlines, come out with
agressive marketing programs and has become more competitive at its
hubs.
   With United's renewed vigor has come rumors of a takeover attempt
that have sent the price of parent UAL Corp. stock soaring on the
New York Stock Exchange. Traders began focusing on United as a
takeover target after last month's acceptance by NWA Inc. _
Northwest's parent company _ of a $3.65 billion buyout by Los
Angeles investor Alfred Checchi.
   Analysts say a bid for United would substantially top that figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
