<HEAD>Posts 20 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eli Lilly and Co. said Tuesday its
second-quarter profit rose 20 percent on a revenue increase of 11
percent, citing increases in its medical instrument and
pharmaceutical businesses.
   Lilly earned $217.1 million, or 75 cents a share, in the second
quarter compared with $180.7 million, or 63 cents a share, a year
earlier.
   Sales for the quarter rose to $1.12 billion from $1.01 billion a
year earlier.
   The company said sales of its new antidepressant Prozac were
particularly strong. Its medical instrument systems division's sales
growth was led by Cardiac Pacemakers Inc. and Advances
Cardiovascular Systems Inc.
   For the first half, net income rose 21 percent to $501.8 million,
or $1.74 a share, from $413.9 million, or $1.45 a share, a year
earlier.
   First-half sales rose 12 percent to $2.35 billion from $2.09
billion a year earlier.
