<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks 1stLd-Writethru f0235 07-18 0947</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0235,0974</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Quarter Profit Up at Citicorp, Wells; Down at Manny Hanny,
BNEC</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, `Bank of ...,'
and ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with Continental Bank results.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp, Wells Fargo &amp; Co. and Continental Bank Corp. reported
higher second-quarter earnings Tuesday while Manufacturers Hanover
Corp. and Bank of New England Corp. said their profits tumbled
during the period.
   Citicorp, the nation's largest banking concern, based in New
York, said its net income for the three months ended June 30 rose 10
percent to $395 million, or $1.11 a share, from $359 million, or
$1.03 a share, in the comparable 1988 period.
   Manufacturers Hanover reported its profits fell 74 percent to
$106 million, or $1.87 a share, from $403 million, or $7.93 a share,
in second quarter 1988. The 1988 quarter included some $336 million
in one-time gains from asset sales and tax benefits.
   Wells Fargo's net income rose 18 percent to $147.4 million, or
$2.68 a share, in the second quarter from $124.4 million, or $2.24 a
share, in the year-earlier period.
   Bank of New England's net income dropped 47 percent to $36.5
million, or 52 cents a share, from $69.2 million, or $1 a share, in
the year-earlier period. The company said the profit decline
reflected significant losses on real estate stemming from the
slowdown of the regional economy.
   Continental reported its earnings for the second quarter
increased 6 percent to $64 million, or $1.01 per share, on revenues
of $286 million, up from profit of $60 million, or 95 cents a share,
on revenues of $258 million for the same period a year ago.
   Citicorp said its net interest revenue rose 8 percent to $1.84
billion, while other revenue rose 5 percent to $1.5 billion and
non-interest expenses rose 6 percent to $2.6 billion.
   The company took a $329 million provision for possible credit
losses and wrote off $534 million in credit, including $223 million
to debtor nations. Citicorp announced earlier in the year that it
was writing down $185 million of medium and long-term debt related
to its Argentine loans.
   For the first half of 1989, Citicorp's net income totaled $924
million, or $2.63 a share, up 29 percent from $717 million, or $2.04
a share, a year earlier.
   Citicorp said first-half results included a gain of $77 million
in the first quarter from the sale of property in Japan and $154
million in interest payments from Brazil, which were due but unpaid
in the first half of 1988. The Brazil payment was offset by $49
million of unpaid interest due from Argentina.
   Citicorp's total reserve for loan losses was $3.9 billion as of
June 30, down from $4.5 billion a year earlier.
   Manufacturers Hanover said its second quarter results reflected
strength in regional banking and global wholesale activities.
Results for the year-earlier quarter included a $291 million gain
from the sale of Manufacturers Hanover Consumer Services Inc.
   Net interest income was up nearly 1 percent to $453 million,
while non-interest revenue fell 47.2 percent to $353 million and
non-interest expense was nearly flat at $530 million.
   Net interest revenue was reduced by $38 million in the quarter
and by $70 million in the first six months due to $894 million in
nonperforming loans from Argentina.
   The company took a provision for possible credit losses of $100
million in the second quarter, down from $133 million in the same
period last year.
   Net charge-offs of loans to developing countries in the second
quarter totaled $291 million, up from $56 million in the 1988
quarter. It included $247 million in net charge-offs of medium- and
long-term loans to Argentina.
   As of June 30, Manufacturers Hanover's total loan-loss reserve
was $2.06 billion, down from $2.53 billion a year earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, the company had net income
of $209 million, or $3.70 a share, down 62 percent from $544
million, or $10.52 a share, in the first half of 1988.
   Bank of New England, based in Boston, reported net interest
income of $252.3 million, down 8 percent from last year. It took a
$69.7 million provision for possible loan losses during the quarter
and had a loan loss reserve of $341.7 million as of June 30.
   Nonperforming assets rose to $667.4 million as of June 30 from
$550.8 million three months earlier.
   The company reported net income of $78.8 million, or $1.12 a
share in the first half of 1989, down 42 percent from $135.4
million, or $1.96 a share, in the first half of 1988.
   Wells Fargo, based in San Francisco, said its second-quarter
benefited from increased net interest income, which primarily
resulted from an increase in domestic loans.
   Net interest income was $531.5 million compared with $482.1
million a year ago.
   Net income in the first half was $288.9 million, or $5.24 a
share, up 18 percent from $244.8, or $4.39 a share, in last year's
first half.
   Wells Fargo took a $100 million provision for loan losses in the
second quarter and net loan charge-offs were $42.7 million.
Nonperforming loans totaled $1.2 billion as of June 30, down from
$1.4 billion a year earlier.
   Chicago-based Continental said that for the first six months of
1989, net income was $140 million, or $2.25 a share, up 9 percent
from $129 million, or $2.05 a share, a year ago.
   ``Our core businesses accounted for a $26 million, or 10 percent,
increase in second-quarter revenues, once again demonstrating good
progress in pursuing our all-business strategy,'' said Continental
Chairman Thomas C. Theobald, referring to the bank's emphasis on
business accounts instead of consumer accounts.
</TEXT>
