<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Northwest     07-18 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northwest,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republic Pilots Vote to Support Checchi Bid For NWA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAM SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Republic Airlines pilots now flying for
Northwest Airline gave their blessing Tuesday to a takeover bid by
Los Angeles businessman Al Checchi, calling it the ``best available
option'' for the carrier's well-being.
   The resolution, passed unanimously by the Republic Master
Executive Council of the Air Line Pilots Association, also urged
other employee groups and unions of Northwest's parent, NWA Inc., to
back the $4 billion offer by Checchi's acquisition group, Wings
Holdings Inc.
   NWA's board of directors approved the takeover last month.
   Union spokesman Curt Kruse said the endorsement by former
Republic pilots of Checchi's buyout offer doesn't mean pilots are
pleased with the pace of negotiations for a new contract between
ALPA and Northwest.
   He also said the pilots still have concerns over the $3.35
billion in debt that NWA would incur in the buyout.
   ``However, once we had an opportunity to review his (Checchi's)
financial plan, our concerns diminished somewhat,'' he said.
   NWA pilots have said they are running out of patience with the
slack pace of contract negotiations. They've also said a strike
would be disastrous for Checchi, who would pay shareholders of the
Eagan-based airline $121 a share.
   Checchi has said he prefers to have the pilots signed to a
contract before his group takes ownership. But some in the union
want to wait for his arrival to complete the negotiations.
   Northwest's largest union, the 20,000-member Machinists union
District Lodge 143, supports the Checchi bid.
</TEXT>
