<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Aeroflot     07-18 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Aeroflot,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aeroflot Applies To Join IATA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aeroflot, the Soviet national airline, has applied
to join the International Air Transport Association, IATA spokesman
John Brindley said Tuesday.
   He said the association welcomed the decision by Aeroflot to
``become part of the civil aviation mainstream.''
   An IATA official, speaking on condition he not be identified,
said one reason for Aeroflot's application was concern that the
airline might be barred from some airports by new regulations on
noise control.
   The official said government civil aviation authorities are
expected to discuss reductions in noise levels at a meeting in
September and Aeroflot's aircraft do ``not meet all the standards.''
   Brindley said membership in IATA, an organization of 187
airlines, would give Aeroflot access to technical information on
issues such as noise control.
   Aeroflot operates more than 3,000 aircraft flying to cities
within the Soviet Union and to 125 destinations worldwide, according
to IATA figures.
   In 1988 the airline transported 126 million passengers, making it
the world's largest carrier. But only 4 million were on
international flights, compared to the 16.9 million people
transported worldwide by British Airways, the biggest international
carrier, Brindley said.
   Boris Paniukov, first vice minister of Soviet Civil Aviation, and
Boris Ryzhenkov, executive secretary of the Soviet Commission on
International Civil Aviation, presented the formal membership
application at a meeting Tuesday at IATA's European headquarters in
Geneva, Brindley said.
   He said representatives at the meeting discussed ways of
integrating the Soviet airline into the association as quickly as
possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
