<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RailroadFined 1stLd-Writethru f0311 07-18 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Railroad Fined, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0311,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Imposes $243.5 Million Damage Award Against B&amp;LE Railroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to ADD that railroad is majority-owned by an
investment firm.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury ordered the Bessemer &amp;
Lake Erie railroad on Tuesday to pay $243.5 million in damages in an
antitrust case brought by steelmakers, truck lines and a dock
company.
   But the railroad, which plans to appeal the verdict, said in a
statement that several important motions remained before the court
that could significantly reduce or eliminate the award.
   B&amp;LE also said it expected the damage verdict to be offset by
payments from settlements by other defendant railroads.
   Litigation is expected to continue in the case for years.
   ``The B&amp;LE ... intends to pursue all of its appellate rights in
seeking to correct what it believes to be totally inappropriate
findings,'' spokesman Robert N. Gentile said.
   Ten suits were filed against the B&amp;LE and other railroads in 1983
and 1984, contending they conspired to block the development of
self-unloading ore boats, forcing steel companies to rely on the
railroads to receive ore shipments.
   Three railroad companies _ CSX Corp., Consolidated Rail Corp. and
Norfolk Southern Corp. _ settled out of court during the trial. The
B&amp;LE was the only defendant to proceed to a verdict in the case.
   Among the plaintiffs were Sharon Steel Corp., National Steel
Corp., Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp., LTV Corp., Tauro Trucking
Co., Ambrosia Trucking and Erie Dock Co.
   The judgment returned Tuesday was in a consolidation of the suits.
   The case was heard by two juries. The first one found the B&amp;LE
guilty on June 19 of violating antitrust laws. The second jury,
charged with determining damages, returned its decision Tuesday
after four days of deliberations.
   The B&amp;LE formerly was a wholly owned subsidiary of USX Corp. USX
spun off the railroad last December to Transtar Inc., which is owned
by Blackstone Capital Partners LP, USX and former managers of the
B&amp;LE. Blackstone holds 51 percent of Transtar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
