<DOCNO> AP890718-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Primerica     07-18 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Primerica,0229</SECOND>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the same day it announced second
quarter earnings of $63.4 million, Primerica Corp. said Tuesday it
had decided to keep its Fingerhut subsidiary after failing to find a
qualified buyer.
   Greenwich-based Primerica announced last year at the time of its
$1.65 billion merger with Commercial Credit Group Inc. that it
intended to sell Fingerhut Companies Inc., a direct mail marketing
business.
   But Sanford I. Weill, Primerica's chairman and chief executive
officer, said Tuesday, ``No appropriate buyer, both in terms of
financial consideration to Primerica and business compatibility with
Fingerhut, has presented itself.''
   He said Primerica, primarily a financial-services company, would
keep Fingerhut and attempt to build up the business.
   Primerica's second-quarter earnings translated into 65 cents a
share. In 1988's second quarter it earned $31.9 million, or $1.37 a
share. The figures aren't directly comparable since the merger
hadn't taken place in the first half of 1988.
   For the six months that ended June 30, Primerica earned $114
million, or $1.18 a share, compared with $61.2 million, or $1.37 a
share, in the first half of 1988.
   Revenues totaled $1.4 billion in the second quarter of 1989 and
$2.6 billion for the first six months. In 1988, revenues were $238
million in the second quarter and $467 million in the first half.
  
</TEXT>
