<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GeneralDynamics     07-18 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-General Dynamics,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attack Submarine's Costs Cited in Company's Results</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp. reported Tuesday its
second-quarter earnings improved despite an an after-tax charge of
$50 million, or $1.20 per share, associated with the SSN 688-class
attack submarine at the company's Electric Boat Division.
   The defense contractor reported earnings of $58.4 million, or
$1.39 per share, on sales of $2.5 billion during the second quarter.
For the second quarter of 1988, the company earned $46.7 million, or
$1.11 per share, on sales of $2.4 billion.
   The results for the second quarter of 1988 reflected an after-tax
charge of $33 million, or 79 cents per share, associated with the
same attack submarine program.
   For the first half of 1989, General Dynamics earned $133.8
million, or $3.20 per share, on sales of $4.9 billion compared a
profit of $132.4 million, or $3.15 per share, on sales of $4.9
billion for the same period in 1988.
   The company's backlog was reported to have reached a record high,
including a funded backlog of $17.9 billion and total backlog of
$28.8 billion representing approximately three years in sales. At
the same time in 1988, the backlogs were listed at $16.7 billion
funded and $23.8 billion total
   ``We have been advising since 1987 that the outlook for the SSN
688-class attack submarine program at Electric Boat has been
uncertain,'' said Stanley C. Pace, chairman and chief executive
officer.
   Pace said General Dynamics has stopped recognizing Electric Boat
earnings and that additional charges will be recognized in the
future. Continuing shortages of qualified New England-area workers
and productivity that has been lower than anticipated resulted in
the rescheduling of work and the extension of Electric Boat delivery
rates, Pace said.
   Cited by Pace for improved performance during the second quarter
were the land systems and general aviation segments of the company.
   The company achieved higher profitability rate on its M1 tank
program through advanced manufacturing techniques and cost
containments, Pace said, and the Cessna Aircraft unit achieved a
substantial increase in its Citation business jets sales.
</TEXT>
