<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PhillyExchange 1stLd-Writethru f0277 07-18 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philly Exchange, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0277,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Stock Exchange Confirms Merger Talks With AMEX, Two
Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The rule ...,' to CORRECT year to 1990 stead
1989.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Stock Exchange and two other
major U.S. exchanges separately are discussing merging with the
Philadelphia Stock Exchange, the country's oldest securities market,
the Philadelphia exchange president said Tuesday.
   The talks come amid concerns by members of the Philadelphia
exchange that a new Securities and Exchange Commission rule dealing
with equity options will put the Philadelphia market at a
competitive disadvantage, Nicholas Giordano said Tuesday.
   The rule, which will be phased in beginning Jan. 21, 1990, will
prohibit exchanges from holding exclusive rights to deal in
particular options.
   The Philadelphia exchange now handles about 13 percent of the
nation's options trading. An option is a right to buy or sell a
block of stock at a certain price within a stipulated time.
   The Philadelphia exchange has been approached numerous times
about mergers in the past, Giordano said. The talks with the
American Exchange and the two other, unidentified exchanges grew
serious after the SEC rule change, he said.
   ``While our discussions with all three markets have been
substantive, the difficulties and complexities of affecting such a
merger are great and we must be realistic about the likelihood of
successful merger discussions,'' Giordano said.
   ``We are proceeding on the assumption that the Philadelphia Stock
Exchange will be independent for at least another 200 years,'' he
said of the market founded in 1790.
   Giordano said determining whether a merger can be arranged would
take months.
   ``They are attracted primarily to our currency options and stock
options marketplace, but they are also attracted to our equity
floor,'' Giordano said.
   The Philadelphia exchange Tuesday also announced a 29 percent
increase in stock trading volume and a 24 percent increase in equity
options traded in the first six months of the year, compared with
the same period last year.
   The Philadelphia exchange and the American Exchange have been
bickering for months over Philadelphia's claim that the Amex copied
its idea for a new security, Cash Index Participations. The CIP,
which is tied to the Standard and Poors Index of 500 stocks, allows
investors to speculate on the trend of the stock market.
   Shortly after the Philadelphia exchange submitted its proposal to
the SEC, the American Exchange submitted a similar proposal. Since
the SEC approved trading of the participations earlier this year,
Philadelphia exchange officials have made sharply worded public
statements about the similarities of the Amex's Equity Index
Participations.
   On Tuesday, Giordano said the argument consisted of ``normal
business differences'' by Giordano.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-18-89 2259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TRW     07-18 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-TRW,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>TWR Reports Slight Drop in Second-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TRW Inc. reported Tuesday that its
second-quarter profit dropped 2 percent on flat sales.
   The high-technology company said its net income decreased to $70
million, or $1.12 a share on a fully diluted basis, from $71
million, or $1.15 a share, in the second quarter of 1988. Sales for
the quarter totaled $1.84 billion, compared with $1.82 billion for
the same period last year.
   However, the company said, the second-quarter operating profit of
its continuing businesses rose by 2 percent. TRW said the decline in
net earnings was caused by higher interest expenses resulting from
the company's Chilton Corp. and Talley air bag acquisitions.
   TRW provides technological products and services mainly for the
space, defense and automotive industries and for information systems
markets.
   For the first half, TRW earned $139 million, or $2.24 a share, on
revenue of $3.63 billion, compared with a profit of $137 million, or
2.22 a share, on revenue of $3.62 billion in the same period of
1988, the company reported.
   ``We continue to make sound progress in all our businesses,''
said Chairman Joseph T. Gorman.
   ``The information systems business has improved its performance
significantly, the space and defense segment again reported higher
earnings despite lower sales in a difficult market, and the occupant
restraints business continues its impressive growth,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
